@node "Manual.Install" "2 - Installation"

@{i}@{b}Chapter 2 - Installing Zeus for the first time@{ub}@{ui}


@{b}2.0.1 Zeus requirements@{ub}

Zeus requires:

 - Any Amiga computer with Kickstart 2.04 installed.
 - A hard drive with 5 megabytes free.
 - Two megabytes of RAM or more.

 - ARexx must be installed.


@{b}2.0.2 Extracting the Zeus disks@{ub}

Zeus is supplied on three distribution disks, and a third-party utility supplement disk. If you have obtained these disks via. an electronic medium they will be archived using the DMS packer. To install Zeus from these files, you must get a copy of DMS (available on the AmiNet), and extract each Zeus file onto four seperate floppy disks.

This can be acheived with the following commands:

@rem <PRE>
 <Insert Disk 1 in df0:>
 1> dms write Z1.DMS to df0:

 <Insert Disk 2 in df0:>
 2> dms write Z2.DMS to df0:

 <Insert Disk 3 in df0:>
 3> dms write Z3.DMS to df0:

 <Insert Disk 4 in df0:>
 4> dms write Z4.dms to df0:
@rem </PRE>


@{b}2.0.3 Installing the Zeus disks@{ub}

Once you have the three Zeus distribution disks unpacked, you can begin to install Zeus. Installation is performed using the standard Commodore Installer program.

 - Insert Zeus Distribution Disk 1 into any drive.
 - On the Workbench screen, doubleclick on the ZDIST icon.
 - Double click on the "Install" icon.
 - Follow the installation instructions.
 - When you are prompted to select a directory to install Zeus into,    select a partition with the required disk space, and select "Make new    Drawer". Call this new drawer "Zeus". Select "Proceed".
 - Follow the installation instructions.

If all went well, the following lines will have been added to your "S:User-Startup" file, which is executed upon bootup.

@rem <PRE>
Assign Zeus:      <Zeus-Directory>
Assign RIPICONS:  Zeus:RIP/Icons
Assign RIPFONTS:  Zeus:RIP/Fonts
Assign Logs:      Zeus:Logs
Assign Doors:     <Door-Path>
Assign Libs:      Zeus:Libs ADD
Assign Devs:      Zeus:Devs ADD
SetEnv FileEditor c:ED %s
@rem </PRE>

Where <Zeus-Directory> is the directory you chose to install Zeus into. The <Door-Path> is the directory you chose in the Installer to store the doors, which Doors: will be assigned to. After installation is complete, please reboot your machine.



@{b}2.0.4 Libraries@{ub}

Zeus libraries are not stored in LIBS:. This is because there are quite a few of them, and some door emulation libraries may conflict with other programs.The line "Assign Libs: Zeus:Libs ADD" will cause the search path for system libraries to be widened to both the Libs: directory and the Zeus:Libs/ Directory.

In addition to the libraries provided with the Zeus Distribution disks, you must have the following libraries installed in LIBS:

@rem <PRE>
        rexxsyslib.library (Kickstart 2.04 or above)
        reqtools.library   (V37 or above)
@rem </PRE>

For file transfers on the BBS the following libraries are required and supplied
on Zeus Distribution Disk #4 as "LIBS.LHA"

@rem <PRE>
        xprymodem.library
        xprzmodem.library
        xprzedzap.library
@rem </PRE>

To share the serial port with other applications at the same time you also need
the owndevunit.library, also suplied in this archive. See Section
Owndevunit.library.


@{b}2.0.5 FileEditor ENV Variable@{ub}

The ENV variable, "FileEditor" stores the command line to execute your local editor. This defaults to the Commodore "ED" program, stored in the C: directory as provided with all versions of Workbench.

The "%s" is expanded to the name of the file to be edited. Other possible values for "ENV:FileEditor" can be set by using the following lines instead of the one written in S:User-Startup:

@{u}CygnusEd@{uu}

@rem <PRE>
 SetEnv FileEditor "CED -keepio %s"
@rem </PRE>

@{u}GoldEd@{uu}

@rem <PRE>
 SetEnv FileEditor "Ed %s Y"
@rem </PRE>

@{u}Amiga Default ED@{uu}

@rem <PRE>
 SetEnv FileEditor "Ed %s"
@rem </PRE>


@{b}2.1.0 After installation@{ub}

After the successful installation of Zeus, a few points must be checked before booting it up for the first time.


@{b}2.1.1 ARexx?@{ub}

Is ARexx installed? If it is not, the following lines must be added to your "S:User-Startup" startup file.

@rem <PRE>
Sys:System/RexxMast >NIL:
Sys:RexxC/rxlib rexxsupport.library 0 -30 0
@rem </PRE>

It is also possible to start ARexx by placing the RexxMast program in the WBStartUp directory, but this method involves RexxMast opening a window to tell you it has started.


@{b}2.2.0 First time usage@{ub}

After your installation has completed, you must first reset your Amiga before Zeus may be loaded.

Once your Amiga has rebooted, open up the Zeus window from the Workbench, which will be installed in the path you selected in the Installer program.

@{"Zeus Drawer Picture" Link "ZeusDrawer.GIF/main"}

The following drawers will be shown:

@rem <PRE>
 Bin/           - CLI based binary utilities for Zeus
 Config/        - Configuration files for Zeus and utilities)
 Conversion/    - Conversion utilities from other BBS programs
 Developers/    - Developer information for Zeus
 Docs/          - Documentation files
 Doors/         - Online door programs
 Logs/          - Text log files
 FileTypes/     - Icon files for your own projects
@rem </PRE>

@{"File Types Picture" Link "FileTypes.gif/main"}

@rem <PRE>
 Libs/          - Zeus System Library files
 Prefs/         - GUI Configuration utilities
@rem </PRE>

@{"Preferences Picture" Link "Preferences.gif/main"}

@rem <PRE>
 Rexx/          - Offline ARexx scripts
 Shortcuts/     - Batch scripts for simple BBS operations
 Scripts/       - Online BBS menus and scripts
 Text/          - Online BBS texts
 Utils/         - GUI utilities for Zeus
@rem </PRE>

@{"Utilities Picture" Link "Utilities.gif/main"}



Also, the Zeus executable and a "ClickForColors" icon will be shown. The latter will reset your main Workbench screen to use "MagicWB" colours, the colour scheme of the Zeus icons.

The main Zeus icon will boot up the BBS in full, but before we click on this, enter the Prefs drawer and double-click on "StartUp".

@{"StartUp Picture" Link "StartUp.gif/main"}

This is the program startup GUI. It defines all the programs that will be started after the main Zeus program has been loaded up. Each program in the list can be assigned a "Stack size", "Priority" and "Delay".  Delay specifies the time to wait in seconds before executing the @{i}next@{ui} program in the list.

The list will contain:

@rem <PRE>
@{b}Zeus:Bin/FileControl@{ub}
Zeus File Server- controls all aspects of the internal file database
@{b}Zeus:Bin/MsgControl@{ub}
Zeus Message Server- controls all aspects of the internal message database.
@{b}Zeus:Bin/BBSLine 0 Local.zeus@{ub}
Sets up the local line task.
@{b}Zeus:Bin/BBSLine 1 Remote.zeus@{ub}
Sets up the first serial line task (defaults to serial.device).
@{b}Zeus:Bin/BBSLine 2@{ub}
task (defaults to znm.device).
@{b}Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI 0 JUMPY ICONIFY@{ub}
Loads up the local line watcher in iconify mode.
@{b}Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI 1 JUMPY ICONIFY@{ub}
Loads up the first remote line watcher in iconify mode.
@{b};Zeus:Bin/Watchers/RIP 0 NTSC@{ub}
Not loaded. RIP server (local)
@{b};Zeus:Bin/Watchers/RIP 1 NTSC@{ub}
Not loaded. RIP server (remote)
@{b};Zeus:Bin/Connector 1 ShowGui@{ub}
Not loaded. Remote line answerer.
@{b}Zeus:Utils/ChatStatus@{ub}
ChatStatus icon on Control screen.
@{b}Zeus:Utils/Control@{ub}
Zeus Control Window/Screen.
@{b}Zeus:Utils/Voyeur@{ub}
Lines Watcher
@{b}Zeus:Bin/ZeusDock@{ub}
Program launcher.
@rem </PRE>


Let's add a new entry:

Click Add. Change the (New) string to

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Bin/PostMan USER "<Your User Name>" EXECUTE "rx Zeus:Rexx/Logon.rexx"
@rem </PRE>

Hit Up once to move this entry before the ZeusDock program.

Hit Save. Then press Quit.

This has set up the PostMan utility, which creates an icon on your Control window informing you whether you have mail waiting.


@{b}2.2.1 PostMan@{ub}

The previous steps set up the PostMan utility, which creates an icon on your Control window informing you whether you have mail waiting or not. Clicking on the icon will run the line specified with the "EXECUTE" argument. You can also specify a command to execute when new mail is received using the "MAILCMD" argument.

@{"No Mail Waiting" Link "PostManNoMail.gif/main"}

No Mail Waiting

@{"1 Message Waiting" Link "PostManMail.gif/main"}

1 Message Waiting

@rem <PRE>
Usage: PostMan EXECUTE/A,USER,MAILCMD,XPOS/N,YPOS/N

   EXECUTE  - Command to execute upon clicking on icon

   USER     - Name of user to check

   MAILCMD  - Command to execute upon receiving mail

   XPOS     - X Position to place icon

   YPOS     - Y Position to place icon
@rem </PRE>

PostMan running a sample when new mail is received:

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Bin/PostMan EXECUTE "rx Zeus:Rexx/Logon/Logon.rexx" USER "Nick Loman" MAILCMD "Doors:ChatPage/DSound Doors:ChatPage/8svx/Alert"
@rem </PRE>

PostMan running it's window at X=500, Y=200:

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Bin/PostMan EXECUTE "rx Zeus:Rexx/Logon/Logon.rexx" USER "Nick Loman" XPOS 500 YPOS 200
@rem </PRE>



@{b}2.2.2 Loading Zeus@{ub}

Now, let's load up Zeus. Zeus can be loaded from the CLI or from the Workbench. We recommend you add the following entry at the bottom of your startup-sequence:

@rem <PRE>
run <>NIL: Zeus:Zeus
@rem </PRE>

Running Zeus from the CLI is recommended as the pathing information from the CLI is maintained, and any programs launched from within the BBS will respect these settings.

Double click on the Workbench icon.

@{"Zeus Loading" Link "ZeusLoading.gif/main"}

The "ZEUS" loading screen will immediately appear, and show the progress of the startup. Zeus first reads the configuration, loads the user files and then starts executing the programs in the Program startup list.



@{b}2.2.3 The Control Window@{ub}

Soon after Zeus reports that it is RUNNING PROGS, the Control Window should pop up on a public screen named "ZEUS". This Control Window allows you to access the preference and utility programs from the menus, as well as your own configuration programs. The Control Window may open on your WB screen by turning off the Control->Prefs->Open Screen option from the menu.

@{"Control Window" Link "ControlWindow.gif/main"}

The Control Window also operates as an icon dock. Zeus programs can be iconified onto this window, and the built-in Dock program, named ZeusDock, may place icons on this window. These icons may launch programs when pressed (see section Dock).

The Line Watcher, named Voyeur, will also be loaded. This program monitors the status of all the lines on the BBS and provides shortcuts to several regularly used node functions.



@{b}2.2.4 Line Watcher@{ub}

The Line Watcher is called Zeus:Utils/Voyeur. It is loaded as part as the default program startup and creates a window which looks like this:

@{"Voyeur Window" Link "Voyeur.gif/main"}

The larger window contains a list of lines, providing information about the callers currently connected to the BBS. The smaller window has a dock of six icons which perform important line functions. You may select a line by clicking in the list box or typing the line number on the keyboard. Once a line is selected, clicking on one of the icons will perform a function on that line.

Icon Description
 Keboard Shortcut
 Description

Jack in the Box
 P
 Pops up the current watcher for this line so you can see exactly what the user is doing. If there is no watcher currently loaded then it will execute the script: Zeus:Rexx/Voyeur/PopUpWatcher.rexx. You should edit this script if you wish to use an alternative to the standard ANSI watcher, named Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI.

Boot
 B
 Kicks the user off the BBS.

Confused User
 D
 Executes Zeus:Rexx/Voyeur/UserDetails.rexx with the current line and public screen Voyeur is open on as arguments. This script comes preconfigured to load the Utils/UserDetails program.

Surgeon
 E
 Executes Zeus:Rexx/Voyeur/EditUser.rexx with the current line number and public screen Voyeur is open on as arguments. This script comes preconfigured to load the Utils/UserEditor program.

Radio Pylons
 S
 Pops up a requester to send a "node message" to the user online. Messages will be sent verbatim and will not say who they have been sent from.

Iconify
 I
 Iconifies Voyeur on the Control window.


The Control Window may also be run on a screen and configured in many different
ways:

@{"Default Zeus Control Window configuration" Link "VoyeurDefault.gif/main"}
Default Zeus Control Window configuration

@{"A reconfigured Control Window" Link "VoyeurRecon.gif/main"}
A reconfigured Control Window





@{b}2.2.5 The MenuEditor@{ub}

NB: The MenuEditor is not for creating menus for the BBS proper, but merely for configuring the SysOp's interface. For more information on configuring the BBS see the chapter on Editing your BBS.

The menu bars of the Control window/screen may be configured to launch your favourite programs or Zeus utilities. In addition, other Zeus programs also allow you to edit their menus.

 These programs are:

@rem <PRE>
  Zeus:Utils/Control
  Zeus:Utils/FileEditor
  Zeus:Utils/UserEditor
  Zeus:Bin/ZMailer
  Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI and Zeus:Bin/Watchers/RIP
@rem </PRE>

Each program stores it's menu file in a different location within Zeus:Config/.Shortcuts to let you edit these menus have been created on the Control Screen, under the menu Miscellaneous->Config:

Program
 Menu Option
 File in Zeus:Config/

Control Screen
 Miscellaneous->Config->Control Menus
 Control/Menus.Dat

FileEditor
 Miscellaneous->Config->FileEditor Menus
 File/FileEditorMenus.Dat

UserEditor
 Miscellaneous->Config->UserEditor Menus
 Zeus/UserEditorMenus.Dat

Mailer
 Miscellaneous->Config->Mailer Menus
 Msg/MailerMenu.Dat

Watchers
 Miscellaneous->Config->Watcher Menus
 Watchers/Menus.Dat

@{"Menu Editor Picture" Link "MenuEditor.gif/main"}

Let's add a new entry to shut down Zeus.

Hit the "Add" button under the "Menus" listview. Change (New) to "Misc".
Hit "Add" under the "Items" menu. Change (New) to "Quit Zeus". Change the following entries:

@rem <PRE>
   CommKey: X
      Type: Execute
     Stack: 4096
Executable: Newshell FROM Zeus:Shortcuts/BBS/ShutdownZeus
@rem </PRE>

Hit the close window. Select "Save". Now, from the "Control" menu on the Control Screen, select "Reload Menus" from the Prefs item.

Your "Quit Zeus" entry will now be listed on the menus.



@{b}2.2.6 Configuring the Control Window@{ub}

The Control Window can also serve as a public screen. From the "Prefs" item in the "Control", select "Open Screen". This will open up a public screen, using the same properties as your Workbench screen.

All prefs and utility programs will open on the Zeus Screen, which is named "ZEUS" if it is active.

Various other properties of the public screen can be controlled from the "Prefs" menu:

Screen Mode
 - Brings up a screen-mode requester. All aspects of the screen mode can be selected from here.

Font
 - Brings up a font requester. The default screen font can be selected here.

Palette
 - Brings up a palette requester.

Backdrop
 - Brings up a file requester- you can choose an IFF file to be tiled on the Control Window. We have supplied a nice marble pattern in "Zeus:Config/MarbleDark" from the MagicWB archive.

Default Screen
 - if this is on all windows will open on this screen instead of the Workbench screen.

Pop Screen
 - Zeus screen will be brought to the front whenever a wndow opens on it.

Borderless
 - Removes the window border providing a more attractive look.

The "Save Config" option will write out these configuration changes to
disk.



@{b}2.2.7 Dock@{ub}

The Dock utility adds icons to the Control Screen which, upon clicking will execute a program. The Dock is configured using the Prefs/DockCfgprogram:

@{"Dock Picture" Link "Dock.gif/main"}

Each item in the listview represents an icon stored within the directory Zeus:Config/Icons. All icon files end in .info but this extension is omitted in the list. For each item, various items of data may be configured.

Execute
 The command to execute upon clicking the icon.

Text
 - The text to display underneath the icon. This field may be left blank.

Stack
 - The stack size to start the program with. This setting should be 4096 by default or higher if need be.

Priority
 - The priority to start the program at. Programs requiring little CPU time should be placed at a high priority (0-10), programs which drain the CPU resources should be placed at a lower priority (-10-0).

Floating
 - The icon will be made "floating", and will find the next suitable place to locate itself. Setting this flag on will ghost the X Co and Y Co gadgets.

X Co
 - Specifies the X position on the Control screen to place the icon.

Y Co
 - Specifies the Y position on the Control screen to place the icon.

Find Pos
 - Pops up a bar which you may drag around the screen to find the exact position you wish the icon to be placed. The "X Co" and "Y Co" gadgets will be updated as it is moved.



@{b}2.2.8 Logging into the BBS@{ub}

Logging into the BBS can be acheived locally from "Line 0". Clicking on the "Line 0" icon from the Control Window will deiconify the watcher. Each ANSI/RIP watcher is a public screen, named "ANSI.<Line Number>" or "RIP.<Line Number>"

The Zeus ANSI Watcher will display various information on the screen:

@{"Watcher Picture" Link "Watcher.gif/main"}

This screen is displayed when Zeus is waiting for a call. Hitting [RETURN] will login to the system.

Before you logon, you may wish to do some configuration. The ANSI watcher will clone the screen resolution from the Workbench screen, but this is often not the best resolution in order to get optimum speed and memory efficiency. To change the resolution hit the "Screen Mode" button. We recommend the following settings:

@rem <PRE>
 European Standard:

 PAL:High Res   Width: 640 Height: 256
 Colors:16
@rem </PRE>

or

@rem <PRE>
 North America Standard:

 NTSC:High Res  Width: 640 Height: 200
 Colors:16
@rem </PRE>

These screen resolutions are more suited to BBS usage. However, any screen resolution may be used with Zeus.

You will probably also wish to select an IBM-style font. Press "Font" and from the list select IBM.font size 8. Any size font may be used with Zeus, but 8-point fonts are the most common.

The Palette is set up for standard Workbench colours on the last callers screen, and the 16-colour ANSI palette while watching. Hitting the "Palette" button will allow you to change both these palettes.

Press the "Keys" button. This will bring up the macro window. From here, you can configure Function Key commands to be executed and text to be pushed onto the input in the current BBS session. Currently set up keys are:

F1
 - Start Chat with User

F7
 - Edit Personal Attributes of User

F8
 - Edit Account of User

F9
 - Edit File Accesses for User

F10
 - Edit Message Accesses for User

S1
 - (Shift-F1) Log user in LOGS Logger.<LineNumber>

S10
 - Boot user offline.



Let's add a new entry. In the F2 string gadget type your name followed by "\r\n". Then change the "Exec" cyclebox next to the string gadget to "Text". This will make this entry a text output string.

Close the window using the close window gadget.

Again, selecting "Save Config" from the Watcher menu will cause the configuration changes to be output to disk.

Hit [RETURN] to log in.

You will be prompted for your name. Hit F2 to output your name. Login as a new user, and complete the new user registration.


@{b}2.2.9 Upgrading the online user's account@{ub}

Hit F8 to load the UserEditor and bring up your account window. Click the "Sel" button next the the "Access" gadget to bring up a list of access levels. Double click on "255- SysOp" entry to give yourself SysOp access on the BBS.Close this window, and select "Save User" from the main menu. Hit Quit to close the UserEditor, or ESC.

NB: The ESC key works as a substitute for the close window gadget on all GUI preference and utility programs supplied with Zeus.


@{b}2.2.10 Using the BBS@{ub}

You are now logged into the example BBS setup supplied with Zeus. Wander around the BBS and try the menu items. To logout use the 'L' option from the main menu. This setup is an actual BBS located in Sweden. You will probably want your BBS to look different to this. We will discuss configuring the look and feel of your BBS in the chapter @{i}Editing your BBS@{ui}.


You have now completed the initial installation of your BBS, and created an account for yourself. You'll now need to configure some "Lines" for your BBS which is the topic of Chapter 3:

@rem <PRE>
 @{" 3 - Lines                             " Link "Lines" }
@rem </PRE>


@endnode


@node "Manual.Lines" "3 - Lines"

@{i}@{b}Chapter 3 - Configuring Your Lines@{ub}@{ui}


@{b}3.0.1 What are lines?@{ub}

Each Zeus Bulletin Board can have one line or more. A line is some kind of interface to provide access to the Bulletin Board. Zeus supports an unlimited number of lines, which are configured in the utility "Prefs/LineEditor", or the "Lines" option from the Prefs menu on the Control Screen. There are two types of line in Zeus:

@rem <PRE>
           ź Local      This type of line has no networking capability and is accessible from the local computer only. It is traditionally used for the SysOp to logon to the Bulletin Board, although more than one local line may be defined.
           ź Serial     A serial line is used for attaching modems, nullmodem cables, ISDN adapters, telnet devices and other similar AmigaDOS shared devices to your Zeus Bulletin Board System.
@rem </PRE>


@{b}3.1.1 Setting up lines@{ub}

Lines are set up with the program "Prefs/Lines", or the Lines menu option from the Zeus Control Window.

@{"Lines Editor Picture" Link "LinesEditor.gif/main"}

The main Lines screen shows all the configured lines on the system. There are also six buttons:

@{u}Add@{uu}
 - This button will add a new line entry. A new window will open to prompt for the configuration details of the line.

@{u}Delete@{uu}
 - This button will delete a line entry. All the line numbers numbers below the new deletion will be shifted up by one.

@{u}Up@{uu}
 - Change the position of the currently selected line by one, upwards.

@{u}Down@{uu}
 - Change the position of the currently selected line by one, downwards.

@{u}Save@{uu}
 - Save the Line configuration out to disk. The Lines configuration is stored in the file "Zeus:Config/Zeus/Lines.Dat"

@{u}Quit@{uu}
 - Close the Line Editor.

In addition, double clicking on a serial line will allow you to edit its configuration settings.

Now double click on Line 1.

@{"Lines Configuration Picture" Link "LinesConfig.gif/main"}


A new window will appear with various gadgets and buttons. This window allows you to customise the line.

@{u}Device@{uu}
 - The Amiga serial device to drive this line. Example entries would be "serial.device", which is used for the Amiga's internal serial port or "znm.device" - Zeus' own nullmodem device.

@{u}Unit@{uu}
 - The Unit number of the device. This setting is used with multi-serial cards like the ASDG dual serial card. The first serial device would be 0, the second 1 and so on. The internal serial port is Unit 0.

@{u}Buffer@{uu}
 - The internal buffer Zeus should use. Higher values use more memory, but allow higher throughput on transfers. Faster modems should have higher settings. Values from 2048-65536 are commonplace, in multiples of 2k.

@{u}Baud@{uu}
 - Speed to run the serial port at. This should be a reflection of the speed of your modems total throughput potential. The Amiga serial device should not be run at speeds greater than 19,200 baud without an accelerator.

                Example Entries:

@rem <PRE>
                Modem                   Baud

                1200                    1200
                2400 (v22b)             2400
                2400 + MNP 5            4800
                2400 + V42b             9600
                9600 + V42b             19200
                14400 + V42b            38400
                16800 + V42b            38400
                28800 + V42b            57600
@rem </PRE>

@{u}Break@{uu}
 - Break delay. This value need not be changed in most cases, a value of 250000 should suffice.

@{u}Use DSR@{uu}
 - This option should be selected if you are using hardware handshaking (RTS/CTS) with a 7WIRE cable.

@{u}Run Script@{uu}
 - This option when off will stop Zeus loading up the line script for the device. This should be set to ON in almost every case.

@{u}Check Carrier@{uu}
 - This option specifies that Zeus should detect whether the user is online, and quit the session if they drop carrier. It should be set ON in most cases.

@{u}Rad Boogie@{uu}
 - Disable some checking to boost serial performance with the Amiga internal serial.device. This option may help improve modem performance at faster baud rates.

@{u}Float Baud@{uu}
 - Ticking this box will cause the baudrate to "float" according to the login baud rate.For example, a line locked at 9600 receiving a caller at 2400 would be shift the baud ratedown to 2400 for the duration of the call. This switch is generally only useful for old modems.

@{u}Data Len@{uu}
 - Length of data bits. Bulletin boards typically use a value of 8 bits per data byte.

@{u}Handshake@{uu}
   RTS/CTS -  most efficient handshaking for modems using a locked baud rate. Requires a 7-wire serial cable.
   XON/XOFF - less efficient handshaking, works with a standard 2, 3, 7 serial cable (RECV, SEND, GROUND).

@{u}Stop Bits@{uu}
 - Number of bits to use to indicate the end of a data byte. Bulletin Boards almost always use a value of 1.

@{u}Parity NONE/EVEN/ODD@{uu}
 - Bulletin boards typically use a setting of NONE.


@{b}3.1.2 Device Compatibility@{ub}

There are various serial device replacements available which help speed up
serial throughput on the internal serial device. They are all available on the
AmiNet in the comm/misc directory.

Name
 Archive
 Notes

8n1.device
 8n1.lha
 Contains bugs which may cause crashing when using ZMailer. There are newer versions, such are New_8n1.lha, which should work okay normally but possibly still crash when using @{i}OwnDevUnit.library@{ui} (see later).

BaudBandit.Device
 baudbandit1.4b.lha
 Speeds up throughput considerably.

artser.device
 ArtSer37_6.lha
 Speeds up throughput.


@{b}3.1.3 Line Access@{ub}

Each line on the BBS may have a separate list of access restrictions. Hitting the Access button from the Device Line window will bring up the following window.

@{"Lines Access Picture" Link "LinesAccess.gif/main"}

This window allows you to specify ranges of times to restrict access to the line. There are several types of line restrictions:

@{u}Restriction@{uu}

This flag prevents logons. "Normal" allows all logons through, but baud and access restrictions are still applicable, "No Logons" prevents logons or mail sessions connecting, useful if you are doing important configuration. "Mail Only" only allows mail calls, useful for Zone Mail Hour (ZMH) periods. "No Answer" will prevent the phone from being answered when used in conjunction with ZMailer or Connector.

@{u}Min Baud@{uu}
 The minimum baudrate that users may use during this period. Useful for restricting users with slower speed modems during busy periods.

@{u}Max Baud@{uu}
 The maximum baudrate that users may use during this period.

@{u}Min Access@{uu}
 The minimum access level a user must have to logon  This is useful for
restricting access to a line during subscriber-only hours for example.

@{u}Max Access@{uu}
 The maximum access level a user must have to logon.


@{b}3.1.4 Strings@{ub}

This window allows you to specify the commands used by Zeus:Utils/Connector and Zeus:Bin/ZMailer when talking to the modem. These strings accept Modem Control Codes.

@{i}Modem Control Codes@{ui}

@{"Lines Codes Picture" Link "LinesCodes.gif/main"}

These boxes may contain the following characters which translate to serial operations:

@rem <PRE>
 Character        Serial Operation

    ~             short delay
    ^             drop DTR, wait a while, raise DTR again
    |             send a carriage return character
    \             escape character, send next character as is
@rem </PRE>

@{u}Init Cmd@{uu}
 Initialisation command for the modem.

@{u}Answer Cmd@{uu}
 Command to send when a RING result is returned from the modem.

@{u}Hangup Cmd@{uu}
 Command to hangup the modem. Usually contains '^' character.

@{u}Ring@{uu}
 String returned by the modem when a ring is detected.

@{u}Connect@{uu}
 String returned by the modem when a successful data connect has been established.

@{u}No Connect@{uu}
 String returned by the modem when an answer command has been sent and no connection has been established.



@{b}3.1.5 Connecting the lines@{ub}

An interface must be provided to sit in between Zeus and the serial device. In the case of a modem device, the phone must be answered and then the BBS must be started. If you are running a front-door mailer for FidoNet connections, Zeus must be "spawned" if it is a human caller.

Each line may be started in a different way. There are four programs which handle the task of answering the phone in different circumstances:

@{u}The Connector@{uu}
 A simple phone answerer. Does not provide any FidoNet facilities.

@{u}Zeus Mailer@{uu}
 Zeus' own "front-door" mailer. Similar to the TrapDoor program.

@{u}NetStart@{uu}
 A BBS spawner to allow telnet connections to the BBS.

@{u}MailerStart@{uu}
 A BBS spawner run by third-party "front-door" mailer programs such as TrapDoor.


@{b}3.2.1 The Connector@{ub}

The Connector is a utility that simply answers the phone when it detects a "RING" command and loads the BBS upon the modem reporting a "CONNECT". The strings Connector sends to the modem are defined in Prefs/LineEditor, in the "Strings" window for the applicable line number.


@rem <PRE>
Usage: Utils/Connector LINE/A,SHOWGUI/S,QUERY/S,NOOPEN/S,OWNDEV/S,WXPOS/N,WYPOS/N.
@rem </PRE>

Connector must be called with the "LINE" argument, which indicates which line the program should open on. The Connector will open in "iconified" mode by default, and will bring up an icon on the Control Window. This icon is stored in Zeus:Config/Icons/Connector.info.

@{u}LINE@{uu}
 - Line number to start the Connector on.

@{u}SHOWGUI@{uu}
 - Show the Control GUI (defaults to iconified)

@{u}QUERY@{uu}
 - Report current modem status on GUI.

@{u}NOOPEN@{uu}
 - Do not open the serial device.

@{u}OWNDEV@{uu}
 - Obtain "exclusive access" on the serial device. Connector defaults to obtaining "shared" access, meaning other serial programs can open the device at the same time.

@{u}WXPOS@{uu}
 - Pixel co-ordinates of the top (X) corner to open the Connector GUIon.

@{u}WYPOS@{uu}
 - Pixel co-ordinates of the top (Y) corner to open the Connector GUI on.


Connector can also be configured via Workbench by its ToolTypes:

Workbench icon tooltypes:

@{u}LINE=<Line Number>@{uu}

@{u}SHOWGUI@{uu}

@{u}QUERY@{uu}

@{u}NOOPEN@{uu}

@{u}OWNDEV@{uu}

@{u}WXPOS=<number>@{uu}

@{u}WYPOS=<number>@{uu}

@{u}XPOS=<number>@{uu}

@{u}YPOS=<number>@{uu}

These are used in the same way as the shell arguments.


@{i}The Connector Window@{ui}

@{"Connector Picture" Link "Connector.gif/main"}

The Connector GUI has the following gadgets and areas:

@{u}Init@{uu}
 Sends the initialisation command to the modem.

@{u}HangUp@{uu}
 Boots the user offline.

@{u}Iconify@{uu}
 Iconifies the window.

@{u}Quit@{uu}
 Quits The Connector.

@{u}Query@{uu}
 Turns query mode on and off. When query mode is activated, The Connector will
ask the serial device what it's status is every second. The `lights' at the
bottom of the window will be updated to show what is going on. The letters stand
for:

@{u} CD@{uu}
  Carrier detect.

@{u} DSR@{uu}
  Data set ready.

@{u} DTR@{uu}
  Data terminal ready.

@{u} RTS@{uu}
  Whether RTS is high or low.

@{u} CTS@{uu}
  Whether CTS is high or low.

@{u} Status@{uu}
  The current status of the Connector.

@{u}Text display@{uu}
 The most recent text sent/received from the modem while in command mode (BBS
I/O does not go through this window).


@{i}Connector ARexx@{ui}

The Connector supports the following ARexx commands, which can be addressed at it's port "CONNECTOR.<line>", where <line> is the line number Connector is running on.

INIT
 Equivalent to pressing the Init button. Returns 0 if successful or 10 if there is a caller online.

HANGUP
 Equivalent to pressing the HangUp button. Returns 0 if successful or 10 if there is no caller online.

QUIT
 Quits the Connector

QUERY <ON|OFF>
 Turns Query mode on or off.

SMODEM <Command>
 Sends the given command to the modem. Returns 0 if successful or 10 if there is a caller online.

ONLINE
 Returns the state of the line. 0 if there is no caller or 5 if there is.

OPENDEV
 Opens the serial device. Returns 0 if successful, 5 is device was already open or 10 if device failed to open.

CLOSEDEV
 Closes the serial device. Returns 0 if successful or 5 if device was already closed.


@rem <PRE>
/* An example script to hang up the line and quit the Connector */

Options Results

Address 'CONNECTOR.1' /* Talk to the Connector */

HANGUP

QUIT
@rem </PRE>


Other example scripts using these ARexx commands can be found in the Zeus:Rexx/Connector/ drawer, and a fuller guide to the connectors ARexx features can be found in the Zeus ARexx Reference Guide, under @{"Connector" link Connector}.


@{b}3.3.0 ZMailer@{ub}

ZMailer is Zeus' own "front-door". As well as answering the phone when a call is received, it detects whether the user is a human caller or a FidoNet mail session. If it is a user then the BBS is spawned, otherwise the FidoNet mail session is initiated, the remote system performs a handshake and mail files are transferred.

When a user calls a Zeus BBS with the Mailer online they encounter a screen like this:


@rem <pre>
Welcome to Zeus BBS

You have connnected on Line 1

Press ESCAPE twice to enter the BBS
@rem </pre>


A mailer dialling in will jump straight to the handshake, after it has detected
a special string.

@{i}Configuring ZMailer to receive calls@{ui}

Configuration of ZMailer is done through the Prefs/Mailer utility, accessable from the Connection->Config->Mailer item from the Control menu. Upon loading the following window will be displayed:

@{"ZMailer Preferences Picture" Link "ZMailerPrefs.gif/main"}

On the right of the window a list of all the serial devices configured in the Line Configuration Editor will be displayed. For each serial device you have configured there is a separate Mailer configuration. To configure the mailer configuration for line 1 (in this example "serial.device", 0) you would select the "001: serial.device, 0" entry in the listview.

The five buttons in the top portion of the window control different aspects of ZMailer's behaviour:

@{u}Addresses@{uu}
 Defines the primary FidoNet addresses and AKA addresses used for this line.

@{u}Modem@{uu}
 Defines values relating to the modem configuration for dialing out and receiving calls as well as timeout values and delays.

@{u}Strings@{uu}
 Defines strings relating to the information the user receives when the Mailer is in certain states (Mail only etc.), and defines strings sent to the modem when answering and dialling out.

@{u}Session@{uu}
 Defines FidoNet protocols to be used when dialling out and receiving calls from
other FidoNet sites. Also allows various miscellaneous options to be set.

@{u}External@{uu}
 Defines programs to be run after specific events occur (fax calls, file requests etc.)


@{i}Addresses@{ui}

@{"ZMailer Addresses Picture" Link "ZMailerAddresses.gif/main"}

This window allows you to enter your FidoNet addresses and AKA's (@{i}"Also Known As"@{ui}). You should enter your primary address first (the entry at the top of the window) and all your other addresses below. Mail waiting for a particular address will only be received if your address is specified in this window.


@{i}Modem@{ui}

@{"ZMailer Modem Picture" Link "ZMailerModem.gif/main"}

@{u}Dial Timeout@{uu}
 The number of seconds to wait before aborting an unconnected outgoing call.

@{u}Drop BBS Secs@{uu}
 The number of seconds to wait for a handshake before spawning the BBS.

@{u}Min Baud@{uu}
 If an incoming connect is lower than this baud rate, ZMailer will hang-up.

@{u}Reset Secs@{uu}
 Send the initialisation string to the modem every `x' seconds.

@{u}Serial Buff@{uu}
 ZMailer's internal serial buffer. If you get serial buffer overflows try increasing this value. Usually at least 16384 bytes.

@{u}Char Delay@{uu}
 Some modems can't handle data being sent to them at full speed while in command mode. This field sets the time (in 1/50th of a second) ZMailer should wait after sending each character. Set to 0 if your modem can handle it!

@{u}Redial Delay@{uu}
 Number of seconds delay between redials to busy systems.

@{u}Redial Retries@{uu}
 Number of redials to attempt on an outgoing call.

@{u}Ring Count@{uu}
 The number of rings to answer after when receiving a call.

@{u}Ringing Count@{uu}
 Number of rings before dropping carrier on an outgoing call.

@{u}EMSI Buff@{uu}
 Size of buffer for storing EMSI information. Default to 4096.

@{u}Long Delay@{uu}
 Sets the time (in 1/50th of a second) ZMailer will delay on a tilde (~) character when sending a modem command. Also sets the time that DTR will be droped for a carat (^) character. Set to 25.


@{i}Strings@{ui}

@{"ZMailer Strings Picture" Link "ZMailerStrings.gif/main"}

The strings in the bottom half of this window may contain Modem Control Codes (see Section Modem Control Codes).

@{u}Banner@{uu}
 A line of text always displayed to the user when they connect. The `|' character is replaced by a newline.  If the first character of this text is a `<', then a textfile is displayed, e.g. putting `@{i}<Zeus:Text/Banner.txt@{ui}' would display @{i}Zeus:Text/Banner.txt@{ui} on connect.

@{u}BBS Message@{uu}
 Another line of text giving instructions of how to login to the BBS. The `<' character may be used to specify a text file.

@{u}Mail Only@{uu}
 A line of text to display when the BBS is in "mail only" mode, as set by the Prefs/LineEditor utility. The `<' character may be used to specify a text file.

@{u}BBS Chars@{uu}
 Upto twenty characters which may be used as an alternative to the ESCAPE key to enter the BBS. This option is useful for user's with terminals which do not support the ESCAPE key. A `.' is the usual setting.

@{u}Pre Dial@{uu}
 The string to send to the modem before the phone number to dial. This is usually the AT command to dial out (ATDT).

@{u}Fax Connect@{uu}
 The string returned by the modem when a FAX connect has been recognised. Specifying `FAX' would be a possible value if your modem returned `CONNET FAX'.

@{u}Voice Connect@{uu}
 The string returned by the modem when a VOICE connect has been recognised.

@{u}Post Dial@{uu}
 A string to output after the phone number to dial. This is usually a | character indicating to send a newline. The format of dialling out is `Pre Dial', followed by the phone number, followed by `Post Dial'.

@{u}Data Connect@{uu}
 If your modem returns a string to let you know it is receiving a data call rather than a FAX or VOICE one, enter that string here (usually "DATA")

@{u}Data Online@{uu}
 If ZMailer receives the string defined in Data Connect, it will send this command to return the modem to online mode. Usually "ATO|".


@{i}Session@{ui}

The Session Window allows you to control the configuration used by ZMailer when connecting with other systems and transferring mail.

@{"ZMailer Session Picture" Link "ZMailerSession.gif/main"}

@{u}Allow Refusing@{uu}
 Allow remote systems to refuse mail you are offering them. ZMailer systems dialling out can acheive this using the Forbid and Keep options.

@{u}Beep on Connect@{uu}
 Makes a call to the Intuition DisplayBeep() function upon receving a connect to flash the screen and/or make a beeping sound.

@{u}Auto UnIconify@{uu}
 Uniconifies the ZMailer window automatically upon connection.

@{u}Use Call List@{uu}
 The record of a remote system polling for mail is stored in the "Last Callers list", and can be read by Last Call utilities and on the Watcher front-end screen.

@{u}Use Line-x.Log@{uu}
 Write out logging information to the line log rather than a dedicated ZMailer log.

@{u}Log Caller ID@{uu}
 Any caller ID information reported by the modem will be stored in the log.

@{u}Accounting@{uu}
 Enable traplist accounting procedures. See the traplist documentation for more details on how accounting works in the NODELIST.LHA file stored on Zeus Disk #4.

@{u}Use Watcher Scrn.@{uu}
 Pop up the ZMailer window on the applicable watcher screen for this line, rather than the Control screen/window.

@{u}Forbid@{uu}
 Select what type of mail/files you do not want to be sent. In an EMSI handshake ZMailer will ask the remote system not to send:

    NONE: (default)
    XMAIL: Compressed mail and file attaches
    FREQ: File requests
    ALL: Both of the above

@{u}Keep@{uu}
 This flag disallows the sending of files and mail to another system dialling.

    ALL: Do not send any files out.
    XMAIL:Do not send out compressed mail and file attaches.
    NONE: Send all files out. (default)

@{u}PickUp@{uu}
 Selects which addresses to receive for when dialling out.

    ALL: Pick up mail and files for all addresses. (default)
    PRIMARY: Pick up mail and files for the primary address only.
    NONE: Don't pick up any mail or files.

@{u}After Sesn@{uu}
 Determines when the After Session string as defined in "Strings" should be called:

    ALWAYS: After every call (BBS or mailer) (default)
    MAILER: After a mailer call only.
    SUCCESS: After a successful mailer call only.
    GOT DATA: After a successful mailer call where data was received.
    NEVER: Never call After Session.

@{u}Handshaking Boxes@{uu}
 Determines which handshaking options ZMailer should offer when dialling out or receiving calls. Defaults to all handshaking options available. These flags should only be changed when you are having difficulties connecting to other mailers.

@{u}Protocol Boxes@{uu}
 Determines which protocol options ZMailer should offer when sending and receiving files.Large buffer Hydra protocols are not recommended unless using extremely fast modems (i.e. ISDN).


@{i}Externals@{ui}

The Externals window allows you to configure "External" programs to be run when special events occur.

@{"ZMailer Externals Picture" Link "ZMailerExternals.gif/main"}

All strings in this configuration window may contain special "control codes" used by ZMailer. These codes are the same as TrapDoor and GMS for the sake of compatability:

@{"ZMailer Codes" link "ZMailerCodes"}


@{u}After Session@{uu}
 A command to be run after a connection. See the "After Sesn." Configuration tag in the Session section for more information about when this command is run. To run ZMP in import mode on the Zeus screen the following command will work:

@rem <pre>
run <>CON:////ZMP/SCREENZEUS Zeus:Bin/ZMP Import
@rem </pre>

@{u}File Request@{uu}
 A command to execute when a file request is received. See the chapter on File Requests for example configuration lines.

@{u}Fax Handler@{uu}
 A command to execute when a fax request is received. ZMailer determines a fax request from the settings in the Modem window. To spawn GPfax from Zeus you can use the following command:

@rem <pre>
Execute Zeus:Config/ReceiveFax
@rem </pre>

Where ReceiveFax is the following script:

@rem <pre>
Wait 1
rx "address rexx_gpfax openserial"
rx "address rexx_gpfax fconreceive"
Wait 3
rx "address rexx_gpfax initmodem"
Wait 3
rx "address rexx_gpfax closeserial"
Zeus:Bin/PostMsg FROM FaxReceiver TO "SysOp" AREA 1 TEXTFILE Zeus:Text/GotFax SUBJECT "You have received  a FAX!!"
Wait 5
@rem </pre>

@{u}Voice Handler@{uu}
 A command to execute when a voice request is received. ZMailer determines a voice request from the settings in the Modem window.

@{u}File Requests@{uu}

ZMailer supports File Requests (FREQs). File Requests allow FidoNet sites to download files directly from your file base without logging into the BBS manually. To enable FidoNet sites to access your file base you must set up a FREQServer. There are many of these available for the Amiga, but only one which supports the Zeus file catalogue directly. This is called GoldFREQ and can be found on the aminet as comm/fido/GFreq29Zeus.lha.

How FREQs work

Requesting a file from another FidoNet system is simple. Create a file called "z.n.n.p.REQ" in your outbound directory, where z.n.n.p is the zone, node, net and point of the destination system separated by periods. Inside this file you should put the names of the files to request line by line, e.g.

@rem </pre>
1> type OUTBOUND:2.442.107.0.REQ
FILES
GFreq28Zeus.LZX
@rem </pre>

This file would request the complete list list of 2:442/107.0 along with the latest version of GFreq. "FILES" is known as a magic name due to the name you request is not necessarily the filename you will receive, eg. FILES may be substituted for Filelist.lha in the remote file base.

To send this file request off you must load ZMailer and tell it to poll 2:442/107.0. After the session handshake has been completed the files you have requested will be returned (during the same session), usually along with a netmail informing you of the results of your request.

@{i}What does the FREQserver do?@{ui}

A FREQserver is the program that reads in these .REQ files after they have been received by the mailer and creates the list of files to be sent back which the mailer reads and duly sends. The FREQserver also decides whether the system calling has access to the files requested (files can be limited in a similar way to the file sub-system ratio system in some FREQservers).

Setting up a FREQserver is different for each package, but we have provided some common lines to place in your "File Request" Configuration string in the ZMailer configuration.

@{i}GoldFreq@{ui}

@rem <pre>
GoldFreq %i %o %O %B "%S" %n c=<path/cfgfile>
@rem </pre>

@{i}Cloning ZMailer Line Configurations@{ui}

You do not have to reconfigure each serial line if the settings are essentially the same. You can Copy a line configuration definition by selecting the line to copy, pressing the Copy button and selecting the line to copy to the configuration to.



@{b}3.4.0 MailerStart@{ub}

MailerStart is used by external "front-door" mailers such as Trapdoor, GMS and JamMail to spawn a Zeus BBS session when they detect a "human" call, as opposed to a mail call.

MailerStart is stored in Zeus:Bin/System/

CLI Usage:

@rem <pre>
MailerStart LINE/N/A,LOCKEDBAUD/N/A,REALBAUD/N/A,STRING/F
@rem </pre>

Information for configuring MailerStart with your preferred mailer is supplied here. Please refer to your mailer instructions for more information on setting it up to receive FidoNet calls.

@{i}JamMail@{ui}

Configure JamMail for a standard BBS, and use this BBS launch command:

1. Command: zeus
2. TextFile: ""
3. Execute: Zeus:Bin/System/MailerStart $(line) $(baudlocked) $(baud)
4. PostBBS:
5. Check Error: Enabled

@{i}GMS@{ui}

Where <x> is the line number to install.

Add the following to GMS:Config/Mailer.<x>/MailerSettings

@rem <pre>
BBSMode=Spawn
BBSCommand="Zeus:Bin/System/MailerStart <x> %b %B"
BBSCommandStack=20000
@rem </pre>

@{i}TrapDoor@{ui}

Where <x> is the line number to install..

Add the following to your trapdoor configuration, typically stored in "MAIL:Trapdoor.cfg".

@rem <PRE>
BBSCOMMAND "Zeus:Bin/System/MailerStart <x> %b %B %C"

BBSINOUT ""

BBSMODE SPAWN
@rem </PRE>



@{b}3.5.0 NetStart@{ub}

NetStart allows you, in conjuction with AmiTCP or Miami and TnServ, to have people logon to your Zeus system by telnet.

1) Install AmiTCP & TnServ
2) Edit your TnServ banner to something like:

@rem <PRE>
---

Welcome to this great BBS!

To access BBS, login as 'bbs' with password of 'bbs'

---
@rem </PRE>

3) Add the following line to your TnServ passwd file:

@rem <PRE>
---

bbs,bbs,1,1,(User),RAM:,Zeus:Bin/System/NetStart

---
@rem </PRE>

4) Decide how many telnet lines you wish to support and with the 'Prefs/Lines' program, generate that many serial lines. You do not need to worry about any of the settings but you must set the Device: to fakesr.device.NetStart takes care of the rest of the magic.



@{b}3.6.0 The Owndevunit.library@{ub}

The owndevunit.library is a shared library which keeps track of which program is currently using the serial device. It allows many programs to use the serial.device at the same time, and "lock" it when it needs to use it exclusively. Enabling owndevunit mode on Zeus utilities such as The Connector and ZMailer will allow you to run other utilities that support the owndevunit.library at the same time.

NB: This does not mean that more than one program can @{i}use@{ui} the serial device at the same time, concurrent programs reading and writing to the serial port would cause unwanted problems!



@{b}3.6.1 Testing your BBS using a local terminal@{ub}

When running communications software there is often a need to test it out over a serial link to see if the data from one program is being properly processed by another. As a Zeus BBS operator you may want to see how your ANSI/RIP screens look on the terminal packages your users will be using to call your system, or to check your scripts concerned with IEMSI, file transfers, or other serial only data processes.

The usual way to create a serial link is to have two machines connected by modems, running over a telephone line, or a null-modem cable which plugs into the serial ports of both machines. Not only are these both hardware solutions, which can be a pain in itself to setup, they also require two machines which not everyone posesses.

The Zeus "Null-Modem" device is a software solution to this problem which combines the features of both systems while only using ONE machine. As an added feature, you can also run multiple null-modem connections at the same time!

Each unit of the device acts as if it has a modem attached which can respond to AT commands, answer calls and dial out, although you may wonder where the unit would connect to! The trick is that units are paired together so when a program opens unit zero, it will connect with the program using unit one, unit two will connect with unit three and so on as this illustration shows.

@{"ZNM Diagram" Link "ZNMDiagram.gif/main"}

Any communication programs that allows you to select which serial device to use should work. Just change them to use znm.device and select a free unit pair.

The 'modem' part of the device only responds to a few AT commands:

@{u}AT@{uu}
 Returns 'OK'

@{u}ATA@{uu}
 Answer an incoming call.  If the other unit is not trying to dial, NO CARRIER will be returned.

@{u}ATD<Number>@{uu}
 Tells the modem to try and connect with the other unit. If the other unit does not answer, BUSY will be returned. Anything can be supplied for <Number>.






@{b}3.6.2 Adding a Line@{ub}

Once you have created the line definition and decided on a method of connecting
the line, you must add an entry to the Startup configuration to start up a new
BBSLine task automatically. To start up a new remote line #3 with Zeus the
following line should be added to your startup configuration:

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Bin/BBSLine 3 Remote.zeus
@rem </PRE>

@endnode


@node ZMailerCodes "ZMailer Codes"

These codes can be used in all of ZMailer's "External Commands" settings.  They are the same as TrapDoor, Gotcha and GMSs for the sake of compatibility.

 %a - aka of the remote system (one aka per %a)
 %A - all akas of the remote system (space separated)
 %b - baudrate (between computer and modem)
 %B - baudrate (of the actual connection)
 %C - full CONNECT message from the modem
 %s - serial device name
 %u - serial device unit number
 %f - serial device flags
 %r - unique random number (timestamp)
 %l - name of logfile
 %Z - zone number of the other system
 %N - net number of the other system
 %F - fido node number of the other system
 %P - point number of the other system
 %n - complete FidoNet address of the other system
 %S - name of Sysop of other system
 %R - name of the ARexx port of this Mailer
 %p - name of the public screen
 %I - name of inbound directory
 %O - name of outbound directory
 %d - direction 1 if inbound call, -1 if outbound call
 %% - %

 For the FREQUEST keyword, the following sequences are allowed in addition to the above:

 %i - name of the .REQ file (input file)
 %o - name of the .RLO file (output file)

@endnode

@node "Manual.General" "4 - General Configuration"

@{i}@{b}Chaper 4 - General Configuration@{ub}@{ui}



@{b}4.0.1 General@{ub}

Before attempting to set the General System Configuration of your BBS, you should first have read and complete Chapters 2 and 3, installation of the program and setting up the Lines.



@{b}4.1.1 System@{ub}

The System Configuration is for the configuration of the BBS itself, and the main settings that Zeus uses for paths and buffers.



@{b}4.1.2 Main System@{ub}

The Zeus:Prefs/System program loads up the System Configuration. This is accessable through the menu entry BBS->Config->System. There are nine buttons on the main screen:

@{"System Picture" Link "System.gif/main"}

@{u}System Settings@{uu}
 This button calls up the "System Variables" window, where general information about the BBS and various buffer sizes are configured.

@{u}Languages@{uu}
 This button calls up the "Languages" window, allowing you to add new languages to the BBS.

@{u}Paths@{uu}
 This button calls up the "Paths" window, where you may edit the locations Zeus searches for files in.

@{u}Menu Sets@{uu}
 The "Menu Sets" window. Allows you to maintain the different menu sets you might support on your BBS.

@{u}Ban List@{uu}
 The "Ban List" windows allows you to ban certain names, or name patterns from logging onto your BBS.

@{u}Computers@{uu}
 The "Computer List" window is a simple configuration to allow user's to enter what computer they are using when they logon.

@{u}Update@{uu}
 This button updates any configurations you have changed on the BBS. It performs the same function as "UpdateConfigs SYS", see Section Update Configs.



@{b}4.2.1 System Variables@{ub}

@{"System Variables Picture" Link "SystemVars.gif/main"}

@{u}User index read buffer@{uu}
 This variable specifies the size of the internal buffer used to speed up user data access. The larger the number, the faster the seek time. The box next to it shows the approximate memory usage.

@{u}Carrier check interval@{uu}
 This variable specifies how often in seconds Zeus checks to see if the user has dropped carrier.

@{u}Inactivity timeout@{uu}
 The number of seconds user's may lay "idle" on the BBS before they are logged off automatically.

@{u}Last calls in list@{uu}
 The size of the "last calls list". Higher values use more memory.

@{u}Count local calls@{uu}
 Should calls on "local nodes" be counted in the system graphs and statistics?

@{u}Buffered text files@{uu}
 The number of text files to be buffered. Zeus has a text buffering system to increase the speed of the BBS. However, for every text file buffered the size of the text file is used up in memory. If you are using text buffering it is wise to limit the number of files to buffer to around 20 to save memory.

 NB: When using buffered text files, if you edit a text file and it is currently stored in the buffer, the text file will not be updated on the BBS. You must either reload Zeus for the change to be noticable for a user, or run the command @{i}"Bin/TextPreload FLUSH"@{ui}.

@{u}Max text file size@{uu}
 Files above this size will not be buffered. Useful for saving memory when displaying text files of a large size which are not BBS menus using the ARexx Display command.

@{i}@{u}IEMSI Information@{uu}@{ui}

This information is sent during an IEMSI handshake with a user to identify the system. It is also used by some scripts on the BBS to get the System Name and SysOp Name.

@{u}System Name@{uu}
 The name of your BBS, e.g. "Bob's BBS".

@{u}System Location@{uu}
 The location of your BBS, e.g. "Brighton, Sussex".

@{u}SysOp Name@{uu}
 Your name.



@{b}4.3.1 Languages@{ub}

@{"System Languages Picture" Link "SystemLang.gif/main"}

Languages take the form of files of text stored in the Zeus:Config/Language directory. They are named "<language>.lang", where <language> is the name of the language.Every language file must contain the following tags for the use of Zeus: All other prompts in the default language file supplied with Zeus, Zeus:Config/Langauge/default.lang are configured within the scripts using the Prompt ARexx command and are not part of Zeus itself.

@{u}WAITRETURN@{uu}
 Sent when the return key must be pressed to continue.

@{u}WAITRETURNANIM@{uu}
 Sent when the return key must be pressed to continue, and the user has Animated Prompts on.  A speed can be specified for the animation using "\\s<speed>".  That is, 'double backslash' (since backslash is also a special character) 's' and the speed as a number.  20 gives approximately the normal speed, and a smaller number means less delay and faster animation.  Speed can be set at any point in the animation, any number of times, so you can have variable speed animation.  Please also see the @{"Read" link "Read"} ARexx command information.

@{u}YN@{uu}
 Sent when the user must press "Yes or No" to continue.

@{u}YNC@{uu}
 Sent when the user must press "Yes, No or Continuous" to continue.

@{u}DEFYES@{uu}
 Sent when the user must press "Yes or No" and the default option is Yes (i.e. pressing return would return yes).

@{u}DEFNO@{uu}
 Sent when the user must press "Yes or No" and the default option is Yes (i.e. pressing return would return no).

@{u}YESTXT@{uu}
 Text sent when the user selects "Yes" at one of the above prompts.

@{u}NOTXT@{uu}
 Text sent when the user selects "No" at one of the above prompts.

@{u}CONTTXT@{uu}
 Text sent when the user selects "Continuous" at one of the above prompts.

@{u}YESCHAR@{uu}
 One letter abbreviation for `Yes'

@{u}NOCHAR@{uu}
 One letter abbreviation for `No.

@{u}CONTCHAR@{uu}
 One letter abbreviation for `Continuous'

@{u}PRIVCHAR@{uu}
 The "secret" letter output character-for-character for each letter of a password.

@{u}YES@{uu}
 Displayed when boolean control codes are positive.

@{u}NO@{uu}
 Displayed when boolean control codes are negative.

@{u}ON@{uu}
 Displayed when active control codes are "on".

@{u}OFF@{uu}
 Displayed when active control codes are "off".

@{u}STRING@{uu}
 The default formatting for a control code of type "string". Should be set at %s in almost all cases.

@{u}NUMBER@{uu}
 The default formatting for a control code of type "number". Should be set at %ld (long number) in almost all cases.

@{u}TIME@{uu}
 The default formatting for a time string. Takes standard date codes, as documented in Chapter x.xx, Control Codes.  *****************************************************

@{u}MORE@{uu}
 Text displayed when asking if user wishes to request more text.

@{u}MONTH1, MONTH2, ... MONTH12@{uu}
 The full name of months from January to December (1-12).

@{u}GENDER0@{uu}
 The string for Gender 0 (unknown)

@{u}GENDER1@{uu}
 The string for Gender 1 (male)

@{u}GENDER2@{uu}
 The string for Gender 2 (female)

@{u}FIRSTFILE@{uu}
 The header displayed when showing files in an area.

@{u}FILEFORMAT@{uu}
 The format of each file in a short file list. Control Codes %1400-%1420 may be used here.

@{u}SCANAREAS@{uu}
 The string to output when scanning through areas. The area name currently being scanned can be retrieved from the %s control code.

@{u}STDINDENT@{uu}
 The number of characters to indent the file description on consecutive lines.

@{u}STDFILENAME@{uu}
 The number of characters used by the file name in the FileFormat tag.



@{b}4.4.1 Banned Users@{ub}

@{"System Banned Picture" Link "SystemBanned.gif/main"}

This window allows you to ban users from your BBS. All AmigaDOS wildcards may be used in the string gadget.

Banning all user's with "SEX" in their name:

Click the ADD button. Enter "#?SEX#?" in the string gadget.

Verifying your ban works:

Enter "MR. SEXY" in the Test Name box. Click on "Test Current" and "Test String". Press Test. If you have entered the string correctly it will report that the User is banned.

Testing no user's are already banned with your banlist settings:

Click "Test All" and "Test Users". Press the "Test" button. Results are displayed in the text gadget.



@{b}4.5.1 Computer Types@{ub}

@{"System Computers Picture" Link "SystemComp.gif/main"}

The Computer Types window allows you to specify a list of computer types that the user's may select when choosing what computer they own. The purpose of this list is simply to match the index number against a description for use when displaying user data.



@{b}4.6.1 Bulletins@{ub}

@{"System Bulletins Picture" Link "SystemBul.gif/main"}

The Bulletins editor allows you to edit a list of text files that the user may read. New Bulletins created since the user's last call are marked as such when they logon, and bulletins which have been changed can be detected using the BM utility. Each Bulletin may have various fields attributed to it:

@{u}Name@{uu}
 The title the user will see when listing the online bulletins. When you add a new bulletin using the file requester the filename will be added into this field - this may be changed.

@{u}Filename@{uu}
 The name of the file to display.

@{u}Key@{uu}
 A short name describing the bulletin of 9 characters or less. This "Key" is used for referencing the bulletin easily through ARexx, without needing to know the sequence of it in the list.

@{u}Created@{uu}
 The date the file was created. Pressing the adjacent "disk" icon will retrieve the date the file itself was last modified.

@{u}Expires@{uu}
 The date this bulletin will "expire". When a bulletin has expired it will be removed from the list. Clearing this string will ensure that the bulletin will never expire.

@{u}Low Access@{uu}
 Lowest access required to access this bulletin.

@{u}High Access@{uu}
 Highest access required to access this bulletin.

@{u}Renumber@{uu}
 Renumbers the bulletins in case one has expired.

@{u}Update@{uu}
 Updates the online configuration. Equivalent to Zeus:Bin/BM UPDATE

@{u}Save@{uu}
 Saves the configuration out to disk.



@{b}4.6.2 BulletinManager@{ub}

@rem <PRE>
Usage: BM
ADD/S,REM=REMOVE/S,UPDATE/S,RNUM=RENUMBER/S,LIST/S,NUM=NUMBER/K/N,NAME/K,
KEY/K,FNAME/K,EXPIRE/S,XWEEKS/K/N,XDAYS/K/N,XMINS/K/N,ALL/S

   ADD      - Add a new bulletin
   REMOVE   - Remove bulletin
   UPDATE   - Set creation date from date stamp
   RENUMBER - Renumber all bulletins from 1 -> n
   LIST     - List all bulletins
   NUMBER   - Specify a single bulletin to
              REMOVE/UPDATE
   NAME     - Specify bulletin name for ADD
   KEY      - Specify bulletin KEY for
              ADD/REMOVE/UPDATE
   FNAME    - Specify bulletin filename for ADD
   EXPIRE   - Specify that bulletin does expire for
              ADD
   XWEEKS   - Number of weeks   till bulletin expires
              for ADD
   XDAYS    - Number of days     ""     ""       ""
               "" ""
   XMINS    - Number of minutes  ""     ""       ""
               "" ""
   ALL      - Affect all bulletins during UPDATE
@rem </PRE>

BulletinManager is a utility typically run from within the
Zeus:Scripts/Remote.zeus script to update the bulletins after each call.This is
necessary in case you have bulletins which are affected by the user's actions,
for example the hi-score files created by some doors. The following line updates
your bulletins from within an ARexx script:

@rem <PRE>
address command 'Zeus:Bin/BM UPDATE ALL'
@rem </PRE>

To add a new bulletin expiring in 2 weeks and 1 day:

@rem <PRE>
1> Zeus:Bin/BM ADD NAME "Global War HiScores" KEY "GWHIGH" FNAME    <-'
"Doors:GW2/HiScores.txt" EXPIRE XWEEKS 2 XDAYS 1
@rem </PRE>

To remove this bulletin:

@rem <PRE>
1> Zeus:Bin/BM REMOVE KEY "GWHIGH"
@rem </PRE>



@{b}4.7.0 Updating Configurations@{ub}

Changing configurations manually by editing configuration files using a text editor, or simply copying new ones across will not be taken as the "on-line" configuration automatically. You can "update" your configuration files in two ways:

  Shut down and reload Zeus

  Use Bin/UpdateConfigs



@{b}4.7.1 UpdateConfigs@{ub}

Run UpdateConfigs with one or more arguments to specify the configuration files you wish to update.

@rem <PRE>
Usage: UpdateConfigs
MA=MSGAREAS/S,FA=FILEAREAS/S,GM=GENERALMSG/S,ED=EDITORS/S,
XPR=XFERPROTOS/S,SIGS/S,GC=GLOBALCMDS/S,MS=MENUSETS/S,
LG=LANGUAGES/S,BAN=BANNEDUSERS/S,COMP=COMPUTERS/S,PATHS/S,
SYS=SYSTEMVARS/S,TM=TEMPLATES/S,GF=GENERALFILE/S,ARC=ARCHIVERS/S,
ALL/S

MA=MSGAREAS            Message areas
FA=FILEAREAS           File areas
GM=GENERALMSG          General message settings
ED=EDITORS             Editors
XPR=XFERPROTOS         File transfer protocols
SIGS                   Special interest groups
GC=GLOBALCMDS          Global commands
MS=MENUSETS            Menu sets
LG=LANGUAGES           Language definitions
BAN=BANNEDUSERS        Banned users
COMP=COMPUTERS         Computers
PATHS                  Paths
SYS=SYSTEMVARS         System settings
TM=TEMPLATES           Access Templates
ARC=ARCHIVERS          Archivers
GF=GENERALFILE         General file settings

ALL                    ALL of the above
@rem </PRE>



@{b}4.7.2 Updating configs while users are online@{ub}

You should not update the language configuration while users are using the BBS.Doing so may cause problems when using certain functions, for safety wait until they have logged off.



@{b}4.8.0 System Graphs@{ub}

Zeus:Utils/TimeStat shows how much time your system has been alive per hour (white graph) and how much of this time had users online (blue graph). The two averages (horizontal bars with numbers to the left) show the number of minutes your board has been alive (minutes per hour) and the number of minutes per hour users have been online. The text box at the bottom shows total active time and total online time.

@{"System Graphs 1 Picture" Link "SystemGraphs1.gif/main"}

@{"System Graphs 2 Picture" Link "SystemGraphs2.gif/main"}

Both stat progs are font sensitive, scalable and can update in real time! The usage is:

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Utils/CallerStat X/N,Y/N,W/N,H/N,FONT/K,FS/N,SCREEN/K,UPDATE/N

Zeus:Utils/TimeStat X/N,Y/N,W/N,H/N,FONT/K,FS/N,SCREEN/K,UPDATE/N

   X      - X position of the window
   Y      - Y position of the window
   W      - Width of the window
   H      - Height of the window
   FONT   - Name of font to use
   FS     - Font size
   SCREEN - Name of the public screen to open on (ZEUS
            by default)
   UPDATE - The stats will be updated every X number
            of seconds.
@rem </PRE>



@{b}4.9.0 Resetting the system settings@{ub}

The file Zeus:Config/Zeus/SystemInfo.dat contains all the system call information. To reset the "number of calls" counter delete this file. The file Zeus:Config/LastCallers.dat stores the last callers data, delete this to reset the lists displayed by ANSI.


@endnode



@node "Manual.Users" "5 - Users"

@{i}@{b}Chaper 5 - Users@{ub}@{ui}



@{b}5.0.1 Users@{ub}

The majority of user editing is done through Utils/UserEditor. This may be activated from the Users->User Editor item on the Control Window, or by pressing F7-F10 in an ANSI watcher.



@{b}5.0.2 The UserEditor@{ub}

The UserEditor main screen displays a list of all the user's on the BBS. If you are searching for a particular user you may jump to the first letter of their user name by hitting that particular key.

@{"User Editor Picture" Link "UserEditor.gif/main"}

Button
 Description

@{u}Personal@{uu}
 Shows the selected user's personal settings.

@{u}Terminal@{uu}
 Shows the selected user's account and terminal settings.

@{u}Files@{uu}
 Shows the selected user's file account.

@{u}Messages@{uu}
 Shows the selected user's message account.

@{u}Iconify@{uu}
 Iconifies the window onto the Control Window.

@{u}Delete@{uu}
 Removes the selected user from the user database.

@{u}Save User@{uu}
 Save's changes to the user.

@{u}Add User@{uu}
 Add's a new user to the user database with standard flags and access.

@{u}Quit UED@{uu}
 Quits the UserEditor.


The bevel box in the top-right allows you to search through the user list using a particular filter:

Gadget
 Description

@{u}All Users@{uu}
 Shows the entire user list (default).

@{u}Access Level@{uu}
 Shows all user's with access level equal to the Input box.

@{u}Unvalidated@{uu}
 Shows all user's who have not been validated by the SysOp.

@{u}Address@{uu}
 Shows all user's who have an instance of the Input box string in their address, city or state.

@{u}Phone Numbers@{uu}
 Shows all user's who have an instance of the Input box string in their voice or data phone numbers.

@{u}Male@{uu}
 Shows all male users (ignores those with gender unknown).

@{u}Female@{uu}
 Shows all female users.

@{u}Show Name@{uu}
 Shows the user's names in the userlist.

@{u}Show Alias@{uu}
 Shows the user's aliases in the userlist.

@{u}Show Info@{uu}
 Shows some account information in the userlist.


The second bevel box controls the method in which the catalogue is searched and sorted:

@{u}Alphabetically@{uu}
 Sort alphabetically

@{u}Chronologically@{uu}
 Sort in relation to the date of their first call.

@{u}Forwards@{uu}
 Search forwards

@{u}Backwards@{uu}
 Search backwards


After selecting a user from the list you may edit and view four windows:



@{b}5.0.3 Personal Settings@{ub}

@{"User Personal Picture" Link "UserPersonal.gif/main"}

This window shows the user data related to the user's personal data. All fields on this window are self-explanatory.



@{b}5.0.4 Terminal Settings@{ub}

@{"User Terminal Picture" Link "UserTerminal.gif/main"}

The top gadget line is the most important part of the Terminal Settings window.Here you can change the access level of the user from the Template Configuration list.

This window shows the user data related to the user's terminal and account settings. The line of checkboxes on the right define the user's terminal settings. The line of gadgets on the left contain account information about the amount of time they have left, statistics and credit information. Some fields need some explanation:

@{u}Validated@{uu}
 Whether the SysOp has approved this user's application as a new user.

@{u}Log User@{uu}
 Dangerous option! Turning this flag off will stop the user's actions being logged to the line log.

@{u}No Restrict@{uu}
 The user may bypass any access or line restrictions on the node they have logged onto.

@{u}Protected@{uu}
 If this flag is on then the user will never be purged or expire.



@{b}5.0.5 File Access@{ub}

@{"User File Access Picture" Link "UserFileAccess.gif/main"}

This window shows the file areas the user has access to, along with the access flags they possess. Individual access to file areas may be granted to users using the "Pick" button, and taken away using the "Del" button. File ratio limits, download and upload statistics, the user's current SIG, file area and transfer protocol are also displayed.



@{b}5.0.6 Message Access@{ub}

@{"User Message Access Picture" Link "UserMsgAccess.gif/main"}

This window shows the message areas the user has access to, along with the access flags they possess. Again, individual message areas may be added to users using the "Pick" button, and taken away using the "Del" button. Message writing limits, current message SIG, current message area and current editor are also displayed here.



@{b}5.1.1 Utils/UserDetails@{ub}

The Zeus:Utils/UserDetails program displays a window with information about a user.

@rem <pre>
Usage: UserDetails LINE/N,USERNAME,PUBSCREEN

 LINE      - Display information about using on Line n
 USERNAME  - Name of user to display.
 PUBSCREEN - Public screen name to open window on.
@rem </pre>

@{"User Details Picture" Link "UserDetails.gif/main"}



@{b}5.2.1 Rebuilding the User database@{ub}

The Zeus:Bin/UserManager utility brings together several CLI only functions for processing Zeus' user base. It has been designed for both stand-alone and interactive use.

Functions available:

@rem <pre>
 1> UserManager REBUILD
@rem </pre>

The user file will be scanned and any users marked as deleted will befiltered out and their user directory and contents deleted. There is no way to recover deleted users after a rebuild.

@rem <pre>
 1> UserManager STRIP x [NOPROMPT]
@rem </pre>

Users who have not called for 'x' number of days will be deleted. You will be prompted before each user is deleted although this can be overidden with the NOPROMPT switch.

@rem <pre>
 1> UserManager UNDELETE [NOPROMPT]
@rem </pre>

Users who are deleted remain in the user file with their DELETED flag set until you perform a REBUILD. Using this function, you will be prompted as each deleted user is found and asked whether to restore them. By using the NOPROMPT switch, all deleted users will be restored without prompting you for confirmation.

@rem <pre>
 1> UserManager LIST pattern
@rem </pre>

All users who match the given 'pattern' (all AmigaDOS wildcards are valid) will be listed. The match is performed on the users name and alias.

@rem <pre>
 1> UserManager DELETE pattern [NOPROMPT]
@rem </pre>

All users who match the given 'pattern' (all AmigaDOS wildcards are valid) will be deleted. The match is performed on the users name and alias. You will be prompted for confirmation unless the NOPROMPT switch is used.

@rem <pre>
 1> UserManager DUPE
@rem </pre>

Checks for and deletes duplicate users. This is not really useful anymore as duplicate users should never appear. It was included to fix dupe problems during development.

@endnode


@node "Manual.Files" "Files"

@{i}@{b}Chapter 6 - File Subsystem@{ub}@{ui}

File Areas are configured using the "Prefs/FileConfig" program. Upon loading the main window will appear:

@{"File Config Picture" Link "FileConfig.gif/main"}


Four aspects of the file configuration can be controlled using this program:


@{b}6.1.0 General File Configuration@{ub}

Selecting the "General" option will bring up a new window:

@{"File General Picture" Link "FileGeneral.gif/main"}


Various options of the file subsystem can be configured with this window:


@{u}Memory Usage@{uu}

Each line on the BBS uses indexing to speed up the file list searching. You can configure the size of these indexes. The size of indexes you use should be related to the amount of memory you have installed on your Amiga.


@rem <PRE>
Setting  Memory         Indexes   Usage
~~~~~~~  ~~~~~~         ~~~~~~~   ~~~~~
LOW      1 mb.or less   32        3k per index.

MEDIUM   1-2 mb.        128       13k per index.

HIGH     >2 mb.         256       26k per index.

OTHER    You may specify your own index usage settings in the string
gadget when using the "OTHER" setting.
@rem </PRE>


@{u}File Notes@{uu}

When a file is uploaded to the BBS, the file description given to the file is added to the AmigaDOS comment field. Due to restrictions in AmigaDOS, only the first 80 characters of the file description will be added. This option should be turned off when adding files from the CD-ROM to Zeus, as file notes may not be added to read-only devices.


@{u}Maximum Marks@{uu}

The maximum number of files a user may mark on the Bulletin Board. Every file marked takes up disk space, and a user marking '#?' on the BBS could fill up your hard drive very quickly if you have a few thousand files. Plus the time that might be required to mark all files could be considerable..


@{u}Temporary Path@{uu}

The path to copy files ready to be downloaded to. This path will only be used if "Copy Files to Temp" is set on in the file area definition.


@{u}Upload Path@{uu}

The base path to upload files to. A directory will be created within this path called Upload<x>/, where <x> is the line number uploading, e.g. specifying dh2:Uploads/ as your upload path will cause files uploaded on line 1 to be sent to dh2:Uploads/Upload1/ for processing. This directory shouldn't be present in the Zeus file area configuration.


@{u}Save@{uu}

Outputs the general file configuration to disk. The name of the general file configuration is "Zeus:Config/File/General.Dat" and is in binary format.


@{u}Quit@{uu}

Leaves the general file configuration window. If you have not saved the configuration you will be prompted to.



@{b}6.2.0 File Area List@{ub}

File areas can be configured in the "Areas" window of the Prefs/FileConfig program..

@{"Files Areas Picture" Link "FileAreas.gif/main"}

This main window controls your file area list.

@{u}Add@{uu} - Add a new file area to the list. The file area list is sorted numerically and a new area will be inserted according to its number.

@{u}Edit@{uu} - Edit the file areas(s) currently marked. Single areas can be marked by double-clicking on the area you wish to edit.

@{u}Copy@{uu} - This will make duplicate copies of the currently marked file area(s).

@{u}Delete@{uu} - Remove the currently marked file area(s) from the file area list.

@{u}Number@{uu} - Renumber the currently marked file area(s). A requester will pop up allowing you to decide the base number to renumber from.

@{u}Save@{uu} - Outputs the file area list to disk.

@{u}Quit@{uu} - Leaves the area list window. If you have changed the file area configuration, a window will pop up.



@{u}6.2.1 The File Area Definition@{uu}

@{"File Area Definition Picture" Link "FileAreaDefinitions.iff/main"}


Selecting 'Add' or 'Edit' will bring up this window, allowing you to edit the attributes of each file area. Editing of the file area definitions can also be done through the Zeus ARexx port. See the commands @{"SetFileArea" link "SetFileArea"} and @{"GetFileArea" link "GetFileArea"} in the reference section of this manual.

Each field may also be accessed through control codes while a user is online.  See ControlCodes %1000 and onwards in the reference section of this manual.

@{i}Settings@{ui}


@{u}Number@{uu} - The index number of this file area. No two file areas in the file area list may have the same number, and if you attempt to enter a duplicate number a requester will popup and make you rechoose. Please note Zeus does not support the use of an area 0 anywhere on the BBS.

@{u}Name@{uu} - A descriptive name for this file area. Up to 64 characters may be used, though for two column file area lists on the BBS to be formatted correctly, a maximum of 30 is recommended.

@{u}Path@{uu} - The main path for storing files belonging to this area in. This may be any valid AmigaDOS path of up to 104 characters long. A '/' or ':' character will be appended to this path if you do not supply one. E.g., entering dh2:aminet would be replaced with dh2:aminet/

@{u}Library@{uu} - Set a File Base library for this area. This allows programmers to write libraries which allow Zeus file bases to be stored in any format - for example, an FTP library would allow files to be stored on a remote FTP site, but look to be present on your BBS. File base libraries are libraries pre-fixed with "fb" - the default library being fbzeus.library. Select a new library using the file selector icon to the right - but @{i}only@{ui} select fb#?.library's ! An incorrect one may crash File Config. If the library has a configuration window, "Opts" will show this.

@{u}Write access@{uu} - This cycle gadget allows the SysOp to allow or disallow write access to this path. CD-Rom drives for instance may not have R/W access as they are a read-only medium. This cycle gadget may have either a "R/W" or a "Read" setting.

@{u}Disk icon@{uu} - This icon will bring up a file requester allowing you to select the main path for this area easily.

@{u}Low@{uu} - The "override" minimum access level required to access this area. Template and SIG definitions take second priority to this setting. See section 8 for more informatioin on restricting access to users on the BBS.

@{u}High@{uu} - The "override" maximum access level required to access this area. A setting of 255 is common in almost every case.

@{u}Age@{uu} - The minimum age a user must be to enter this area. This setting is useful for restricting access to "over-18" file areaa.

@{u}Gender@{uu} - This cycle gadget allows you to prevent access to this file area for Male or Female members of the Bulletin Board.

@{u}U/L BPS@{uu} - This setting defines the minimum modem speed required to upload a file to this area. Typical settings are "1200" or "2400" to disallow the slower modem rates.

@{u}D/L BPS@{uu} - This setting defines the minimum modem speed required to download a file from this area. Some SysOps will only allow high-speed (over 9600 bps) users to download from their file bases.


@{i}@{u}Multiple Paths@{uu}@{ui} - If the files in this file area are stored over more than one path, for instance if you have more than one AmiNet CD and you wish to incorporate each directory on the CD into one directory on your BBS you should use the Multiple Paths option. Clicking this button will bring up a new window.

@{"MultiPaths Picture" Link "MultiPaths.gif/main"}

An unlimited number of paths may be stored in this window.

@{i}New@{ui}: - Adds a new entry to the list. This entry may be changed with the Disk Icon (will bring up a file requester to allow you to select the path), or the string gadget in which you can enter the path directly.

@{i}Del@{ui}: - Deletes the currently selected item from the list.



@{i}@{u}Flags@{uu}@{ui}


@{u}Allow Downloads@{uu} - Allow users to download files from this area. Typically set on.

@{u}Allow Uploads@{uu} - Allow users to upload files to this area.

@{u}View Files@{uu} - Allow users to view the files in this area.

@{u}Make Files Free@{uu} - All files in this area will default to "free access". This means that the user's download ratio will be unaffected when accessing files in this area.

@{u}DOS FileNames@{uu} - This setting truncates uploaded files to the MS-DOS 8.3 character file format. Zeus file bases usually allow file names of up to 30 characters which may be unacceptable to some MS-DOS machines. For instance, if this flag is set ON, the file "obnoxiouslylongfilename.zip" would be truncated to "obnoxiou.zip". Multi part files are also catered for with this algorithm, e.g. "obnoxious_part1.dms" and "obnoxious_part2.dms" would be truncated to "obnoxio1.dms" and "obnoxio2.dms".

@{u}Validation Required@{uu} - The SysOp must "hand-validate" using the Utils/FileEditor program each new upload to this area before users can download them. See section 8 for more information on allowing users to access unvalidated files.

@{u}All Files to Temp@{uu} - Files to be downloaded from this area will first be copied to the "Temporary Path" as specified in the "General File Configuration" window of Prefs/FileConfig. Use this when the storage the file is on will be too slow to send over the link the users might be using, or, if you have a multi-disk CD-ROM, this option will avoid any excessive switching between disks.



@{b}6.3.0 Transfer Protocols@{ub}

The transfer protocols callers to the BBS may use to upload and download files may be configured by selecting "Xfers" from the main FileConfig window.

@{"File Protocols Picture" Link "FileProtocol.gif/main"}

@{u}Add@{uu}  - Adds a transfer protocol to the list.

@{u}Double Click@{uu} - Edits the transfer protocol you have selected.

@{u}Remove@{uu} - Removes the transfer protocol you have selected from the list.

@{u}Up@{uu} - Moves the transfer protocol up one place in the list.

@{u}Down@{uu} - Moves the transfer protocol down one place in the list.


@{i}Information about transfer protocols@{ui}

Zeus comes supplied with two transfer protocols built-in. These are executable programs stored in "Zeus:Bin/System/" and are called "HydraXfer" (for Hydra bi-directional transfers) and "LocalXfer" (for simulating an upload from the local terminal). Other popular transfer protocols like "XModem", "YModem" and "ZModem" may be added using the "XPR" library system.

XPR libraries are standard Amiga libraries, commonly stored in LIBS:, which  handle the uploading and downloading of files. There are many different XPR protocol libraries available, but Zeus comes with the following ready configured.

The libraries themselves can be found on Zeus Disk #3, in the XPR.lha archive.

@rem <pre>
Protocol Name   Library                 Version Flags   DL Options      UL Options
XModem          xprymodem.library       2.20    -----   Z1 C1 B0 YS     Z1 C1 B0 YS
XModem-1K       xprymodem.library       2.20    -----   Z1 C1 B1 YS     Z1 C1 B1 YS
XModem-1K-G     xprymodem.library       2.20    -----   Z1 C1 B1 YG     Z1 C1 B1 YG
XModem-CRC      xprymodem.library       2.20    -----   Z1 C1 B0 YS     Z1 C1 B0 YS
YModem          xprymodem.library       2.20    BDU--   Z1 C1 B1 YB     Z1 C1 B1 YB
YModem-G        xprymodem.library       2.20    BDU--   Z1 C1 B1 YG     Z1 C1 B1 YG
ZModem          xprzmodem.library       2.0     BDU--   TN OR B16 F0 E10 AN DN SN RN    TN OR B16 F0 AN DN SN RN
@rem </pre>


@{i}Editing the file transfer protocol@{ui}

@{"File Protocol Editing Picture" Link "FileProtocolEdit.gif/main"}

@{u}Name@{uu} - The name of the file transfer protocol as seen by the user.

@{u}Library@{uu} - Library name of XPR protocol, or the executable file to be run if in "Executable" mode.

@{u}D/L Options@{uu} - XPR options to be passed to the library for downloads. Refer to your XPR library documentation for more information about these settings.

@{u}U/L Options@{uu} - XPR options to be passed to the library for downloads.

@{u}Low Access@{uu} - The minimum access level required to access this protocol.

@{u}High Access@{uu} - The maximum access level required to access this protocol.

@{u}Batch files@{uu} - This protocol supports the sending or receiving of more than one file at once.

@{u}Auto download@{uu} - Flag to indicate whether the protocol does initiates transfers automatically.

@{u}Auto upload@{uu} - Flag to indicate that the protocol supports upload without prior entering of file name(s).

@{u}Executable@{uu} - Setting this flag to on means that the Library field is a program to run, rather than the name of an XPR library.

@{u}Bi-Directional@{uu} - Indicates whether the transfer supports uploading and downloading at the same time.



@{b}6.3.0 Adding files to the BBS@{ub}

There are many ways to add files to your BBS. The easiest is using @{i}Zeus:Utils/FileEditor@{ui}. It can also be accessed from the Files->File Editor entry in the Control menu.

The File Editor

Upon loading the File Editor the following window will be displayed:

@{"File Editor Picture" Link "FileEditor.gif/main"}

The large listview on the right doubles up as an area list and a file list. When the File Editor is first loaded the list of areas will appear, clicking on one of these will bring up a list of all the files in the area.Clicking on the "..parent" entry will bring you back to the area list.

The project menu from the menubar allows you to access some important general features of the File Editor:

@{u}About@{uu}
 Displays a small about request.

@{u}Iconify@{uu}
 Iconifies the File Editor on the Control Screen.

@{u}Edit Menus@{uu}
 Fires up the Prefs/MenuEditor program to allow you to edit the menu bar of the File Editor (see Section The MenuEditor).

@{u}Reload Menus@{uu}
 Reloads the menu configuration after editing with the "Edit Menus" function.

@{u}Quit@{uu}
 Quits the File Editor.


The second bevel box on the left contains "search controls". They allow you to filter the files displayed in a certain way:

@{u}Chrono@{uu}
 This mutually exclusive button allows you to choose between the files being displayed chronologically (i.e. by date), or alphabetically.

@{u}Forward/Backward@{uu}
 This set of buttons allows you to read the list forwards or backwards, e.g. if this was set on backwards in alphabetical mode the files would be listed from Z-A.

@{u}All/Validated/Unvalidated@{uu}
 This cycle gadget allows you to view files according to whether they have been validated by the SysOp, not validated yet or not to filter at all (all mode).

Clicking on a file in the list will display it's "file catalogue data". For every file which is on the BBS the file catalogue stores information about it:

@{"File Catalogue Picture" Link "FileList.gif/main"}

@{u}Number@{uu} - A unique number identifying the file in the file base. No two files may have the same number, and the number may not be changed.

@{u}Name@{uu} - The name of the file. Zeus does not allow file names to contain more than 31 characters, and the first character of the file may not be a character other than a letter or a number.

@{u}Downloads@{uu} - The number of times this file has been downloaded on the BBS.

@{u}Size@{uu} - The size of the file in bytes.

@{u}Uploaded By@{uu} - The name of the user who uploaded this file.

@{u}Upload Date@{uu} - The date this file was uploaded in the format "dd-mmm-yy hh mm ss"

@{u}Last Dl@{uu} - The last date this file was downloaded in the format "dd-mmm-yy hh mm ss".

@{u}Offline@{uu} - Is the physical file offline? This flag is not updated automatically, use the FileManager program in "OFFLINE" mode to set all the flags.

@{u}Free@{uu} - Will this file debit the user's downloaded file counters?

@{u}Validated/ Unvalidated@{uu} - Has the SysOp decided that this file is fit to be on the BBS?


If you wish to edit any of this data you must press the Update Filebutton after you have made the appropriate changes.

Once you have selected a file area the file menu becomes available. From this menu you can manipulate the file base in various different ways:

@{u}Add File@{uu} - Allows you to add a file from your hard drive to the file base. This option firstly opens a file requester to let you select the file, the current directory will be the main path from the area definition. Then you may add a short description of upto 256 characters. To add a larger description later you should select the file and ue the Edit Description option from this menu.

@{u}Bulk Upload@{uu} - Allows you to add more than one file at the same time using a multi-select file requester, and lets you retrieve the file description either from the AmigaDOS file comment or by entering a global description for all files.

@{u}Delete File@{uu} - Deletes all the selected files in the current area. You will be prompted to decide whether you wish to delete the physical files as well as the file catalogue entries.

@{u}Move File@{uu} - Allows you to move all the selected files from one area to another, retaining their description and data. After selecting this option you should choose the area to move them by selecting another area.

@{u}Edit Description@{uu} - Loads your local editor up and lets you change the description of a file. To configure your local editor you can use the option Configure Editor from the Prefs menu within File Editor.

@{u}Bulk Validate@{uu} - Validates all unvalidated files within the area.

@{u}Unlisted Files@{uu} - Shows all the files within the search paths of this file area which have notbeen added to the file catalogue. When you are in unlisted files mode you can automatically bulk upload the entire list by selecting the Bulk Upload menu option.

@{u}Find File@{uu} - Prompts you for a name and jumps directly to that file. AmigaDOS wildcards are not used, the name must be exact.

@{u}Select All@{uu} - Marks every file in the current area.

@{u}Deselect All@{uu} - Unmarks every file in the current area.

@{u}Next Suitable Area@{uu} - Jumps to the next area with "suitable" files in. If you have selected a search mask such as Unvalidated files only then it will skip file areas with only validated files in.

@{u}Previous Suitable Area@{uu} - Jumps to the previous area with "suitable" files in.


The "Scripts" menu is entirely configurable through the MenuEditor program. It comes with three menu items pre configured:

@{u}Rebuild Catalogues@{uu} - A hotlink to the RebuildCatalogues shortcut (see Section Shortcuts)

@{u}Renumber Catalogues@{uu} - A hotlink to the RenumberCatalogues shortcut.

@{u}Extract FILE_ID.DIZ@{uu} - This script uses the FileEditor ARexx port to extract the FILE_ID.DIZ files from the archives marked and add it in as the new description. The script called is "Zeus:Rexx/FileEditor/ExtractDIZ.zeus" and uses the Archivers Configuration to extract the files fom the archive correctly.


@{b}Adding AmiNet CD's to the file catalogue@{ub}

The Bin/ZAmiNet utility has been provided to allow you to upload files from your AmiNet CD's to the BBS. In order to upload files from the "FILES.BBS" or "INDEX" description files you must have already created the areas on your BBS. This can be acheived very easily using the Zeus:Rexx/FileAreas/AddCDAreas.rexx script.

@{i}Adding Areas@{ui}

Create a list of all the areas you wish to upload from the AmiNet CD to a file,
each area separated by a new line and call it "Areas.txt", e.g.:

@rem <PRE>
1> type Areas.txt

comm/bbs
comm/dlg
comm/tcp
dev/c
dev/e
util/misc
@rem </PRE>

Run the following command, where "CD0:Aminet/" is the first part of the path
used to locate files in this directory. For example, for "comm/bbs" we would
search fo the files in "CD0:Aminet/comm/bbs". "200" is the number you wish to
start numbering the areas from. In this example "comm/bbs" will be area 200,
"comm/dlg" area 201 etc.

@rem <PRE>
1> rx Zeus:Rexx/FileAreas/AddAreas Areas.txt CD0:AmiNet/ 200
@rem </PRE>


@{i}Adding Files from the CD@{ui}

To upload the files from these areas we would run Bin/ZAmiNet in the following mode:

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Bin/ZAminet AREAS 200-205 INDEX
@rem </PRE>

This specifies that we wish to upload areas 200-205 (this is a "range" argument), and we wish to retrieve the file descriptions from the "INDEX" file located in the path, CD0:Aminet/comm/bbs/INDEX for example.

If your AmiNet CD does not have the INDEX format but instead uses the FILES.BBS format then the following line could be used:

@rem <PRE>
Zeus:Bin/ZAminet AREAS 200-205 INDEX
@rem </PRE>


@{i}Adding a large number of files.@{ui}

The Bin/FileManager utility is provided to make uploading many files to the file catalogue easy. Running in "ADDNEW ALL" will cause it to scan all the file areas searching for files that are in the area's physical path(s) but not in the file catalogue. Once it has found one it will ask you if you wish to upload it to the file catalogue, and prompt for a description. If you wish to add the files using the description provided in the AmigaDOS file comment then add the argument "FILENOTE".

To upload all new files in a <AreaNumber>:

@rem <PRE>
Bin/FileManager ADDNEW AREAS <AreaNumber>
@rem </PRE>

To upload all new files on the BBS using the FileNote description:

@rem <PRE>
Bin/FileManager ADDNEW ALL FILENOTE
@rem </PRE>


@{i}Tidying up your file base@{ui}

If you have file catalogue entries with no matching physical file due to a
partial file loss then you can delete all the file catalogue entries using the
FileManager with the "EXISTS" argument. This will search for the matching
physical file in the area's path(s) for each file catalogue entry it finds and
prompt you if a mismatch is found. You can opt to delete all files using the `a'
key when the first mismatch is found.

To delete all non-present file catalogue entries:

@rem <PRE>
Bin/FileManager EXISTS ALL
@rem </PRE>

To delete all non-present file catalogue entries in a particular area

@rem <PRE>
Bin/FileManager EXISTS AREAS <Area>
@rem </PRE>


@endnode



@node "Manual.Messages" "7 - Message Sub-system"

@{u}@{b}Chapter 7 - The Message Sub-system@{ub}@{uu}

The Message Subsystem is based around the Prefs/MsgConfig configuration utility. Here you can set up all your message areas in which local, FidoNet, Internet E-Mail and UseNet messages may be saved.

Loading up Prefs/MsgConfig (Messages->Config->Areas Configuration from the Control Window will bring up the following window:

@{"Message Config Picture" Link "MsgConfig.gif/main"}


Hitting General will bring up the:

@{b}General Message Configuration@{ub}

@{"General Message Config Picture" Link "MsgGeneral.gif/main"}

This window lets you configure the colours for the message texts. Each value may be between 0-15, 0-7 are low intensity colours, 8-15 are high intensity colours. A description of the colour will popup on the left after entering a value.


@{b}Message Area List@{ub}

@{"Message Areas Picture" Link "MsgAreas.gif/main"}

@{u}Add@{uu} - Add a new message area to the list. The message area list is sorted numerically and a new area will be inserted according to its number.

@{u}Edit@{uu} - Edit the message areas(s) currently marked. Single areas can be marked by double-clicking on the area you wish to edit.

@{u}Copy@{uu} - This will make duplicate copies of the currently marked message area(s).

@{u}Delete@{uu} - Remove the currently marked message area(s) from the file area list.

@{u}Number@{uu} - Renumber the currently marked message area(s). A requester will pop up allowing you to decide the base number to renumber from.

@{u}Save@{uu} - Outputs the file area list to disk.

@{u}Quit@{uu} - Leaves the area list window. If you have changed the message area configuration, a window will pop up.


@{b}Message Area Configuration@{ub}

@{"Message Area Picture" Link "MsgArea.gif/main"}

@{u}Number@{uu} - The unique number of this message area. `0' is not a valid entry.

@{u}Area Name@{uu} - The descriptive name of this area.

@{u}TagName@{uu} - The FidoNet tagname of this area. Not applicable for Local Bases.

@{u}Origin@{uu} - Pops up the "origin window". Not applicable for Local Bases.

@{u}Executable@{uu} - Pops up the "executable window".

@{u}Library@{uu} - Pops up the "message base library window"

@{u}Address@{uu} - Pops up the "FidoNet address window". Not applicable for Local Bases.

@{u}Low Access@{uu} - The minimum access level required to access area.

@{u}High Access@{uu} - The maximum access level required to access area.

@{u}Age@{uu} - The minimum age the user must be to access the area.

@{u}Gender@{uu} - The gender the user must be to access area.

@{u}Max Msgs@{uu} - The maximum number of messages that will be kept in the area after the trim function has been called.

@{u}Private Base@{uu} - Messages in this base are made private by default?

@{u}Hi-Ascii@{uu} - This base supports "hi-ascii" (8 bit) characters.

@{u}Quoting@{uu} - This base allows user's to "quote" messages back when writing replies.

@{u}Aliases@{uu} - This base allows the use of aliases in the From: field of messages. Not permitted in most FidoNet bases.

@{u}Del Own Msgs@{uu} - User's may delete messages they have written in this base.

@{u}Show Kludges@{uu} - Show FidoNet kludge lines when displaying messages.

@{u}Show Seen-Bys@{uu} - Show FidoNet SEEN-BY lines when displaying messages.

@{u}Show Paths@{uu} - Show FidoNet PATH lines when displaying messages.

@{u}Moderator@{uu} - Message base has moderator status.

@{u}Text Styles@{uu} - "Text styles" are displayed in this area.  These are the *bold*, /italic/ emphasis markers that may be used in FidoNet.

@{u}ANSI Base@{uu} - This flag is an ANSI base and messages are sent verbatim.

@{u}@{i}Basetype@{ui}@{uu}

@{i}Local@{ui}: Area is not networked.

@{i}Echomail@{ui}: Area is a FidoNet style area.

@{i}Netmail@{ui}: Area is a FidoNet Netmail area.

@{i}UUCP@{ui}: Area is a UseNet base.

@{i}Email@{ui}: Area is an Internet e-mail base.

@{i}Bad@{ui}: Area is for bad messages.

@{i}Origins@{ui}

@{"Message Origins Picture" Link "MsgOrigins.gif/main"}

This window allows you to add Origin lines and assign an origin line to the message area. You can also opt to assign a "random" origin line from the list to messages written. The Origin configuration is stored in Zeus:Config/Msg/Origins.Txt and is in text format - origins stored one per line.

Origins should not be greater than 65 characters long or they may cause the message length to overflow.

@{i}Text Processing@{ui}

@{"Message Processing Picture" Link "MsgProcessing.gif/main"}

This window allows you to assign "text processors" to the message area currently being edited. From here you may also add and delete text processors.


How to add a Text Processor

This can be a script or a program which is run after you write a message on the BBS, which modifies the text to be written in some way.

There are various programs which could be used. The most common ones are quote-generators or text translators which serve simply to add a touch of humour into your message bases (Gibber, Kraut, ValSpeak, Jive).

There is also potential for a spell-check program, a message text analyser, or a program in the same vain.


How to use Text Processing

The string gadget in the "Select Text Processor..." window is for the input of a
line to be executed when a message is written in the area. The code `%s' is
replaced by the name of the file containing the text.


Text Translators

Some text translators are included with Zeus, and are stored in the Zeus:Bin/ directory.

To use any of these translators, we have to use some simple scripts.

To use Jive, the Exe field should look like this:

"C:Execute Zeus:Bin/Jive.Scr %s"

This requires us to have the script, Jive.Scr in the Zeus:Bin/ directory. The included one looks like this:

@rem <pre>
.key filename
.bra {
.ket }

Copy {filename} t:TempJive
Delete {filename}
Zeus:Bin/Jive <t:TempJive >{filename}
Delete t:TempJive
@rem </pre>


@{b}Message Base Libraries@{ub}

Up until this point all the message areas we have covered have had used the mbzeus.library as their "Message Base Library". A "Message Base Library" is a collection of routines that handle message database functions at a low level, e.g. Loading, saving, deleting and scanning messages. Zeus' own Message Base Library is called mbzeus.library and is a particularly optimised and fast standard of it's own. It stores all the messages in a message area in two files, once for the header and one for the text. This provides fast access speeds and minimum disk fragmenting with high usage.

The only disadvantage with Zeus' own message format is that it is only compatible with utilities that suppport it, such as Zeus' own FidoNet mail processor ZMP.

Zeus is able to interface with other message base formats through the "Message Base Library" system. Message areas assigned to a message base library other than mbzeus.library work in exactly the same way from the point of view of the user, but are stored physically in a quite different format.

Currently there are only two message base libraries available for Zeus.

 - mbzeus.library
 - mbstarmsg.library

In general, the mbzeus.library should be sufficient for your needs. However, if you wish to use FidoNet utilities relying on the FTS-1 format message base format then you must use the "mbstarmsg.library". This is also known by the name "Plain" in the MailManager software.


@{b}mbstarmsg.library@{ub}

The mbstarmsg.library stores it's data files in quite a different way to the mbzeus.library. For every single message in an area a separate message called "x.MSG" is created in the directory "MAILDIR:<tagname>/", where x.msg is the number of the message, MAILDIR: is your mail directory (as set up in Prefs/System->Paths) and <tagname> is the Tagname of the area (as set up in the Message Configuration).

A physical set-up using mbstarmsg.library may look like this:

@rem <PRE>
 MAIL:
      StarMsg.idx
      AMIGA/
            20.msg
            21.msg
            22.msg
            23.msg
            24.msg
            25.msg
      ZEUS_BETA/
            1.msg
            2.msg
            3.msg
@rem </PRE>

The "StarMsg.idx" file keeps a record of the "Message Pointers" (see Section Message Pointers).


@{u}Using mbstarmsg.library with other Mail Processors@{uu}

If you are not using ZMP on your message bases, or will be using other utilities which will create/delete messages in your mbstarmsg.library you need to inform the mbstarmsg.library that changes have been made for them to show up on the BBS. The Bin/mbManager utility plays a part in this (see Mainting your Message Base for detailed information about mbManager).

You should set up an automatic event using a CRON to run mbManager in "UPDATE ALL" mode will detect new messages written on the BBS and change the pointers as appropriate. In addition to the message pointers being incorrect, using other mail processors will result in no Waiting Mail files being created for each user to inform them that new messages have arrived for them. To create Waiting Mail files you should run mbManager in "WAITINGMAIL ALL" mode. Areas which do not use the mbstarmsg.library will be ignored in this mode.


@{b}Maintaining your Message Base@{ub}

The most common maintenance function to be performed upon the message base is to trim it down when more messages than are desired have been imported. The Message Area Configuration tag "Max Msgs" defines the number of messages that should be kept. In order that no messages are lost when the base is not read often and more than 200 messages have been imported the base will keep expanding until you "trim" the base.

@{u}Trimming your Message Base@{uu}

The "trim" function is accessed through the Bin/mbManager program.

@rem <PRE>
Usage: mbManager
UP=UPDATE/S,RS=RESCAN/S,M=MAINT/S,T=TRIM/S,INITIALISE/S,WM=WAITINGMAIL/S,AREA/N/K,RANGE/K,ALL/S

   UPDATE      Check High and Low pointers are correct
   RESCAN      Scan area for High and Low message
               pointers

   MAINT       Perform a health check on message
               area(s)

   TRIM        Trims message area(s) till it contains
               'MaxMsgs'

   INITIALISE  Delete all messages and reset message
               pointers

   WAITINGMAIL Create waiting mail data information
               from new messages

   AREA        Specify one area to act upon

   RANGE       Specify a range of areas to act upon

   ALL         Act upon all message areas
@rem </pre>

Running the following command line will "trim" all your bases:

@rem <pre>
1> mbManager TRIM ALL
@rem </pre>

The trim command has the effect of deleting mail, and as such the user's waiting mail files may be affected. To clean-up the waiting mail files you should use the "Bin/MsgMaint" program:

@rem <pre>
Zeus Bulletin Board System (c)1992-1996 Alex May &
                                        Nick Loman

Message Subsystem datafile manager - written by Nick Loman
Usage: MsgMaint H=HIGHPTR/K/S,W=WAITMAIL/K/S,AREA/N/K,RANGE/K,ALL/K/S

   HIGHPTR     - Check users high pointer data
   WAITMAIL    - Check users waiting mail datafiles
   AREA        - Specify one area to act upon
   RANGE       - Specify a range of areas to act upon
   ALL         - Act upon all message areas
@rem </pre>

Running "MsgMaint" with the following command line will trim all the waiting mail files:

@rem <pre>
1> MsgMaint WAITMAIL ALL
@rem </pre>

Resetting user's high message pointers is also a good idea, else they will not know whether new messages have appeared in the area. Use this command line for this:

@rem <pre>
1> MsgMaint HIGHPTR ALL
@rem </pre>

These two commands are provided in an easy to use shortcut "Messages/TrimBases.zsc", see the Shortcuts section for more information.

@{b}Resetting a Message Area@{ub}

Message Areas should not be reset by deleting the data files it uses. Some message base libraries (see Section Message Base Libraries) use specially formatted data files to contain message pointer information. To reset all the messages in an area and to reset the pointers to 0 you should use Bin/mbManager with the following command line:

@rem <pre>
1> mbManager INITIALISE AREA <AreaNumber>
@rem </pre>

You do not have to INITIALISE bases area by area, see the RANGE and ALL keywords accepted by mbManager.

@{b}Mail Processors which support FTS-1@{ub}

A fair number of programs for the Amiga (generally found in AmiNet/comm/mail and AmiNet/comm/fido) support the FTS-1 format. This is a short list of programs that do:

 - Foozle
 - MailManager (set your message bases to Plain or Indexed mode)
 - TrapToss

@{"FTS-1 Config Picture" Link "MsgFTS1.gif/main"}


@{b}Setting up bases with mbstarmsg.library@{ub}

@{u}Individual Bases@{uu}

To set an individual message base to the "mbstarmsg.library" you should load up the Message Area Configuration, double-click on the area, and press the "Sel" button next to the "Library" field.

This will bring up the "Select Message Base Library..." window.

@{"Message Base Libraries Picture" Link "MsgLibs.gif/main"}

Double-clicking on a message base library will assign it to this message area.

@{u}All Areas@{uu}

The "Zeus:Rexx/MsgAreas/ChangeBaseLib.rexx" script has been provided for changing all the areas on your BBS to a new message area. To change all the areas to "mbstarmsg.library" for instance you would execute the following command line:

@rem <pre>
1> rx Zeus:Rexx/MsgAreas/ChangeBaseLib.rexx mbstarmsg.library
@rem </pre>

NB: The message base filename is case-sensitive, entering "MBSTARMSG.LIBRARY" will cause adverse affects!

@{u}Installing new message base libraries@{uu}

From the "Select Message Base Library..." window you can add new message base library files by clicking on the "ADD" button and using the file requester to select the message base library file.


@{b}Prefs/Editors@{ub}

Zeus:Prefs/Editors allows you to configure the Editors Configuration- the list of online editors that user's may use to write messages, edit file descriptions and create signature files with.

This is the main Editors Configuration window, which can be loaded from the Messages->Config->Editors menu option on the Control Window.

@{"Editors Picture" Link "Editors.gif/main"}

Editing an editor brings up the following window:

@{"Editors Config Picture" Link "EditorsCfg.gif/main"}

@{u}Name@{uu} - The name of the editor as seen by the user.

@{u}Low Access@{uu} - The minimum access level required to access this editor.

@{u}High Access@{uu} - The maximum access level required to access this editor.

@{u}Remote/Local/Both@{uu} - Whether the editor may be used on Local, Remote or either


Editors are configured in a rather different way from other parts of Zeus. For each Editor you have a text file which may contain "tags" and Arexx script segments. These tags split the file up into sections relating to what is being edited, and the Arexx segments are executed when a particular editor is run. To edit the text file press the Edit Scripts button. This will load up your text editor (as specified in ENV:FILEEDITOR) with the current editor's script segment. Here is an example script segment for CygnusEd:

The #FILE segment is related to file description editing. All file descriptions are edited in t:FileDesc.<line>, where <line> is the current line number.

The #MSG segment is related to message text editing. All message text is edited in t:MsgText.<line>, where <line> is the current line number.

@rem <pre>
#FILE
CLIDoor `"c:ED -keepio t:FileDesc.'Line'"'

#MSG
CLIDoor  `"c:ED -keepio t:FileDesc.'Line'"'
@rem </pre>


@{b}Netmail Mapper@{ub}

@{"Message Mapper Picture" Link "MsgMapper.gif/main"}

The Netmail Remapper is called Prefs/Mapper and may be accessed from the Messages->Config->Netmail Remapper menu on the Control Window.

The Netmail remapper is particularly useful if you are feeding points. The basic theory is that messages for the names in the left-hand side box get sent to the addresses listed in the right-hand side box. This process is carried out during the ZMP Import phase.

In addition, nicknames may be set up: in the above example messages addressed to "SysOp, Nick and Pinky" will be renamed to Nick Loman and sent to my address. This is acheived by using the `@' sign as the first character.


@{b}Updating File and Message Databases@{ub}

Upon quitting an Area Configuration program, the following window will popup if any changes have been made:

@{"Update Picture" Link "MsgUpdate.gif/main"}

@{u}Save the Configuration@{uu} - You wish to save all the changes made.

@{u}Update Online Configuration@{uu} - You wish to update the active configuration.

@{u}Update Data Files@{uu} - You wish to make any changes to the message database prompted by any configuration changes made (deleting, renumbering and adding areas),


@endnode



@node "Manual.FidoNet" "FidoNet"

@{i}@{b}Chapter 8 - FidoNet@{ub}@{ui}

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

This part of the manual covers the use of the message processing tools supplied with Zeus such as ZMP (fidonet mail import and export utility), ZMailer (fidonet packet transfering utility) and nodelisting documentation such as creating your own point net and using Traplist for parsing nodelists. Nodelists are like a telephone book listing the names and numbers of all the systems connected to FidoNet.

Also covered are other mail applicable aspects such as file hatching with fidonet technology.

@{b}About Fidonet and other Networks.@{ub}

FidoNet is the largest amateur network in the world. It was started in 1984 by Tom Jennings. Currently more than 20000 nodes worldwide are connected. The network has a hierarchic tree (or star) topology:

@{"FidoNet Picture" Link "FidoTopology.gif/main"}

Zones are divided in Regions, which are divided in Nets. The Nets consist of Nodes, which are usually (but not necessarily) Bulletin Board Systems. Each node has a unique address which consists of four parts: Zone, Net, Node and Point, in text form expressed as "zone:net/node.point". Zone numbers 1 up to and including 6 are used by FidoNet:

@rem <pre>
    1 = North America (United States of America and Canada)
    2 = Europe and Commonwealth of Independent States
    3 = Oceania (Australia and New Zealand)
    4 = Latin America
    5 = Africa
    6 = Asia
@rem </pre>

There are several other networks that use FidoNet Technology. Networks such as AmigaNet use higher zone numbers which are allocated by a central body, 39-41 for example.

Many nodes have one or more points. A point is a user who gets mail from a node (it's "boss"), usually as compressed mail files. This way they can read and write messages offline saving time and money. The point address of the boss is 0 (e.g. 2:441/58.0) but the ".0" is often omitted from the address.

To operate successfully as a FidoNet node a variety of tools are needed. As you would expect Zeus provides these tools built-in but also has extensive support for third-party programs.


@{b}Mailer@{ub} (also known as a FrontDoor)

The mailer is a program that waits for incoming calls from users and FidoNet systems. Users calling are passed through to the BBS. FidoNet calls are intercepted and a handshaking procedure is started. This handshaking establishes a common protocol between the two mailers, exchanges information about each other's system and makes sure that the connection is secure (i.e. the passwords match and mail is not being received by a foreign source).

Zeus's internal mailer is called ZMailer and is stored in Zeus:Bin. Its configuration program is Zeus:Prefs/Mailer.

Other Amiga mailers are available and compatible with Zeus. They are all available on the AmiNet.

@rem <pre>
Mailer                   AmiNet FileName

TrapDoor                 from most BBS's as TD_1_84.lzh
Gotcha                   Gotcha12b1.lha
GMS                      comm/fido/GMS_11b64.lha
JamMail                  comm/fido/jm960227.lha
"The Shelter Mailers"    comm/fido/SHELTER275.lha
@rem </pre>


@{b}Mail Processor@{ub} (also known as a tosser, scanner or packer)

This program is used to "import" and "export" mail. Most mail processors work on a two phase basis. Exporting scans the message bases on the BBS searching for mail that has not been seen by all the systems who take an area (or 'echo') and gathers it into "bundles" stored in the "outbound" directory ready for collecting or sending by the Mailer. Importing scans the "inbound" directory for new mail bundles received by the Mailer and unpacks them into the message bases ready for reading by the BBS users and the system's points.

Zeus's internal mail processor is called ZMP and is stored in Zeus:Bin. Its configuration is stored and changed using a text file called Zeus:Config/ZMP.cfg.

Other Amiga mail processors are available and compatible with Zeus (using the mbstarmsg.library, see chapter Message Subsystem, section Message Base Libraries).

@rem <pre>
Mail Processor                  AmiNet FileName

EMS                             ems_1_0_exec.lha
Foozle                          comm/fido/foozle102.lha
MailManager                     comm/fido/mm_1_2.lha
JS_Toss                         comm/fido/JS_Toss102b.lha
TrapToss                        comm/fido/TrapToss_1_50.lzh
@rem </pre>


@{b}Tick Processor@{ub}

FidoNet also provides support for "file echoes". These are similar in setup to a message echo, except they carry binary files rather than ASCII message text. A tick processor reads in TIC files from the inbound directory and adds their associated files to the correct file areas. Tick often has a companion called "Hatch" which allows FidoNet systems to send files to the file echo for distribution.

Zeus's Tick is built into the Zeus Mail Processor (ZMP) and can be run by specifying the TICK keyword on operation.

Other Tick processors for the Amiga are available, but not recommended for use as they cannot integrate with the Zeus file catalogue which renders them only partially useful.


@{b}Areafix@{ub}

Areafix is a relatively new FidoNet utility designed to take the pain out of running a busy node system for the SysOp. Before Areafix was used FidoNet administrators had to "fix" people into message echoes manually by editing their configurations. This was time wasting when users wished to add a large number of echoes. In addition to this, Areafix allows user's to connect to echoes not taken by the node. This is done by sending a chain of Areafix requests back up the FidoNet hierachy until a system is found which taks the echo that the user requries. Areafix could cause huge space wastage and gigantic mail packets if abused, so most Areafix programs allow strict access restriction systems to be implemented to stop some systems fixing into private echoes, too many, or any at all.

Zeus's Areafix is built into the Zeus Mail Processor (ZMP) and is automatically run when an import is in progress.


@{b}Nodelists@{ub}

To function in a proper environment the Zeus specific mailer (ZMailer) requires you to have configured nodelists for every FidoNet technology network you carry on your bulletin board. This may include a pointlist, as nodelists only carry information about zones, networks and nodes.

The 'TrapList' utilities you will need to compile and update nodelists can be found on disk #4 of the Zeus distribution set as `NODELIST.LHA'.

Please take the time to read the relevant documentation for traplist and the nodelist tools within that archive for a more verbose description of nodelist technology than covered here.

To cover briefly setting a system up for a link with your BBS system then it's just a matter of using the SetPasswd tool within the Nodelist archive like this:

 SetPassWd <Session Password> Address_1 Address_2 etc....

These passwords can also be set within the traplist configuration file which will be explained later on along with an example configuration file. This is also the recommended route since the nodelist data can be damaged and lose all the password information.

Needless to say both you, and the system(s) you are exchanging mail with will have to use the same passwords, else the link will be considered insecure and mail will not be transferred.

Here is an example traplist configuration which will give you an idea on setting up to recieve the Zeus support echos.

@rem <pre>
ZONE 85

NODELISTPATH "NODELIST:"
BUFFERSIZE 65536
REPORT "Ram:Traplist.log"
NOCHECKCRC
NODELIST "ZeusNet"
PASSWORD "SECRET" 85:1/1.0
DIAL "44" "0"
@rem </pre>

The entries broken down individually are :-

@{u}Zone@{uu} - This is the network number. 85 is a unique number used by the ZeusNet. While more than one nodelist can be parsed with this single config file, you must use only one Zone line which should be the lowest network number you are on.

@{u}NodelistPath@{uu} - This is the directory where the nodelists and nodediff files are present. You must assign Nodelist: to a directory and use that path here as in the example above.

@{u}BufferSize@{uu} - The bigger the buffer, the quicker traplist can process the nodelists. Obviously this depends on memory restrictions with your computer.

@{u}Report@{uu} - Path to a file to output any messages from the processing. A logfile you can refer to to check if it all worked okay.

@{u}NoCheckCRC@{uu} - If this line is ommited then Traplist will run a crc check on the nodelists listed in the following lines and compare it to the number within the nodelist itself. This is really only of use to sysops using nodediff files for updating nodelists and for nets as small as Zeus, it's easier to just release the full nodelist and so crc checksums within the nodelist are rarely needed.

@{u}Nodelist@{uu} - As many of these entries as you like can be configured. Each name will be checked by traplist for a nodelist <name>.082 for example and processing will take place if it finds a valid file. You don't need to specify an extension number on the name as traplist will do it for you, and automatically makes sure it uses the highest number.

 For example if ZeusNet.024 and ZeusNet.046 were found, *.046 would be processed.

@{u}Password@{uu} - This is how you configure session password between systems linked to your bbs for security checks and to prevent any system polling your Mailer with the right address and stealing someone elses mail.

 For example

 PASSWORD "Backyard" 85:1/13.0

 This means that if system 85:1/13.0 calls your mailer then no files will be transferred unless it also sent a session password of Backyard.

@{u}DIAL@{uu} - This is a modifier string for changing phone number formats within the nodelists as they are processed.

 For example

 DIAL "44" "0"

means any instances of 44 at the start of a phone number for a system in the nodelist would be replaced with 0, used by British sysops as the 44 is a number used to dial outside of England which isn't normally needed. A system with the number "44-4423-443533" in their nodelist entry would be replaced with "04423-443533" when dialling out.


NB: This is a very brief breakdown of usage regarding Traplist and mailer technology. Refer to the full documentation within the Trapdoor archive for more detailed explanations as the above is a quick starting guide only.

Here is an example pointlist file which you can customise to generate a list of points from which Zmailer will get their system information when a call is recieved from their address. It's not actually necessary to use a pointlist with Zeus but you will still need a password line for each point listing their session password and addresses or they will not be able to send or recieve mail. You set up a points password details within the traplist config file (as detailed above) as normal, or with the SetPasswd tool within the Trapdoor archive.

@rem <pre>
;A My Pointlist/Fakenet list -- fake crc 0 : 0<Ctrl M>
;A^M
Zone,2,->^M
Region,254,->^M
,255,BackYard,North_Harrow,Anthony_Brice,44-0-181-4242065,9600,HST,MO^M
Point,1,Hell_On_Earth,North_Harrow,Anthony_Brice,UNLISTED,9600,MO^M
Point,3,The_Garage,Rayners_Lane,Gary_Pearse,UNLISTED,9600,MO^M
^Z
@rem </pre>

Note: The information within the < > brackets are control codes which need to be used when generating your own pointlist. <Ctrl M> means press Control and M at that point. I recommend using an editor such as CygnusEd when creating a nodelist, as that allows the insertion of such control codes, and nodelists MUST have these codes to process properly.

The Point lines are defined as below:

Point,<PointNumber>,<SiteText>,<Location>,<Point Name>,<PhoneNumber>,<Baud>,<Flags>


@{u}PointNumber@{uu} - Their unique number as a point.

@{u}Site Name@{uu} - Some text describing their system.

@{u}Location@{uu} - Their town / state.

@{u}Phone number@{uu} - Can be set to UNLISTED as above, which means you can't use a mailer to dial them up by using their fido address as they are points and wouldn't have a mailer to answer the phone.

@{u}Baud@{uu} - A maximum rate of 9600 due to some old nodelist processors not handling handle a five digit number.

@{u}Flags@{uu} - Usually set to MO (Mail Only).


@{b}Setting up a simple node system@{ub}

Most bulletin board's operate as "nodes" within the FidoNet hierarchy.

Here is an example configuration for a FidoNet node "2:888/43.0" who polls an IBM system called "2:888/1.0".


@{i}Addressing@{ui}

A note on addressing:

The address defined in the NODE keyword is used as the base for all the AREA, SYSTEM and ROUTE addresses so you only need to specify the parts which are different.

Example:

@rem <pre>
NODE 85:1/1.0@zeusnet

85:1/100.0@zeusnet
85:1/100.0
85:1/100
1/100
100
@rem </pre>

Are all valid ways of writing '85:1/100.0@zeusnet'

@rem <pre>
85:1/100.1@zeusnet
85:1/100.1
1/100.1
100.1
@rem </pre>

Are all valid ways of writing '85:1/100.1@zeusnet'

@rem <pre>
85:1/1.1@zeusnet
85:1/1.1
1/1.1
1.1
.1
@rem </pre>

Are all valid ways of writing '85:1/1.1@zeusnet'


@{b}Structure of ZMP.cfg@{ub}

This is the order of the items required for a ZMP configuration:

@rem <pre>
; Comment Lines

Main Configuration Tags

-> Network
NODE
AKA
POINTNET
ZONES

SYSTEM Lines
AREA lines
TICK Lines
ROUTE Lines
-> Network

Next Network...
@rem </pre>


Configuration files are stored in Zeus:Config/ZMP.cfg

This is the example:

@rem <pre>

MSGBUFFER 32768
IDXSTORE  1024

FLOCTRL
4DFLPO
CTRLCHAR ^
NOCHKNETDOMAIN
NOCHKPKTDOMAIN
BOUNCEBADADDR
BOUNCENOROUTE
BOUNCENOUSER
UNPACKDIR T:
PACKDIR T:

; FidoNet setup

NODE           2:888/43.0
AKA            0
POINTNET       8843
ZONES          1 2 3 4 5 6
CREATENEW      1
CREATELINK     1

SYSTEM     1   U2YYNNNBY   ZIP   PASS   PASS   PASS   0

AREA       NET888          0     1 43
AREA       AMIGA_UK        0     1 43
AREA       AMIGASOFT       0     1 43
AREA       CONTROV         0     1 43

ROUTE      *:*/*.*         1
@rem </pre>

For a better and more fully commented ZMP.cfg example, please see the example files installed in Zeus:Config/


@{b}Explanation of configuration tags.@{ub}

@{u}MSGBUFFER@{uu} <bytes>

defines the largest FTN message ZMP will be able to import. <Number> is the amount of bytes ZMP allocates and must be a minimum of 32768 bytes.

@{u}IDXSTORE@{uu} <records>

defines the amount of index records in ZMP.index. The more indexes, the better the dupe checking and reply linking but ZMP will use more memory, disk space and time. Each index record is 36 bytes long.

@{u}FLOCTRL@{uu}

makes ZMP use special characters in the .?LO flow files. Most Amiga mailers support this flag (including ZMailer), but some older ones may require NOFLOCTRL to be set.

@{u}4DFLO@{uu}

makes ZMP use 4 dimensional filenames in the Outbound directories. Again most Amiga mailers (including ZMailer) support this format.

@{u}CTRLCHAR@{uu} <character>

indicates that mail packet files should be prefixed with <character> in outgoing mail packets. The default is a ^ which means that the file should be deleted. Most Amiga mailers support these characters. Other acceptable values are:

# - Truncate this file to zero length

^ - Delete this file (with logging)

- - Delete this file (without logging)

~ - Don't send this file

@{u}NOCHKNETDOMAIN@{uu}

When a netmail's origin and destination addresses are not in the same domain, ZMP will attempt to bounce the message back to the sender. Specifying this keyword disables this checking.

@{u}NOCHKPKTDOMAIN@{uu}

If ZMP detects that a message packet's origin and destination addresses are not in the same domain, it will rename it *.BAD and not process it. Specifying this keyword disables this check.

@{u}BOUNCEBADADDR@{uu}

If you use netmail domain checking (by not specifying NOCHKNETDOMAIN in your config) then badly addressed messages will be bounced back to the node which sent them (if possible).

@{u}BOUNCENOROUTE@{uu}

If a netmail is processed which is not destined for your system but ZMP is unable to route the message to another system, a message will be sent back to the sender telling them about it.

@{u}BOUNCENOUSER@{uu}

Specifying this keyword causes ZMP to check the To: field of every netmail that is destined for your system against your current list of users. If the recipient does not have a user record, ZMP will bounce the message with the message 'User not known at this address'.

@{u}UNPACKDIR@{uu} <directory>

The temporary directory ZMP will unpack mail bundles into. Specifying a directory in the Ram Disk (RAM:) will make importing quicker, but will cause problems if trying to import large sized message packets on a system without much free memory.

@{u}PACKDIR@{uu} <directory>

The temporary directory ZMP will pack the mail bundles from before they are put in the outbound directory. The same limitations apply here as with UNPACKDIR.

@{u}ATTACHDIR@{uu} <directory>

The directory to place any files that arrive attached to messages. If you do not use this keyword, the inbound directory will be used.


@{i}Also@{ui}..

@{u}INBOUND@{uu} <directory>
@{u}OUTBOUND@{uu} <directory>

These force ZMP to use different directories than those set in the General Paths configuration (in the Prefs/System program).  Useful if you don't want ZMP to import packets/bundles received via ZMailer, but @{b}do@{ub} still want ZMP for other work.


@{u}NODE@{uu} <network address>

NODE defines your address in a FTN network. The address must be at least 4d (Zone:Net/Node.Point) and preferably 5d (Zone:Net/Node.Point@Domain).

@{u}AKA@{uu} <network address>

Defines one or more AKA addresses (for netmail routing).

@{u}POINTNET@{uu} <number>

The net number defined by POINTNET will be stripped out of incoming messages and replaced with 3d control lines.

@{u}ZONES@{uu} <zone number, zone number [...]>

Defines all valid zone numbers for this domain. These are used when incoming netmail messages have no domain information. A maximum of twenty may be defined.

@{u}CREATENEW@{uu} <area>

When an echomail comes in with an unknown tag and the sending system has ALLOWNEW capabilities, ZMP will also create a message area on your board. If the given message base number is already used, ZMP will increment it until it finds an unused one.

@{u}CREATELINK@{uu} <area>

If you want to link into a pass-through area you would usually have to create the area on the board and then add your address to the appropriate AREA line. By specifying this keyword (BEFORE your AREA lines) you only need to add your address to the AREA line and ZMP will create a new area on the board while it loads its config.

The Message Base Number works in the same way as CREATENEW.


@{u}SYSTEM@{uu} <address> <flag array> <archiver> <packet password> <areafix password> <tick pw> <groups>

defines a known system for the current network. The arguments are:

Address - The FTN address of this system.

Flag Array - Nine characters together (i.e. 'U2YYNNNBY') as follows:

@rem <pre>
AreaFix Access - One of the following characters:

 N No AreaFix access. All requests from this system will be ignored.
 Y May use %LIST, %QUERY, %UNLINKED, %HELP, %PAUSE, %RESUME, %RESCAN and link/unlink into echos.
 U As for 'Y' but AreaFix enables uplink requests. (See AreaFix section).
 C Full AreaFix control. May create, delete and rename echos.  May also request for other systems.

Control Type
 Specifies the number of dimensions used on SEEN-BY and PATH lines.

 2 Net/Node for nodes. PointNet/Point for points.
 3 Net/Node for nodes. Net/Node.Point for points.

Packet Change
 Specify 'Y' to make ZMP generate the same packet header types for this system
 as it receives. 'N' to disable.

Archiver
 Change Specify 'Y' to make ZMP change the archiver it uses on this systems mail
 packets to match the ones it receives.  'N' to disable.

Netmail FLO
 Specifies the 'flavour' of netmail packets.

 N  Normal
 H  Hold
 D  Direct
 C  Crash

Echomail FLO
 Specifies the 'flavour' of echomail packets. Same options as the netmail FLO
 flag.

Tick FLO
 Specifies the 'flavour' of *.TIC files. Same options as the netmail FLO flag.

Packet header
 Specifies the packet header type used on outgoing mail packets. May be one of:

 A Basic FTS-0001 revision 15 header. No point information.
 B FSC-0039 header. Uses four dimensional addressing.
 C FSC-0048 header. Uses four dimensional addressing.
 D FSC-0045 (Packet 2.2) header. Has full five dimensional addresses.

Archive Netmail.
 If this SYSTEM can handle archived netmail, set this flag
 to 'Y', otherwise set to 'N'.
@rem </pre>

Archiver

 The name of an archiver as defined with Zeus:Prefs/Archivers. All echomail (and optionally netmail) for this system will be archived using the specified type.

Packet Password

 For extra security, you can specify a password which will be placed in the packet header. If you do not want to use a packet password (or the system does not support them) use '-NONE-'

AreaFix Password

 If the system has AreaFix access then you can specify a password which the system must put in the subject field of all AreaFix requests. If you don't want to use an AreaFix password then specify '-NONE'. If you want to use the packet password for areafix as well, specify two quote marks like "".

Tick Password

 The password to be used in *.TIC files sent and received to/from this system. You can disable the password by specifying '-NONE-' you can duplicate the AreaFix password by using "".

Group Number(s)

 The area group numbers that this system has access to. AreaFix uses this information when deciding what echos this system can link into.



@{u}AREA@{uu} <tagname> <group> <address address [...]>

This keyword defines an echomail area. The arguments are:

TagName

 The tagname for the echo.

Group

 A number between 0-65535. By grouping certain echos together you can easily restrict access for a system.

Linked Systems

 A list of system addresses which are linked into this echo. If you do not specify your address, the messages will not be stored in any message base but be passed through to the other connected systems. The address may be prefixed with one of the following characters:

 '-' The system has read-only access to this echo.

 '=' The system is not linked in but if they link in using AreaFix, they will have read-only access.

 '|' The system is linked in but their feed is currently paused (using the %PAUSE areafix command).

 '#' The system is linked in but their feed is paused and when they resume the area, they will have read-only access.



@{u}ROUTE@{uu} <from address> <to address>

Specifies Netmail routing information. When Netmail's are imported to the system, their to address is compared against the "from address" entry of each ROUTE statement in the applicable network. If a route statement matches, then the Netmail will be routed to the "to address", e.g., if a netmail addressed to 2:888/67.0 was imported to the system and the following ROUTE lines existed:

ROUTE 40      56

ROUTE *:*/*.* 1

The first entry would be ignored as the to node of the message is 67, not 40.The next entry is a wildcard and all addresses will match it. Therefore the message would be routed to node 1 (2:888/1.0).


@{b}Setting up Archivers@{ub}

ZMP reads the Archivers configuration file so it can pack and unpack message bundles, which are traditionally archived to save transmission time with the Mailer.

When setting up your ZMP configuration you must make sure that all the archiver entries have the correct paths to the binaries. These archivers all available from the AmiNet.

@rem <pre>
Archiver Name             AmiNet File

ARC                       util/arc/arc.lha
LHA & LZH                 util/arc/LhA_e138.run
LZX                       util/arc/lzx121.lha
UUENCODE                  util/arc/uuxt31.lha
ZIP                       util/arc/Unzip512x.lha,
                          util/arc/zip201x.lha
ZOO                       util/arc/zoo2-0.lzh
@rem </pre>

The Archivers configuration program can be accessed from the Message->Config->Archivers menu on the Control screen, or from the Zeus:Prefs drawer.

@{"Archivers Config Picture" Link "ArchiversCfg.gif/main"}

Each archiver has various fields to be configured:

@{u}Name@{uu} - The descriptive name of the archiver. This field is the one used in your ZMP.cfg to define what archiver a particular node uses. It should not have spaces in it.

@{u}Compress@{uu} - The line is expanded to make the command line used to compress one or more files into this archive type. This line takes expansion codes ~a and ~f, e.g. if we were packing a file called 00003445.pkt into a file called OUTBOUND:2.888.1.0.LHA, the compress line would be expanded to "c:LHA -2 -a a OUTBOUND:2.881.1.0.LHA 00003445.pkt".

@{u}Extract@{uu} - This line is expanded to make the archiver extract one or more files from an archive. This line takes expansion codes ~a and ~f, where ~a is the archive name to extract and ~f is an optional argument to extract one or more single files. If all the files are to be extracted then the program will not use the ~f argument.

@{u}Test@{uu} - This line is expanded to make the archiver test the archive. This line only takes the ~a expansion code. Zeus detects whether the file tested OK by checking the result code of the archiver. If the result code is 0 then it is assumed that the archive is not corrupted.

@{u}Recog@{uu} - This line is a hex string used to detect whether an archive to extract is of this type. For example all LHA archives start with two random characters and then the string "-lh5-". We represent this with the line "** ** 2D 6C 68 35 2D", where ** compares to any single character.

@{u}Show User@{uu} - This flag determines whether the archiver will be able to be viewed by an on-line user accessing the archivers configuration, for example within Phoenix.Archivers such as "UUENCODE" and "ZGATE" should not have this flag set off.



@{b}Other ZMP configuration tags.@{ub}

@{u}DELFILECHAR@{uu} <Character>

This character will be prefixed to netmail attached files in the destinations .FLO file if you have turned on FLOCTRL and DELNETATTACHED.

@{u}DELNETATTACHED@{uu}

When an incoming netmail, which has attached files, is not destined for your system the files will be added to the destinations FLO file with the DELFILECHAR prefixed to the file name so your mailer will deleted the file once sent. This only works in conjunction with the FLOCTRL keyword.

@{u}DELNETMAIL@{uu}

ZMP always imports netmails into your message base but if this keyword is used, ones that are not from or to your system will be deleted during export.

@{u}ATTACHDIR@{uu} <Directory>

Files that come in attached to messages will be put in the ATTACHDIR. When the messages are exported, ZMP will look here for attached files.

@{u}AREAFMT@{uu} <Format String>

When AreaFix adds a new area to your ZMP.cfg it uses the specified format string to make it match to your other AREA lines. You need one '%s' (for the tagname) and one '%lu' for the group number. Both are standard C formatting codes. There are two other special codes which are:

       \\t  Tab (single backslash followed by t)

       \\s  Space (single backslash followed by s)

@{u}TICKFMT@{uu} <Format String>

As for AREAFMT but this specifies the format of TICK lines. You need an extra '%lu' in the format for the file area number, but apart from that, it is the same as AREAFMT.

@{u}NOAREAFIX@{uu}

Disables ZMP's internal AreaFix.

@{u}MINMSGS@{uu} <Number>

Specifies the number of new messages that must be in a message base before ZMP will try to export the area. By running ZMP with the arguments EXPORT FORCE', ZMP will ignore the MINMSGS setting.

@{u}NOUSERBOUNCE@{uu} <User Name>

If you have user bouncing enabled (with BOUNCENOUSER - don't get confused!) there are some names that you might not want to cause a bounce with i.e.'SysOp'. This keyword gives you this option.

@{u}NETEXEC@{uu} <Name> <Password> <Executable>

If a netmail is received addressed to <Name> the given executable will be run. <Name> must have quotes around it if there are spaces.

Password should be a maximum of ten characters long but may be pecified as '-NONE-' which will disable the password checking. Using NETEXEC before any NODE statements defines a global entry, you can also limit the entry to a domain by putting it after the appropriate NODE entry.

Various control codes can be passed to the "Executable" line of NETEXEC to expand into data relating to the message:

%f
 Who the message is from

%t
 Who the message is to

%s
 The subject of the message (Usually password but could be other data!)

%A
 The from address of the message (Zone:Net/Node.Point)

%D
 The dest address of the message (Zone:Net/Node.Point)

%n
 The number of the saved message

%a
 The area the message was saved into

%F
 Who the message is from (with underscores)

%T
 Who the message is to (with underscores)

%S
 The subject of the message (with underscores)

%%
 A '%' character

@{u}DELBADMSGID@{uu}

If a message comes in with a non-FTN standard MSGID kludge it will usually be imported. Specify this flag if you want these messages to be deleted during import. Not really recommended, as there are a lot of PC packages which really mess it up.

@{u}ALLOWRESCAN@{uu}

By specifying this keyword, you allow systems that have AreaFix access to use the %RESCAN command.

@{u}ALLOWMIXEDPKT@{uu}

Special kludge which causes echomail packets to be processed in a slightly different way to support some brain-dead PC tosser software!

@{u}NOECHOCREATE@{uu}

Disables ZMP's auto echomail creation function.

@{u}NOTICKCREATE@{uu}

Disables ZMP's auto tick area creation function.

@{u}TWITUSER@{uu} <User Name>

Any messages being imported that come from <User Name> will be deleted.This is a global setting for all domains.

@{u}HIDEARCS@{uu}

When (de)archiving mail packets, the archivers will be redirected to NIL: if this keyword is set.

@{u}ANNOUNCENEW@{uu} <Message Area Number>

When a new Message or Tick echo is created automatically, a message will be posted in this message area to inform yourself and/or your users.  Placed in the global section, this will affect all areas. In the NODE section, it will affect only that network. If you have a global one, you can use "ANNOUNCENEW 0" in a NODE section to stop announcements for just that network.  You can, of course, also have a global config item and still have messages for some networks go to unique areas.


The following keywords must appear after a NODE definition:

@{u}NEWTICKAREA@{uu} <File Area Number>

When ZMP creates a new TICK area, it uses the given number as the file area for the new TICK line. ZMP does NOT create new file areas on your BBS.

@{u}TICK@{uu} <TagName> <Group> <File Area> [Linked System Addresses]

Defines a TICK file echo. The format and usage is the same as the AREA line but you need to specify a file area number so ZMP knows where to save the files. If you wish to have a pass-through area, the <File Area> maybe zero.

@{u}FILEECHO@{uu} <TagName> <FileAreaNumber>

Echomail messages may also have file attaches. This keyword links an echo tag to a file area on your BBS. Files that come attached to messages in <TagName> will be uploaded to area <FileAreaNumber>automatically.

@{u}UPLINK@{uu} <Address> <Password>

Specifies an uplink address for AreaFix. See AreaFix section for more information. The password should be the one you use when accessing the given systems AreaFix.

@{u}ALLOWNEW@{uu} <Address> [Address...]

When a message is received with an unknown tag ZMP will create the AREA in your ZMP.cfg only if the message came from an address defined with the ALLOWNEW keyword.

@{u}AUTOECHOADD@{uu} <Address> [Address] ...

Whenever ZMP creates a new AREA, it automatically adds the addresses specified with this keyword to the export to list. Very useful if you are a hub for a small network!

@{u}AUTOTICKADD@{uu} <Address> [Address] ...

Whenever ZMP creates a new TICK, it automatically adds the addresses specified with this keyword to the export to list.

@{u}TWITUSER@{uu} <User Name>

Any messages being imported that are from <User Name> will be deleted.

@{u}TWITADDR@{uu} <Address>

Any messages being imported that are addressed from <Address> will be deleted. <Address> may include wildcards.

@{u}MAXPKTSIZE@{uu} <Bytes> <Address> [Address] ...

Some systems cannot handle mail packets over a certain size. This keyword specifies the maximum number of bytes per packet to create for the listed systems (wildcards accepted).

@{u}MAXBUNDLESIZE@{uu} <Bytes> <Address> [Address] ...

More importantly, some systems cannot handle mail bundles over a certain size, usually due to memory or disk limitations. This keyword specifies the maximum number of bytes per bundle to create for the listed systems (wildcards accepted). Remember that as the packets are compressed to about a third of their usual size, so it MAXPKTSIZE is set at 256000 bytes, MAXBUNDLESIZE at 512000 is plenty!

@{u}ITRANSLATION@{uu} <Table1> [Table2]

Translation tables are stored in Zeus:Config/Translation. On import, the text is translated through <Table1> and then, if specified, through <Table2> Defined tables affect all areas after the keywords, e.g.

ITRANSLATION ISO IBM

OTRANSLATION IBM ISO

AREA ...

AREA ...

These areas are affected by the ISO-IBM translations.

ITRANSLATION SE7 ISO

OTRANSLATION ISO SE7

AREA ...

AREA...

These areas are affected by the SE7-ISO translation tables.

@{u}OTRANSLATION@{uu} <Table1> [Table2]

On export, the text is translated through <Table1> and then, if specified, through <Table2>. It is then exported to all connected nodes.


@{b}Uplinks@{ub}

Uplinks are systems which you poll for mail, have a wider range of echos, and you have AreaFix access to.

To setup an uplink, you need to specify them in the config with a SYSTEM line and an UPLINK line. You also need a list of echo tagnames that they carry and you have access to. This list needs to be saved in the Zeus:Config/AreaFix/ directory and the filename format is z.n.n.p.LST

An example:

I have an uplink at 1:234/56.0 and they carry three echos which I don't. Their names are ECHO1, ECHO2 and ECHO3. So I create a file called Zeus:Config/AreaFix/1.234.56.0.LST and in it I have the echo tagnames listed one per line, like so:

@rem <pre>
ECHO1         Example Echo #1
ECHO2         Example Echo #2
ECHO3         Example Echo #3
@rem </pre>

If the echo tagname is followed by a description (as in the above example) then it will be used to describe the area if a system asks for an %UPLINK list.

When a system (with uplink access) requests ECHO2, AreaFix scans the echolist file, finds ECHO2 and sends an AreaFix request to 1:234/56.0 asking it for the echo.

Meanwhile, the original requesting system is told that the echo has been requested from the uplink and ZMP adds a new AREA line into ZMP.cfg which sets up ECHO2 as a pass-through area. When the new echo starts flowing from the uplink, it is passed automatically to the original system and you don't need to change your configs at all!

The uplink lists are AREAS.BBS format, if your uplink can supply them. Otherwise, an edited %LIST response could be used.


@{b}The AreaFix Help Command@{ub}

The following help file is sent to the user on receipt of a %HELP command in an AreaFix request - if you would like to edit it for your own needs, it is stored in Zeus:Config/AreaFix/AreaFix.hlp


1. What is an AreaFix?

   Running an AreaFix saves the SysOp of a node from the annoying business
   of adding/removing systems to/from their echomail distribution list.


2. Formatting your AreaFix request

   Requests are made via netmail messages which contain specific
   information in some of the fields.  In particular, the addressee is
   always 'AreaFix' and the subject is the password assigned to you by the
   SysOp of this system.

   For example:

      From:     Jon Dough    (1:234/56.7)
      To:       AreaFix      (1:234/56.0)
      Subject:  Password

   The text of the message contains one or more request commands (one per
   line) which are detailed below.


3. Information requests

   You can request information from AreaFix about what echos you have
   access to and which ones are already being exported to you.

   These are the currently supported commands:

@rem <PRE>
      %HELP      Sends this file to your system as a netmail.

      %LIST      Lists all the echomail and file areas currently available
                 from this system.  The list also shows which areas you are
                 currently linked into.

      %QUERY     Lists all the areas you are currently linked into.

      %UNLINKED  Lists all the areas you are _not_ currently linked into but
                 are available to you.

      %UPLINK    Lists all the echomail areas available to you from this
                 systems uplinks (if any).
@rem </PRE>


4. Linking and Unlinking to areas

   You can link into an echo by specifying it's tagname in your AreaFix
   request.

   For example:

      ECHONAME

   Will link you into the echo with a tagname of 'ECHONAME'.  If the echo
   doesn't exist at this system, and you have the relevent access, the
   request will be passed to this systems uplink.

   You can unlink from an echo by specifying a '-' before the tagname.

   For example:

      -ECHONAME

   As an extension to this, you can request to be linked/unlinked to/from
   all the available echomail areas at this system.

      %ALL
      %-ALL

   The first command would link your system into all the echos available to
   you and the second unlinks them all.  These commands do not apply to file
   echos.

   After any echomail link changes, AreaFix will send you a message with
   the results of the request.


5. %PAUSE and %RESUME

   If you wish to temporarily disable the flow of all echomail areas
   without actually linking out of them, then send the %PAUSE command.

   When you want to enable the echomail flow send a %RESUME command.

   Netmails for your system are unaffected by these commands.


6. Rescanning

   Sending a %RESCAN command to AreaFix will cause it to export all the
   messages you haven't seen yet from all the echos you are linked into.

   You can rescan a single area by using:

      %RESCAN <Echo Name>

   Specifying ALL for the echoname will have the same effect as having
   no arguments.


7. Remote maintainance

   If the SysOp of this system has granted you full AreaFix control then
   you have access to the following commands.

@rem <PRE>
      &ECHONAME               Create a new echo with the tag name
                              'ECHONAME'.  Your system will not be linked
                              into the new echo.

      ~ECHONAME               Delete the echo with a tag name of 'ECHONAME'

      # OLD_NAME : NEW_NAME   Change an echo's tagname from 'OLD_NAME' to
                              'NEW_NAME'.  The spaces are optional.

      %FROM: 1:234/56.0       Specify that the request comes from
                              1:234/56.0 instead of your system.  Note that
                              the password in the subject line must be
                              correct for your system.
@rem </PRE>


@{b}Using AreaFix@{ub}

AreaFix can be thought of as a robot, waiting on your system for requests from users. Each network has its own AreaFix robot. If a user wanted to receive a list of echoes which you carry in the FidoNet network, for example, they would send a netmail to the `@{i}user@{ui}' "AreaFix" at your FidoNet address. In this message, they must put the command "%LIST". The AreaFix is password protected however, to ensure that nobody else attaches them to any areas they don't want (imagine suddenly one day receiving several megabytes of mail when normally you'd only get a few kilobytes - this is the abuse that passwords are designed to stop). The users password must be in the subject line.

@{b}Using AreaFix for remote SysOping@{ub}

If you are away from your BBS computer, but can stay in touch with it (using a laptop with some terminal and pointing software and a mobile phone for example), then you can still manage your mail system!

You must first make sure the point address you have set for yourself has SysOp access to AreaFix.  Check the relevant section in this chapter on the SYSTEM keyword.  Once done, you can perform the changes mentioned in the AreaFix help file.

This system may also be useful if your BBS is run by many Co-SysOps. A co-SysOp can be in charge of a single network's (or more, remember that SysOp access can be set per-network) management while not actually needing to be at the BBS computer.

Of particular note is the "%FROM:" keyword.  If a point or other downlink of the BBS is having trouble fixing into an echo (for example), then you, as a SysOp also pointing, can send an AreaFix with that users password from your address if you specify "%FROM <their address>".

@endnode



@node "Manual.Internet" "Internet"


@{b}@{b}Chapter 9 - The Internet@{ub}@{ub}

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

@{i}Types of InterNet account@{ui}

There are currently two widly used types of InterNet account: static and dynamic.  Static accounts provide you with your own IP address, domain name and multiple mail boxes.  Dynamic accounts allocate a new IP address for you every time you connect to your provider, have only one mailbox and usually a 'firewall' stopping outside access to your system using Telnet, FTP and other InterNet protocols.

@{i}Zeus and the InterNet@{ui}

Zeus comes with six utilities to help interface your BBS to the InterNet:

@rem <PRE>
* Zeus:Bin/System/NetStart
@rem </PRE>

Telnet is a very simple InterNet protocol which sends and receives text between a host and a client, much like a normal BBS session, except the data is divided up into packets and transfered over the net instead of a normal dialup connection.

Because of this similarity, several Telnet daemons have been written which allow Amiga terminal and BBS packages to interface to Telnet by opening a faked serial.device.

Some Telnet daemons allow multiple incoming sessions by allocating a new unit number to every connection and spawning an external program such as NetStart.

Telnet daemons will normally only work well with static InterNet accounts.

@rem <PRE>
* Zeus:Bin/ZGate
@rem </PRE>

ZGate converts Email into Netmail, UseNet newsgroups into Echomail and vice versa.  You will need to have a working mail processor setup (preferably ZMP) although you do not need to be a member of any external network if you only wish the mail and news to appear on your BBS.

ZGate will work fine with dynamic InterNet accounts but, if you want to give your users Email access or run a private/public gate, astatic account is preferred.

@rem <PRE>
* Zeus:Rexx/ZAmiMirror.rexx
@rem </PRE>

The Aminet archive is the biggest collection of non-commercial Amiga software and information in the world.  It is accessable on the InterNet using FTP from several sites and is constantly being added      to by the Amiga community.

ZAmiMirror is an ARexx script that downloads the latest files from the archive and uploads them to file areas on your BBS.

ZAmiMirror will work with both static and dynamic InterNet accounts.

@rem <PRE>
* ZPOP3Xfer
@rem </PRE>

ZPOP3Xfer transfers messages using the POP3 Internet mailbox format from the Internet to your hard drive, ready for processing with ZGate.

@rem <PRE>
* ZSMTPXfer
@rem </PRE>

ZSMTPXfer transfers messages using the SMTP to and from the Internet.

@rem <PRE>
* ZNewsXfer
@rem </PRE>

ZNewsXfer transfers messages with the NNTP protocol from the Internet to a file on your hard drive, ready for use with ZGate.


@{b}InterNet Configuration@{ub}

@{"Internet Configuration Window" Link "InternetConfig.gif/main"}

@{u}User Name@{uu} - If you have a dynamic InterNet account you must enter your mailbox name. Example If your mail address is zeusbbs@net.com then set this field to zeusbbs. If you have a static account, this field should contain nothing.

@{u}Address@{uu} - Your InterNet address.  If you have a dynamic account this will be the address of your InterNet provider. Example If your mail address is zeusbbs@net.com, you would enter net.com.

@{u}Organization@{uu} - our organization, if you have one, or your BBS name if you wish.  If this field is left blank, it will not be used.

@{u}News Receipt@{uu} - Some InterNet news systems require that new articles be submitted by Email.  If your provider works like  this then enter the destination address here.

@{u}Save Config@{uu} - Saves the configuration.  If Zeus is running, it will also be updated.

@{u}Close Gadget@{uu} - Quits the program. If changes have been made and you have not saved them, a requester will appear asking if you wish to save.



@{b}Options Window@{ub}

@{"Internet Options Window" Link "InternetOptions.gif/main"}

@{u}Gate Type@{uu} - Sets the kind of gate you wish to run

@{u}Local@{uu} - Only messages written on your BBS will be gated.  Any messages comming from other systems will be bounced back informing them of the situation.

@{u}Private@{uu} - Messages will only be gated if they came from your BBS or from a system listed in the 'Gate Access' list AND the user has be specified in the 'User Mapping' configuration.

@{u}Indexes@{uu} - ZGate keeps an index file of information about each mail and newsgroup article that it processes.  By specifying a low number into this field (minimum of100) you will save disk space but ZGates duplicate message detection and message linking functions will not work very well.  As a guide, you should set this field to the approximate number of InterNet messages you process in one week.


@{u}Disk Usage@{uu}:

@rem <PRE>
100 Indexes (Minimum)
1600 bytes (1.5kb)
1000 Indexes
16000 bytes (15.6kb)
10000 Indexes
160000 bytes (156.2kb)
1000000 Indexes
16000000 bytes (1.5mb)
@rem </PRE>

@{u}Your Addr@{uu} - Your FidoNet address.

@{u}Gate Addr@{uu} - The FidoNet address you have given to your InterNet gate.

@{u}Domain@{uu} - Usually this should be set to 'fidonet.org'.

@{u}Time Zone@{uu} - Your time zone.

@{u}GMT Offset@{uu} - The difference in hours from GMT to your time zone.

@{u}Gate Access@{uu} - If 'Gate Type' is set to Private or Public then this list becomes active.  It specifies the systems that may access your gate.  Entries are of the form You can use the wildcard character '*' for any of Zone, Net, Node or Point to allow multiple systems access without having to type all the addresses in.



Examples:

+2:441/58.72

 - Allow this point access.

+2:441/58.*

 - Allow all my points access.

+2:441/*.*

 - Allow all the nodes and points in net 441.

+2:441/*.*

 - Allow all nodes/points in net 441

-2:441/59.*

 - except node 59 and all his points.


By default, no systems have access so you don't need a entry of '-*:*/*.*'.

@{u}Add@{uu}: Add a new gate access entry.

@{u}Del@{uu}: Deletes the currently selected access entry.



@{b}Paths & Commands Window@{ub}

@{"Internet Commands Window" Link "InternetCommands.gif/main"}

@{u}News Dir@{uu} -  The directory which contains your newsgroup hierachy. This is usually 'UUNEWS:'.

@{u}Temp Dir@{uu} -  A directory where temporary files will be stored.  You should set this to 'T:' to speed up program execution.

@{u}Spool Dir@{uu} -  The directory where spool files are written.  Usually 'UUSPOOL:'.

@{u}Mail Dir@{uu} -  The directory which contains your mail boxes.  Usually 'UUMAIL:'.



The next three fields are used by ZGate to interface to your InterNet email and news setup.  See further on for example configurations.

@{u}Send News@{uu} -  Full path and command line of the program you use to post news articles to the InterNet.

@{u}Send Mail@{uu} -  Full path and command line of the program you use to post email to the InterNet.

@{u}RNews@{uu} -  Full path and command line of the program you use to process incoming news articles.



@{b}Headers Window@{ub}

@{"Internet Headers Window" Link "InternetHeaders.gif/main"}

Email and news articles contain many header lines of which only a few are actually needed by ZGate.  By default, ZGate reads its information from the header lines and then discards them.  If you would like certain header lines to be included in the message text then you can specify which ones in this window.

@{u}Add@{uu} - Adds a new header line entry.  If you only enter the beginning of a header line, ZGate will include all lines which begin with what you have entered.

@rem <PRE>
Examples:

From:
 - Will match 'From:'

From
 - Will match From:, Fromage:, etc..

X-
 - Will match all lines beginning with 'X-
@rem </PRE>

@{u}Delete@{uu} - Deletes the currently selected entry.

@{u}Port/Kludge@{uu} - Specifies how the currently selected header line will be added to the message text.

@{u}Port@{uu} - The line will appear at the top of the message text

@{u}Kludge@{uu} - The line will be hidden behind a FidoNet ^A kludge.


@{b}ZGate@{ub}

ZGate is basically a conversion utility that sits between your current InterNet setup and your BBS mail processor.  It was designed like this to give a lot of flexability in how email and newsgroup articles are processed.  For example:

The simplest use of ZGate is to convert email and articles to a form which can be imported into your BBS message areas using any FidoNet mail processor (although ZMP is preferred!).  This gives read only access to the InterNet for you and your users.

ZGate can of course work the other way: taking new messages from the BBS and converting them to emails and articles ready to be sent onto the InterNet.

Because ZGate converts messages to and from FidoNet packets, you can also link your points or other node systems into the areas, thus giving them access as well.

Please note that some InterNet providers will charge you extra if you want to start gating to other systems.

And finally, if you wanted to keep emails and articles in InterNet format, maybe for feeding to a local network over NNTP or SMTP, ZGate ill convert the messages to FidoNet format but won't delete the original files.

ZGate keeps two index files containing information from every email and newsgroup article it processes.  Because of this, it has duplicate message detection and advanced message linking abilities.


@{b}InterNet E-Mail to Zeus@{ub}

When emails are transfered from your InterNet mail host to your system, they end up as either mailbox files or individual messages depending on what software you use.  ZGate takes either format and converts them to FidoNet netmail packets in your inbound directory ready to be imported onto your BBS.

To convert a single email message, you use the GATEMAIL option with ZGate:

@rem <PRE>
CLI> ZGate GATEMAIL T:NewMsg.tmp [DELETE]
@rem </PRE>

The DELETE option tells ZGate to delete the email message if it was successful in converting it.

Converting a mailbox is equally as simple: just use the MAILBOX option:

@rem <PRE>
CLI> ZGate MAILBOX UUMail:zeus [DELETE]
@rem </PRE>


@{b}Zeus -> InterNet E-Mail@{ub}

To send an email from your BBS, you need to write a netmail with the To: field set to the receipients email address, and the destination FidoNet address set to the gate address you specified in the InterNet config.  When you export the message, the mail processor will create a FidoNet packet in your outbound which can then be imported by ZGate using the GATEPKT option:

@rem <PRE>
CLI> ZGate GATEPKT Outbound:00000000.PKT [DELETE]
@rem </PRE>

This process can be automated by setting up ZGate as an archiver!  If you are using ZMP then add the following entry into Prefs/Archivers:

@rem <PRE>
   Name    : ZGATE
   Compress: Zeus:Bin/ZGate GATEPKT ~f
   Extract : <Leave blank>
   Recog   : <Leave blank>
@rem </PRE>

In your ZMP.cfg, setup the gate SYSTEM like so:

@rem <PRE>
   SYSTEM .1 N3NNNNNBY GATE -NONE- -NONE- -NONE- <Group Numbers...>
@rem </PRE>

This example sets the gate address to .1, the archive netmail flag on, and the archiver type to GATE.  Now, when ZMP comes to archive some messages destined for the gate address, it automatically calls ZGate which processes the packet!



@{b}Newsgroup Configuration@{ub}

The InterNet configuration gives ZGate enough information to import and export email but, if you want it to process newsgroups, it needs a text config file, called ZGate.cfg, which defines the groups you want to gate and how they should be handled.

Since newsgroup tag names are usually quite long, ZGate supports mapping between newsgroup tag names and FidoNet tag names.  ZMP will happily process tags up to sixty characters long but other mail processing software may have problems.  If you will be gating newsgroups to other systems, or using a mail processor other than ZMP, you will probably need to define a shorter FidoNet tag for all your newsgroups.

A number of newsgroups have restrictions on who may post articles to them.  Some require that all new articles be sent to a moderator as email. If the moderator thinks that the article is relevant to the newsgroup, they ill post it for you.

Other newsgroups have a matching discussion group where people reply and alk about the articles in the main group.  These newsgroups use the same ag name with '.d' appended to signify a discussion group.

ZGate supports both of these restriction systems automatically once the relevant information has been entered into the ZGate.cfg file.  Here is an example of what the config looks like:

@rem <PRE>
;
; An example Zeus:Config/ZGate.cfg
;

;     <InterNet Tag> <FidoNet Tag>  [Moderator/Followup]

AREA  zeus.announce  ZEUS_ANNOUNCE  zeus@pavilion.co.uk   ; Moderated
AREA  zeus.news      ZEUS_NEWS      zeus.news.d           ; Followup
AREA  zeus.news.d    ZEUS_NEWSD                           ; Normal Group

;         <Filename>

XGROUPS   UULIB:active

; End of example
@rem </PRE>

As the example shows, you can place comments in the config by preceding them with a semi-colon ';'.  ZGate will also ignore blank lines.

The AREA keyword describes a single newsgroup and has the template:

@rem <PRE>
AREA <InterNet Tag> <FidoNet Tag> [Moderator/Followup]
@rem </PRE>

@{u}InterNet Tag@{uu} - The tag name of the newsgroup

@{u}FidoNet Tag@{uu}  - The tag name to use in FidoNet packets

@{u}Moderator/Followup@{uu} - If this argument is present, it specifies either a moderators email address to which all new articles will be posted, or a follow-up discussion newsgroup tag name.  ZGate decides which type of argument you have given by checking for a '@' character.  If it finds one, it assumes an email address.



To save adding all your newsgroups in by hand, you can use the XGROUPS keyword to specify a file which contains the groups you want ZGate to process.  The format of this file is simple:  one newsgroup tag per line like this:

@rem <PRE>
   zeus.announce
   zeus.news
   zeus.news.d
   <etc. etc.>
@rem </PRE>

Several external newsgroup processing utilities use a similar file format which, since ZGate doesn't change the file in any way, you can 'share' it between them.

Some utilities append other information after the newsgroup name in these files, like high and low message pointers, which makes the file look like this:

@rem <PRE>
   zeus.announce 1482 1266 n
   zeus.news 8273 6350 n
   zeus.news.d 17623 8232 n
   <etc. etc.>
@rem </PRE>

ZGate can still read this format since it only takes the first part of each line, stopping at any space or tab character.

The disadvantage of using the XGROUPS keyword is that no FidoNet tag mapping or moderator/followup information is present.  For the example, it is equivilent to the following AREA lines:

@rem <PRE>
   AREA zeus.announce zeus.announce
   AREA zeus.news     zeus.news
   AREA zeus.news.d   zeus.news.d
@rem </PRE>

So, if you want tag name mapping for all your newsgroups, you will still have to enter them all in as AREA lines.  If, however, you don't want to use tag name mapping, then you only need to use AREA lines for groups that have a moderator or follow-up newsgroup.



@{b}Newsgroups to Zeus@{ub}

When transfering newsgroup articles from the InterNet to your machine, some software will create a batch file containing all the articles whereas others store them as individual files.  The batch method is faster and less system intensive, but ZGate will handle both formats.

To convert a batch file you use the GATEBATCH option:

@rem <PRE>
CLI> ZGate GATEBATCH T:News.batch [DELETE]
@rem </PRE>

To convert a single newsgroup article, you use the GATENEWS option:

@rem <PRE>
CLI> ZGate GATENEWS T:News.article [DELETE]
@rem </PRE>

Some InterNet software doesn't store the article in a file but instead, 'feeds' it over stdio.  ZGate has the option POSTNEWS for this type of situation.

@rem <PRE>
CLI> ZGate POSTNEWS <T:News.article
@rem </PRE>



@{b}Zeus to Newsgroups@{ub}

Because Zeus generates the new articles as echomail, the setup for processing is the same for new email.  See section 3.2.



@{b}Example Configurations@{ub}

This section will explain in detail how to setup ZGate with several of the available email and newsgroup transfering packages around. It assumes that you already have the InterNet software installed and working.

INetUtils 1.4 for AmiTCP/AS225r2



@{b}ZGate to InterNet@{ub}

Although email will be stored in a temporary spool directory, news will not.  If you have a direct link to the InterNet or if you are running ZGate manually while connected, use these options:

@rem <PRE>
   Prefs/InterNet - Paths:

      Send News: NNTPpost ~f
      Send Mail: SMTPpost ~f
@rem </PRE>

Otherwise you can implement a simple version of news spooling by creating the directory 'Mail:NewsSpool' and using the following script:

@rem <PRE>
;
; AmiTCP:SendNews/StoreNews.script
;

.key NEWSFILE/A
.bra {
.ket }

Copy {NEWSFILE} Mail:NewsSpool/
Echo >>Mail:NewsSpool/SendNews.script "NNTPpost Mail:NewsSpool/{NEWSFILE} -x Mail:NewsSpool/{NEWSFILE}"
Delete {NEWSFILE}

; End of script
@rem </PRE>

Then you need to set the following in the InterNet configuration:

Prefs/InterNet - Paths:

@rem <PRE>
      Send News: Execute Mail:NewsSpool/StoreNews.script ~f
      Send Mail: SMTPpost -Q ~f
@rem </PRE>

This will create a script called 'Mail:NewsSpool/SendNews.script' which you should execute when you are next connected to the InterNet.  It will call NNTPpost for each spooled news article which in turn will post the message and then delete it if everything went well.



@{b}InterNet to ZGate@{ub}

To make NNTPxfer use ZGate to process incoming news articles, add this line to your S:User-Startup

@rem <PRE>
   SetEnv NNTPRNews Zeus:Bin/ZGate POSTNEWS
@rem </PRE>

Incoming email is best processed with SMTPpost to deliver it to the mailbox directory.  Once all mail has been transfered, run this script to make ZGate convert and delete all the mailboxes:

@rem <PRE>
.key MAILBOXDIR/A
.bra {
.ket }

List {MAILBOXDIR} FILES LFORMAT="Zeus:Bin/ZGate MAILBOX %s%s DELETE" >T:Temp
Execute T:Temp
Delete T:Temp
@rem </PRE>

Gate Access:  If 'Gate Type' is set to Private or Public then this list becomes active.  It specifies the systems that may access your gate.  Entries are of the form:




@{b}ZAmiMirror@{ub}


@{i}What is Aminet?@{ui}

Only the largest collection of Amiga software, data and information in the world!  It lives on the Internet, so, if you don't have an InterNet account, this program will not be of much use to you.

There are a wide range of files which are stored in a hierarchical directory tree by the (nice) people who administrate the Aminet.  These are available for free and, since it usually contains all the latest public domain and shareware products, it is very popular with Amiga owners.


@{i}What is an Aminet Mirror?@{ui}

The Aminet exists on several systems throughout the InterNet.  These are called Mirrors since each machine has an identical copy of all the files contained on all the other Aminet mirror systems.  Since so many people access the Aminet everyday, one single system would not be able to cope.

Another advantage to having several sites is that you can connect to a system 'near' you and get faster TCP/IP responses than if you were having to drag data from the other side of the world.

Using this program, your Zeus system can become an Aminet 'mini-mirror', taking in only a few directories, or a full blown mirror, taking in every directory.  Obviously the choice comes down to storage space and how much time you actually want to spend logged into the InterNet.  If you have a 64k ISDN line linked to the InterNet 24 hours a day and a 15Gb hard drive, then you might want to go the whole hog...


@{i}How does ZAmiMirror.rexx work?@{ui}

It interfaces to the InterNet using the File Transfer Protocol (FTP) client NcFTP which comes as part of the AmiTCP package, but is available from the Aminet (of course).  ZAmiMirror has not been tried with any other FTP packages as they do not have the features needed by this program.

Basically, it works like this:

 - Download a list of the new files available
 - Scan through the list, noting which files are wanted.
 - Download the files.
 - If the files have been downloaded successfully, upload them to the matching Zeus BBS file areas.


@{i}Setting up ZAmiMirror@{ui}

1. This is not a simple task but by following the steps below you should not have any problems.  If you do encounter problems with the FTP side of things and are not confident with NcFTP, you should seek help from someone who is.

2. First of all you need a working InterNet setup.  If you haven't got it working properly yet then stop reading this and go sort it out!

3. Next you need to find the closest reliable Aminet mirror.  For the purposes of this document we shall use the Imperial Collages site in the Uk - its address is sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk'.

4. Decide where on your system you want to store your Aminet mirror.  Make a directory there called 'Aminet'.  We shall use 'DH3:' as an example.

5. Load up Zeus:Rexx/ZAmiMirror.rexx into your text editor and take a look at the user variable section.  It looks something like this:

@rem <PRE>
 Base     = 'DH3:Aminet/'
 AmiAddr  = 'sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk'
 SysAddr  = 'phoenix.doc.ic.ac.uk'
 AmiDir   = 'pub/aminet'
 MaxSize  = 1024000
 RecName  = 'ADT_RECENT_7'
 LogFile  = 'Logs:ZAmiMirror.log'
 FullTree = 'No'
@rem </PRE>

6. Edit the 'Base' line to reflect where your Aminet directory is.  Don't forget the slash '/' at the end.

7. Put the address of your chosen Aminet mirror site into 'AmiAddr'.

 'SysAddr' and 'AmiDir' will be covered later...

8. Set the 'MaxSize' variable.  Files that are larger than 'MaxSize' will      not be downloaded.

 RecName' is the filename of the recent files list on your chosen Aminet      mirror site.  It comes in two flavours:

@rem <PRE>
 ADT_RECENT_7  - New files in the past seven days
 ADT_RECENT_14 - New files in the past forteen days
@rem </PRE>

9. Choose a name and location for the ZAmiMirror log file and set 'LogFile' accordingly.

10. If you want to mirror all of the Aminets directories then set 'FullTree' to 'Yes'

11. Save the script at this point.

12. Log into the InterNet and get a AmigaDOS shell ready.

13. Type 'CD DH3:Aminet' (or wherever your Aminet directory is).

14. Type 'NcFTP sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk' (or whatever your Aminet site is).

15. When connected and the NcFTP prompt appears it should look something like this:

@rem <PRE>
 phoenix.doc.ic.ac.uk:/
 ncftp>
@rem </PRE>

 Although you connected to 'sunsite.doc.ic.ac.uk', the site name is actually 'phoenix.doc.ic.ac.uk' and this must be entered into the 'SysAddr' variable.

 If the site name is the same as the address in 'AmiAddr', you still need to set 'SysAddr'.

16. Type 'cd pub/aminet'

 If the prompt now looks like this:

@rem <PRE>
 phoenix.doc.ic.ac.uk:/pub/aminet
 ncftp>
@rem </PRE>

 Then 'AmiDir' is correct.  If the site complains that the directory does not exist then you will have to find the 'aminet' directory and set 'AmiDir' accordingly.

17. Type 'cd info/adt' and then 'get TREE' which will download a list of all he current Aminet directories to a file called 'TREE' in your Aminet directory.

18. Type 'dir ADT_RECENT_*'

19. If you see 'ADT_RECENT_7.Z' then this Aminet site supports 'GZip' compressed files.  If you have GZip on your system then add the '.Z' extension to 'RecName'.  (Example: RecName = 'ADT_RECENT_7.Z')

20. If you want to mirror all the Aminet directories then skip to step 27

21. If the file transfered successfully then type 'exit' and shut down your InterNet connection.

22. Load the TREE file into your text editor.  It should look something like this:

@rem <PRE>
 new           Upload area
 priv          Private uploads
 recent        Files uploaded the last seven days
 biz           Business software
 biz/dbase     Data base software
 biz/demo      Demo versions of commercial software
 biz/misc      Misc business type soft
 biz/patch     Commercial software patches
 comm          Communications
 comm/bbs      BBS programs
 :   :          :    :
 [Lots more directories]
 :   :          :    :
@rem </PRE>

23. Remove the 'new', 'priv' and 'recent' lines.

24. Go through the list and delete all the directories you do not want to mirror.

25. Save the file.

 If you do not want the files automatically uploaded to your Zeus file areas then skip to step 30.

26. You need to create a file area for every Aminet directory you wish to mirror.  Fortunately, this can be automated with the included 'TreeToCfg.rexx' script.

27. In the shell, type 'rx Zeus:Rexx/TreeToCfg <Dir> <Area>' where <Dir> is your Aminet directory (Same as the 'Base' variable) and <Area> is the starting file area number.

28. If all went well, type 'Zeus:Bin/UpdateConfigs FA' to reload the file area configuration.  You will also need to edit your SIG and Template configs at some point to give your users access to the new areas.

29. Make sure you have saved all the changes to ZAmiMirror.rexx.

30. Thats it!  To start the program, log into the InterNet, and, once connected, type 'rx Zeus:Rexx/ZAmiMirror' into a shell.



@endnode




@node Manual.SIG "10 - Special Interest Groups"

@{b}@{u}Chapter 10 - Special Interest Groups@{uu}@{ub}

Special Interest Groups allow the SysOp to separate the message and file areas on the BBS into distinct topics which may include both message and file areas.This feature is useful when you have more file or message areas and want to group them together to make finding the right area easier for your areas.

Let's imagine our BBS is split up into three distinct groups of interest.

  @{i}AmiNet files for download@{ui}

  @{i}Information about herbal remedies@{ui}

  @{i}Support for the YARGLE(tm) software.@{ui}

For each SIG's there may be some file areas or message areas, and our

Message Area configuration looks like this:

@rem <pre>
[  100] AmiNet New Files
[  200] Herbal Remedy Recipes
[  201] Discussion about innovations in the Herbal
        Remedy field.
[  202] Herbalists General Chat.
[  300] YARGLE(tm) betatesters echo
[  301] YARGLE(tm) users echo
[  302] YARGLE(tm) general chat
@rem </pre>

And the File Area Configuration may look like this:

@rem <pre>
[  100] AmiNet comm/bbs
[  101] AmiNet comm/fido
[  102] AmiNet comm/mail
    ::    ::    ::   ::   more AmiNet areas.

[  200] Herbal recipes (archived with .ZIP)
[  300] YARGLE(tm) betatester updates
[  301] YARGLE(tm) support files
@rem </pre>

These are not huge lists, but it makes more sense to be split up into separate
groups:

@rem <pre>
AmiNet
 AmiNet New Files
 AmiNet comm/bbs
 AmiNet comm/fido
 AmiNet comm/mail

Herbal Remedies
 Herbal Remedy Recipes
 Discussion about innovations...
 Herbalists General Chat
 Herbal recipes (archived with .ZIP)

YARGLE(tm)
 YARGLE(tm) betatesters echo
 YARGLE(tm) users echo
 YARGLE(tm) general chat
 YARGLE(tm) betatester updates
 YARGLE(tm) support files
@rem </pre>

This setup makes it easier for the user to pinpoint exactly what they want and resembles a directory structure system familiar to all computer users.

In a similar way to a file system, Zeus allows multi-levels of directories.

@{b}Configuring SIGs@{ub}

@{"SIG Configuration Window" Link "SIGConfig.gif/main"}

Each SIG has various items of configuration data to be set:

@{u}Tag@{uu} - The "tagname" of the SIG. This name will be the "key" for user's to type when selecting which SIG they wish to access, rather than by a conventional numbering system. This should be less than 8 characters long. For multi-levelled SIG's they can be represented in a way similar to directories "e.g. AMINET/BBS" would access the SIG named BBS located within the AMINET SIG.

@{u}Description@{uu} - The description of the SIG. This should be less than 40 characters.

@{u}Low@{uu} - The lowest access level necessary to access this SIG. This value has no bearing upon the access to the areas within it.

@{u}High@{uu} - The highest access level necessary to access this SIG.

Even if you have not configured any SIG's you will already have one set up on the BBS. It's name is "GLOBAL" and contains all your file and message areas.Load up the SIG Editor (Special Interest Groups from the Config->Messages and Config->Files menu or Prefs/SigEditor) and select "GLOBAL". You will see the "Default" checkbox is set on. This means that whenever a new area is added to the BBS it will automatically be added to this SIG definition. A new user logging into the BBS will have the GLOBAL SIG attributed to their user account by default.

@{i}How do SIG's work?@{ui}

Each user has two SIG settings, one for files and one for messages. However, a user selecting a SIG which contains both file and message areas will have both their File SIG and their Message SIG change.

Conversely, a user selecting a SIG with only message areas attributed to it will only have their Message SIG changed.

@{i}Attributing an Area to a SIG@{ui}

After selecting the SIG you wish to edit, the two listviews displaying the complete list of file areas and the list of message areas are activated.Clicking upon the area will attribute the area to a SIG when the check icon is displayed, when the check icon disappears the area is not attributed to the area. If you wish to add or remove more than one area at one time menu items are provided for this:

@rem <pre>
File ->     Add all Areas
            Remove all Areas
            -------------------
            Copy range...
            Match string...

Messages -> Add all Areas
            Remove all Areas
            -------------------
            Copy range...
            Match string...
@rem </pre>

Add all Areas -Attributes all the file or message areas on the BBS to the currently selected SIG.

Remove all Areas - De-attributed all the file or message areas on the BBS to the currently selected SIG.

Copy range - Attributes a certain "range" of areas to the current SIG. Input to this function may contain the standard range formatting commands (1-39,4,6 etc.)

Match string - Attributes all areas which descriptive name match the wildcard pattern entered. This function accepts all AmigaDOS wildcards and is not case-sensitive, e.g. #?Zeus#? would match "Zeus Updates", "Zeus Doors" and "comm/zeus"

You should set up your SIG's once you have set up your message and file areas correctly. Firstly split up the different catagories of your BBS into separate sections linked together by a subject or topic.

@{b}Setting up example SIGs@{ub}

Here is an example file area and message area configuration:

@rem <pre>
 File Areas                  Message Areas

 [100] AmiNet comm/bbs    [100] Latest AmiNet uploads
 [101] AmiNet comm/dlg
 [102] AmiNet comm/fido   [200] Ancient Greek history
 [103] AmiNet comm/mail         discussion
 [104] AmiNet comm/tcp    [201] Ancient Norweigan
 [105] AmiNet comm/zeus         mythology
                          [202] The Bronze Age era
                          [203] Henry VIII - artist
                                or fat bloke?
 [110] AmiNet dev/asm
 [110] AmiNet dev/c       [300] Neighbours discussion
 [111] AmiNet dev/e       [301] Home & Away discussion
 [112] AmiNet dev/gui     [302] Eastenders plot
 [113] AmiNet dev/misc          giveaways!
 [200] Pictures of Amiga Tech
       employees nude.
 [300] Pictures of Coronation
       Street stars nude.
 [900] Pictures of rare birds.
 [500] Uploads
@rem </pre>

From this list we can pick out four distinct catagories, the AmiNet, Pictures,
History and TV Soaps.

Load up the SIG Configuration and click ADD four times.

Replace the (new) entries with:

@rem <pre>
   Name: AMINET
   Desc: The AmiNet Software Archive
    Low: 0
   High: 255

Default: No
   Name: PICTURES
   Desc: Pictures of rare and exotic things!
    Low: 0
   High: 255

Default: No
   Name: HISTORY
   Desc: Discussion of all things history!
    Low: 0
   High: 255

Default: No
   Name: TV
   Desc: Television- view of the world or boring tosh?
    Low: 0
   High: 255
Default: No
@rem </pre>

Select the "AMINET" SIG. Select "Copy range..." from the Files menu and enter 100-113 in the box to add all the AmiNet areas.

Select the "PICTURES" SIG. Select "Match string..." from the Files menu and enter "Picture#?" to add all the Picture related areas.

Keep going for the other two SIGs...

We may think that file area 300 is worthy of being in two SIGs, PICTURES and TV. Select the "TV" SIG and select area 300 from the file area listview to add this in.


@{b}Access Restrictions@{ub}

This section is concerned with restricting access of the BBS and the file and message data contained within to users. Information on how to restrict login access to the BBS can be found in Chapter Configuring your lines, Section Line Access.

@{i}Access Levels@{ui}

Every user on the BBS is assigned an access level in the range of 0 to 255.Conventions dictate that 0 refers to a new user, where 255 is reserved for the local SysOp. When a new user logs into the BBS they are automatically assigned level 0.

@{i}The Design of the Access Level System@{ui}

This is the process that Zeus goes through to determine whether a user has
access to a file or message area:

@rem <PRE>
Is the users access greater than the low access definition?

If not, no access to area.

Is the users access less than the high access definition?

If not, no access to area.

Is the message/file area defined in the ranges in the Template Configuration for
this particular access level?

If not, no access to area.

Is the Access flag set?

If not, no access to area.

Is the user old enough to access this area?

If not, no access to area.

Is the user the right gender to access this area?

If yes - @{i}Access granted to area.@{ui}
@rem </PRE>

@{b}Low and High Access Definitions@{ub}

These fields have the highest priority over-ride all over the other access definitions. If you set a file area's low access level field to 10 then new user's may not access level even if the area has been defined in the Template Configuration ranges.


@endnode



@node Manual.Templates "11 - Templates"

@{b}@{u}Chapter 11 - Template Configuration@{uu}@{ub}

The Template Configuration allows the most precise restrictions to be placed on the BBS. There are three distinct parts to the Template Configuration:

 - User Limits

 - Message Area Definitions

 - File Area Definitions

The Template Configuration may be accessed by running Prefs/Templates, or selecting Users->Configuration->Templates menu on the Control Screen.

@{"Template Window" Link "TemplateConfig.gif/main"}

@{i}User Limits@{ui}

User Limits allow the SysOp to limit the amount of time spent on the BBS each
day, regarding the number of files that may be downloaded each day; the number
they may download in ratio to the number of files that they upload, and the
maximum number of messages the user may write per day.

For each access level defined in the Template Configuration they may be another
set of user limits. You may edit the user limits by pressing the

"Edit User Limits" button:

@{"Template Limits Window" Link "TemplateLimits.gif/main"}

@{u}Calls/Day@{uu}
 The maximum number of calls a user may make per day. "0" indicates the user may log on as many times as desired.

@{u}Mins/Call@{uu}
 The maximum amount of time in minutes a user may spend online per call. "1440" would give the user access to the BBS for a full 24hrs a day.

@{u}Mins/Day@{uu}
 The maximum amount of time in minutes a user may spend online every day. "1440" would give the user access to the BBS for a full 24hrs a day.

@{u}File Ratio@{uu}
 The number of files a user may download for every one they upload. A value of "10" would set the ratio at 1:10 meaning that they may download 10 files for every one they upload. "0" gives them unlimited File Access.

@{u}Byte Ratio@{uu}
 The number of bytes a user may download for every byte they upload. "0" gives them unlimited Byte Access.

@{u}Max Bytes@{uu}
 The maximum number of bytes they may download every day. "0" means there is no restriction on download.

@{u}Max Files@{uu}
 The maximum number of files they may download every day. "0" means there is no restriction on download.

@{u}Free Files@{uu}
 The number of "free" files they are allowed to download before the File Ratio field becomes active. A typical value would be "10" with a file ratio of 1:10. Giving a user 0 free files means they must upload before they can download.

@{u}Free Bytes@{uu}
 The number of "free" bytes they are allowed to download before the Byte Ratio field becomes active.

@{u}Max Msgs@{uu}
 The number of messages a user may write per day. "0" indicated unlimited write access.


Simply changing the values in the User Limits Value will not affect the user's account data. If you wish to update all the users' access levels to new levels then press the "Update User Limits" button. A window will pop-up showing the user names as they are being processed.

@{"Template Updating Window" Link "TemplateUpdate.gif/main"}

This function can also be acheived through the ARexx script "Zeus:Rexx/SetLimits.rexx"


@{b}Area Definitions@{ub}

The main window of the Template Configuration is concerned with attributing "access types" to ranges of areas. This means that different "access types" (allow access, allow download etc.) can be set for whole ranges of areas at a time, making it easy for you to partition your file and message area list.

Once you have created an access level, or selected an existing one you can add and delete ranges of areas to the "access list", which is represented by the large listview in the middle of the window. Each area range defined for the currently selected access level will be shown here, along with the "access types" assigned to it.

@{i}Access Types@{ui}

There are 12 access flags for message areas and file areas.

A '-' character as an access type indicates that the area is set off, where a "access letter" shows shows that the access flag is set on. Pressing the according buttons will toggle the flag of the currently selected access range.

Ranges defined do not necessarily need to cover existing message areas. The range "1-1000" is a legitimate range even if only area 4, 5 and 50 exist currently. The ranges will apply to new areas defined after the template configuration was set.

For file areas the following tags are available to be set:

@{"File Tags Window" Link "TemplateFileTags.gif/main"}

Descriptor in Window
 Letter Tag
 Description

A
 A
 The user may access this area.

V
 V
 The user may view files in this area.

D
 D
 The user may download files in this area. Providing the user's access allows
them enough file ratio and credits to access the file they may transfer files
from this area to their local storage.

U
 U
 The user may upload files in this area providing the area definition supports
uploading to this area (see Section File Area Configuration) and there is enough
space left on the BBS hard drive.

EO
 O
 The user may edit the description of files they have uploaded.

EA
 A
 The user may edit all files. The user may change the description of any files
in this file area regardless of whether they uploaded it. This flag should only
be granted to trusted user's and SysOp's in most cases

UV
 u
 The user may access unvalidated files and the user may list, download, edit and
delete (providing the correct flags are set) files that have not be validated by
the SysOp after uploading.

D
 d
 The user may delete the file catalogue entry and the physical files in this
area.

VA
 v
 The user may validate files. The user may validate files uploaded to this
area.This flag is generally coupled with the UV flag.

S
 S
 The user has SysOp privelidges in this area, useful for defining a specific
access level for SigOp's (special SysOp's that manage and control a particular
area of the BBS)

M
 M
 The user is masked out of the BBS by default.

P
 P
 The user has pack access in this area. When using an offline grabber they will
by default have this area selected for downloading.


For message areas the following tags are available to be set:

@{"Template Message Tags Window" Link "TemplateMsgTags.gif/main"}


Descriptor in Window
 Letter Tag
 Description

A
 A
 The user may access this area. This area will show up when the user lists file
areas.

R
 R
 The user may read and scan public messages and private messages addressed to
them, or writing by them in this area

W
 W
 The user may write messages in this area. Under the constraints of the Message
Area Configuration (see Section Message Area Configuration) the user may post
messages to other users or "ALL" in this area.

WP
 P
 The user may write private messages in this area. This flag overrides the
"Private Base" flag defined in the Message Area Configuration and is generally
used only as a privelidged access type.

PR
 V
 The user may read private messages not addressed to, or written by themselves.
This flag is generally only granted to SysOp's for monitoring of the nature of
the conversations taken place. User's do not take kindly to their private
messages being read so this flag should be kept for the exclusive use of the
SysOp or SigOp in most cases.

KO
 K
 This flag allows the user to mark messages written by them as deleted (NB this
does not remove the message from the storage physically).

KA
 L
 The user mark any message in the area as deleted. In general this flag should
only be granted to SysOp's or SigOp's.

CN
 C
 The user may send crash netmails. This flag only applies in "Netmail bases" as
defined in the Message Area Configuration. The definition of a Crash Netmail can
be found in Section x.xx Netmail Types

FA
 F
 The user has file attach access. This flag allows the user to assign one or
more physical files to the message for distribution over the BBS or mail
network.This flag should only be granted "en masse" to local message areas and
should be restricted to the SysOp for distributed networks.

S
 S
 The user has SysOp privelidges in this area, useful for defining a specific
access level for SigOp's (special SysOp's that manage and control a particular
area of the BBS)

M
 M
 The user is masked out of the BBS by default.

P
 P
 The user has pack set in this area, upon using an offline grabber they will
by default have this area selected for downloading.

You may wish to use the [A-----------] flag set for new user's to the BBS, so they can see what is available on the BBS but not be able to interact with it.


@{b}Updating Template Configuration@{ub}

Changes made in the Template Editor will only affect user's when the online configuration has been updated, or when Zeus has been reloaded.

Upon quitting the template editor a requester will pop-up asking whether you wish to update the online configuration. Selecting to update the online configuration has the same effect as "UpdateConfigs TEMPLATES" (see section Bin/UpdateConfigs).


@{b}Editing access user-by-user@{ub}

More intricate configuration can be acheived upon certain users' access flags by using the UserEditor. Although the access level system affects the entire user base, any changes of the access flags from within the UserEditor will remain constant when changing the Template Configuration.

e.g. If we defined an Access Level 100 [Special User] from within the Template Configuration with the following access groups.

[M] [1-1000] [ARW----------]

[F] [1-1000] [AVDU---------]

Then we assigned user "Joe Normal" to this access group using the UserEditor.When asked if we wish to "Assign Template Limits" we select YES and the correct area definitions are copied to his account. We can verify this by looking in the "Messages" window of UserEditor.

Now if we wanted to give him Crash Netmail access to area 30 - FidoNet netmail but we did not want every user who had access 100 to be able to send Crash Netmails we could select area 30 from the UserEditor and click on the Crash Netmail checkbox.

Saving this user account and quitting the UserEditor would mean he could instantly write Crash Netmails now in that area. However, what if we changed the Template Configuration to have the access group:

[M] [1-1000] [ARW---O------]

Would Joe Normal lose his Crash Netmail setting? No, he wouldn't. All "changes" to his message or file area account are saved in his user data and respected after any Template changes.


@{b}Typical Access Flags@{ub}

Typical flag accesses' for access levels are as follows:

@{i}New User@{ui}:

Messages: [AR----------]

Files:    [AV----------]

@{i}Normal User@{ui}:

Messages: [ARW---------]

Files:    [AVDU--------]

@{i}SigOp@{ui}:

Messages: [ARWPVKL-F--P]

Files:    [AVDUOEudv---]

@{i}SysOp@{ui}:

Messages: [ARWPVKLCFSMP]

Files:    [AVDUOEUdvSMP]


@{b}Resetting all Template Changes@{ub}

In case you wish to flush out any changes you have made to user's, the ARexx script "PurgeXData" is supplied. For more information on how user's XData works.

Usage: PurgeXData <XData> [Access Level]

To flush out all the changes to every user's message area account you would run it in the following manner:

1> rx Zeus:Rexx/Users/PurgeXData.rexx MCHG

To flush out all the file area changes to all users will access level 0 the following line would be run:

1> rx Zeus:Rexx/Users/PurgeXData.rexx FCHG 0


@{b}An example BBS Configuration@{ub}

For a simple BBS, three access levels should suffice and are set up on the
distribution disks provided with Zeus.

Let's assume we have set up the file areas so they fall within the following bounds:

Area 1
 Local Announcement Area, all users should have PACK access to this automatically.

Areas 2-500
 All areas falling within this range are of unrestricted access to user's, new users can access and view these areas.

Areas 501-1000
 Only validated users should be able to access these areas (software support or privelidged information for example)

Areas 1001-2000
 For the SysOp's private use.

We would set up the Template Configuration in the following way.

@rem <pre>
[  0] - New User
                [M] [  2-500 ]  [AR----------]
                [F] [  2-500 ]  [AV----------]
                [M] [  1-1   ]  [AR---------P]

[ 10] - Validated User
                [M] [  2-1000]  [ARW---------]
                [F] [  2-1000]  [AVDU--------]
                [M] [  1-1   ]  [ARW--------P]

[255] - SysOp
                [M] [  2-2000]  [ARWPVKLCFSMP]
                [F] [  2-2000]  [AVDUOEUdvSMP]
@rem </pre>


@endnode


@node Manual.ARexx "12 - Getting started with ARexx and Zeus"

@{b}@{u}Chapter 12 - Getting started with ARexx and Zeus@{uu}@{ub}

@{i}Written by Andrew Rooney@{ui}

@{b}What is Arexx?@{ub}

ARexx is an very flexible high level scripting language used to manipulate and control other programmes. Communication is done by sending information though message ports. Many pieces of Amiga software have an ARexx port. By using ARexx with other software, you can automate or perform new tasks by using combinations of the ARexx functions the software supports.

ARexx is usually an optional extension to a program. Zeus, however, requires the use of ARexx to change the look and feel of your BBS.

@{b}Why Arexx with Zeus?@{ub}

Zeus uses an extremely powerful set of extended ARexx commands. The way your BBS appears is dependant upon the code within your own set of Arexx scripts.The Zeus ARexx command set allows you to create your BBS according to your own tastes, due to the almost infinite combinations of commands and the powerful language structure ARexx provides. The "look and feel" of the BBS is entirely up to you. After becoming familiar with Zeus you will soon see how Zeus BBS breaks down the barriers created by old-generation BBS software.

Zeus allows you design your BBS the way YOU want it. You are only limited by your imagination!

@{b}How Do I Use Arexx?@{ub}

Arexx is invisible. If you have installed it an introductory message when RexxMast is run is the closest you will come to seeing it running.RexxMast is a server that allows Arexx to function. Arexx scripts (usually ending in .rexx) can be started using the command Rx. However, Zeus runs internal Zeus scripts automatically without any interaction on your part.

If you are looking for the files "Rexxmast" and "Rx" the paths for the files are "Sys:Rexxc/Rx" and "Sys:System/RexxMast".

In order to write your Arexx programmes you will require a good text editor. The type of editor can be important when it comes to writing BBS software you will want to add ANSI colour codes, CygnusEd is the best, but it is a commerical programme and not available as shareware. There are many available on the AmiNet in the text/edit directory.

@{b}Format of a Zeus Arexx Script@{ub}

All Zeus Arexx scripts have a few specific similarities. A few simple guidelines will help you get on your way to creating your own scripts.

Zeus requires a few important keywords to be placed at the beginning of your scripts.

The first line must be a comment:

@rem <pre>
/* Comment string */
@rem </pre>

All Arexx scripts require a comment line at the beginning. Comment lines start with the characters /* and end with */. If they are not present the Arexx server will not recognize it as an Arexx programme and will report an error, such as "Command returned 5/1: Program not found". If the scripts was launched by Zeus the error will appear in the ZeusError.log file within your Log Directory.

Within the comment braces you should put a description of what the script does.

After the comment the next line should be:

@rem <pre>
Parse Arg Line
@rem </pre>

The above line of text is very important for the Zeus functions to operate properly. This line puts the current line number the script is running on in the variable Line. For most Zeus ARexx functions to work the Lineargument must be present.

The next line should be:

@rem <pre>
Options Results
@rem </pre>

This text, commonly the 3rd line in every Zeus Arexx script is extremely important. Without it, nearly all Zeus Arexx functions will fail. This allows functions to return information to you in a variable called "RESULT" and plays a key role in making your script work. This is explained later in the chapter "Results, Strings, Variables, and Return Codes".

To recap:

@rem <pre>
/* My First Zeus Arexx Script! */

Parse Arg Line

Options Results

Running your Zeus Arexx Script
@rem </pre>

The Arexx scripts that you write are not compiled such as a programme written in C or Assembler. Instead they are interpreted. A "standard" Arexx script, one which does not use any non-asynchronous Zeus Arexx commands (see Chapter Arexx Command Set) could be run with the command:

@rem <pre>
Rx HelloWorld.rexx
@rem </pre>

Where HelloWorld.rexx was:

@rem <pre>
/* HelloWorld.rexx */

say 'Hello, world'
@rem </pre>

When you are running a Zeus Arexx script you do not need to issue the Rx command as Zeus will interpret your script for you. Zeus will always begin and end it's script sequence with the scripts Zeus:Rexx/Local.zeus or Zeus:Rexx/Remote.zeus as explained later on.

@{b}"Hello World" Example@{ub}

Load up your text editor and type the following into the window:

@rem <pre>
/* Example Script "Hello World.Zeus" */

Parse Arg Line

Options Results

ClrScr

Write '"Hello World!\n\n"'

WaitReturn

/* End Example Script */
@rem </pre>

Now Save it as "HelloWorld.zeus" in your Zeus:Scripts/ directory, and then add the following text to the end of Zeus:Scripts/Main/MainMenu.zeus

@rem <pre>
CMD_9:

CallScript 'HelloWorld'

Signal MenuLoop
@rem </pre>

Then when you select option '9' from your BBS menu it will then clear the screen and display something similiar to:

@rem <pre>
Hello World!

Press RETURN to continue
@rem </pre>

@{b}Why Your Arexx Script Will Not Work@{ub}

Check the following first:

 - Is RexxMast Running?

 - Did you add the rexxsupport.library in your startup-sequence

 - Are you executing it from you BBS menu properly?

 - Check spelling and other annoying errors.

 - Are FileControl and MsgControl Running?

If these lines of enquiry prove unsuccessful then it is time to start going through your code. The best way to begin debugging is to remember where exactly in your programme that the error happened. Then you should check your logfile called Zeus:Logs/ZeusError.log. The error log is not a 100% accurate method of debugging, but it will give you an idea of what is going on.If the error log tells you you have an unmatched quote, then you must go through each line checking for quotes that are not completed.

Example:

@rem <pre>
'"This is a correctly quoted string"'

'"This is NOT a correctly quoted string"
@rem </pre>

There are many possible errors with Arexx, but the best way is to write code a few lines at a time and checking they work until you build up more confidence.It is important to read your Arexx script character by character.

Eventually Arexx scripting will become quite natural.

Another good way to check for errors and when the occur is to run Zeus:Prefs/Startup and remove the line that starts up the BBSLine on node 0. Start Zeus again with a reboot. Line 0 will not be active (you will not be able to login locally). You can manually start the line from shell.

@rem <pre>
1> Zeus:Bin/BBSLine 0 local.zeus
@rem </pre>

While line 0 is in use, any Arexx errors encountered will be echoed to the shell you started BBSLine from in realitime.

@{b}Results, Strings, Variables, and Return Codes@{ub}

@{u}Strings@{uu}

Strings are anything, they can contain numbers, letters or any printable character. They can be of any length.

@rem <pre>
MyString = 'Hello World!'
@rem </pre>

Would place the words Hello World! into a variable called MyString.

@{u}Variables@{uu}

In Arexx, if you would like to store the string "Hello World!" as a variable, you would do the following in your text editor:

@rem <pre>
/* Making a String! */

Parse Arg Line

Options Results

string = 'Hello World!'  /* Create the String  */
ClrScr                   /* Clear the Screen   */
Write '"'string'\n\n"'   /* Display the string */
WaitReturn               /* Wait for a Return  */

/* End Making a string */
@rem </pre>

Now add it to your Menu and try it with Zeus.

The result of this example does the same thing as the first Hello World Example script, only using a variable string, instead of a constant string.

Another type of variable you may find that is used quite frequently is an array variable. These variables are made up of two parts and will look similiar to VARIABLE.EXT

Where VARIABLE is the actual variable and EXT is the numbered extension.

Some Examples:

@rem <pre>
Variable.1 = 'Hello '
Variable.2 = 'World'

Do i = 1 to 2
 Write '"'Variable.i'"'
End

Write '"\n\n"'
WaitReturn
@rem </pre>

The result of this example would output:

@rem <pre>
Hello World

Press RETURN to continue
@rem </pre>

@{u}Results@{uu}

In order to use the RESULT from an Arexx function, you must add the line "Options Results" to the top of your programme. This is very important when writing Zeus Arexx programmes. RESULT is a special variable that is created every time you run a Zeus Arexx function and is used to return information you have requested.

Example:

@rem <pre>
/* Get the user's name */

Parse Arg Line

Options Results

GetUserData 'NAME'  /* The Zeus Arexx function! After
                       this function is used it will
                       store the user's name in the
                       variable called RESULT */

UserName = Result   /* Now we make the variable UserName equal to RESULT */

Write '"You are 'UserName'\n\n"'
WaitReturn

/* End Username Example */
@rem </pre>

After you run this example from Zeus, it will show you something similiar to:

@rem <pre>
You are Andrew Rooney

Press RETURN to Continue
@rem </pre>

@{u}Return Codes@{uu}

Return codes work exactly the same way that RESULT codes do, only this time the variable is called "RC" and not "RESULT". Once again, the variable RC is created automatically each time you run a Zeus Arexx function. If you look in the chapter ARexx Command Set you will see that GetUserData will return two different return codes (RCs), 0 if everything went OK, or a number greater than zero (>0) if something went wrong.

Example:

@rem <pre>
/* Get the user's name */

Parse Arg Line

Options Results

GetUserData 'NAME'
UserName = Result

/* Check if the RC is >0, if so, something went wrong! */

If RC > 0 then Write '"Something went wrong! Could not get your name!\n\n"'
/* If everything went OK, then write what we want to
   see */
Else Write '"You are 'UserName'\n\n"'

WaitReturn
@rem </pre>

If this programme was to fail (not likely), you would see:

@rem <pre>
Something went wrong! Could not get your name!

Press RETURN to continue
@rem </pre>

However, if everything went fine, you would see the original example's output of:

@rem <pre>
You are Andrew Rooney

Press RETURN to continue
@rem </pre>

@{b}Formatting Strings@{ub}

Most Zeus functions require a certain format when strings are involved. Because the inputs to Zeus Arexx functions may contain strings or keywords, Zeus Arexx functions requires separate pieces of information sent to it to be all in one string and therefore enclosed in single quotes.

@rem <pre>
'This is a single quoted string'
@rem </pre>

Using the Zeus command Write if you used the string in it's present state you would only see the following:

@rem <pre>
Write 'This is a single quoted string'

Result: THIS
@rem </pre>

Placing the string in double quotes, the same result will occur:

@rem <pre>
Write "This is a single quoted string"

Result: THIS
@rem </pre>

In order to display the entire string, you must first close it within double quotes then single quotes:

@rem <pre>
Write '"This is a dual quoted string"'

Result: This is a dual quoted string
@rem </pre>

In many cases, you will want to display a variable created in your script and use it with other constant string information. When this instance arises, you must place the variable only within single quotes.

@rem <pre>
ExpandCC '"%50|"'
Variable = Result
Write '"Hello 'Variable', How are you today?"'

Result: Hello Nick Loman, How are you today?
@rem </pre>

@{b}Asynchronous Arexx Commands@{ub}

An asynchronous Zeus Arexx command may be run from ARexx scripts executed by the Rx function, where the input and output are redirected to the CLI, rather than to the user on the Bulletin Board.

Not all Zeus ARexx commands are asynchronous.

In order to gain access to asynchronous commands, you must specifically address the Zeus ARexx port. This is acheived with the following line which must appear near the top of your ARexx script.

@rem <pre>
Address 'ZEUS'
@rem </pre>

@{b}Avoiding Variable Collisions@{ub}

The best way to avoid variable collisions is to not create variable that will be the same as arguments to functions. Using the Zeus Arexx function GetUserData as above, you will see that it accepts the keyword NAME.

Examples:

@rem <pre>
Name="Nick Loman"

GetUserData NAME         /* GetUserData NICK LOMAN */

GetUserData 'NAME'       /* GetUserData NAME       */
@rem </pre>

The second example is the best method to use since 'NAME' will always be constant. If you had nothing assigned to the variable NAME, then the first example would work just as well as the second. You will have problems however, if you are using NAME as a variable.

example:

@rem <pre>
Name = 'HELLO'

GetUserData NAME
@rem </pre>

If you do this, then GetUserData will not work properly since what you are

truly asking the function for is:

@rem <pre>
GetUserData HELLO
@rem </pre>

And to avoid a variable collision you should use the following instead:

@rem <pre>
Name = 'HELLO'

GetUserData 'NAME'
@rem </pre>

In this instance, you are still asking GetUserData to use NAME rather than what the variable NAME contained. This will keep you from having problems along the way, making it easier to debug your software.

@{b}DO, WHILE, UNTIL and ELSE Loops@{ub}

Loops are a very important element when writing your programmes. The loops will help you control the flow of your script without making jumps to subroutines within the programme. The combination of IF, DO, ELSE and END will allow you to perform most of the essential tasks on your Bulletin Board System.

@rem <pre>
/* Display the prompt               */

Write '"Please Enter the letter A: "'

/* Get a single letter in uppercase */

Read MAKEUPPER HOT

/* Store it as variable 'Letter'    */

Letter = Result

/* Check if the letter A was entered*/

If Letter = 'A' then do
 Write '"\nCongratulations you entered the letter A!"'

End

Else Do

 /* Do this if it was something else */
 Write '"\nThat's not the letter A!"'

End

Write '"\n\n"'

WaitReturn
@rem </pre>

REMEMBER:

Every loop, no matter what kind, requires an END statment to tell Arexx when your loop has been completed. If you do not place this statement at the end of each loop you will get an error returned in the Zeus ErrorLog. For every DO branch you use there must be a corresponding END statement.

The following error is commonly reported:

@rem <pre>
+++ Error 26 Missing or unexpected END
@rem </pre>

The same problem will occur if you place too many END statements as well where they are not required or expected.

@{i}WHILE Loops@{ui}

A WHILE loop remains in operation until a condition is false. This change can be a number of things such as a change in a string or numeric value.

@rem <pre>
Var = 0

Do while var < 5  /* Do this loop while 'var' is less than 5 */

 Var = var+1

End
@rem </pre>

In this example, the variable 'var' will increase by 1 for each time the loop is executed. Eventually 'var' is no longer less than 5, and the loop exits and continues executing the commands after the 'End' statement.

@{i}UNTIL Loops@{ui}

UNTIL loops are similiar to WHILE loops, except that the loop will remain in
operation until a condition is true.

@rem <pre>
Var = 0

Do until var > 5
 say Var
 Var = var+1
End
@rem </pre>

As you can see, the variable 'var' is being increased again, and the loop cycles each time and will exit once 'var' has become greater than 5.

@{b}Getting Better@{ub}

There is no real way around it, getting better at Arexx requires time and effort on your part, as does learning any language. Jumping in at the deep end, experimenting with commands and reading the source of other Arexx programmes are the best ways to achieve a better understanding of the language. If you do not know how to program in any language Arexx is a great place to start since it can prepare you for other high-level languages such as C. The combination of Arexx and Zeus should provide you with all the flexibility you require for your Bulletin Board System.

Where to Obtain More Information

There are several disk based Arexx tutorials and documentation available to you on AmiNet. Books are also available.

@{i}AmiNet@{ui}

ARexxGuide20rq.lha   util/rexx  343K+        ARexx ref & tutorial. ReqTools ver.

ARexxGuide2_0A.lha   util/rexx  343K+        Complete ARexx reference. AmigaGuide.

@{i}Books@{ui}

"ARexx User's Reference Manual, The REXX Language for the Amiga" written by William S. Hawes, from Wishful Thinking Development, 1987.

"Using ARexx on the Amiga" written by by Chris Zamara & Nick Sullivan, from Abacus, 1992.


@endnode


@node "Manual.Support" "Support"

Appendix A

Software Support


Technical support and help for your Zeus Bulletin Board System can be obtained in a variety of different ways. Support is available from your localdistribution site and from the authors direct. A FidoNet mail network feed for the Zeus echoes can be obtained from your local distribution site. If this proves to be too costly, or inconvenient, feeds can supplied via FidoNet to Internet email tunnelling, or via Internet email mailing lists.

The public FidoNet echoes supported currently are:

@rem <PRE>
 TagName     | Description
 ------------+----------------------------------------------
 ZEUS_BETA   | Bug reports relating to Zeus
 ZEUS_SYSOP  | General Zeus-related chat
 ZEUS_UTIL   | Door/Utility programming for Zeus
 ZEUS_SCRIPT | ARexx script help and discussion
 ZEUS_USER   | Open for users of Zeus BBSs to chat
@rem </PRE>

To subscribe to the Internet mailing lists, please visit the Zeus Developments website.  In the Support section you will find details for subscribing.

When contacting us, please provide your Zeus serial number as obtained from the "About" option on the main Zeus control screen.


Support Sites


An up to date list of support sites is always available from the Zeus Developments BBS in the U.K, and from the Internet WWW page:

 http://www.bleach.demon.co.uk/zeus/

@endnode


@node "Manual.HowDoI" "How do I..."

@rem <PRE>
 @{" Log-on to the local line                   " Link "Logon"}
 @{" Upgrade my access level?                   " Link "AccLevel"}
 @{" Make my BBS available to remote callers    " Link "Callers"}
 @{" Shut down Zeus                             " Link "Shutdown"}
 @{" Tell what all these funky icons do?        " Link "Icons"}
 @{" See what users are doing on the BBS        " Link "Watch"}
 @{" Edit the menu bars of programs?            " Link "MenuBars"}
 @{" Enable RIP Graphics                        " Link "RIP"}

 @{" Macro Keys available on line watchers      " Link "Macros"}
@rem </PRE>

@endnode

@Node "Icons" "What are all these icons for?"

@{b}@{i}Main Icons:@{ub}@{ui}

 @{b}Two men talking/Ignoring each other:@{ub}

   This icon allows you to toggle whether you are available for paging.
When the men are ignoring each other it means you are not available. This
icon is created by a program called @{b}Utils/ChatStatus@{ub} and the image is
taken from the file @{b}Zeus:Config/Icons/ChatStatus.info@{ub}, which is a standard
icon file.

 @{b} ZEUS icon with a line number underneath:@{ub}

    These icon(s) indicate that an ANSI watcher is loaded/iconified.
Clicking on one will pop up the watcher for the applicable line. If it
is a local line then pressing @{b}Return@{ub} will log you into the BBS. A watcher 
allows you to see what the remote user is doing, chat with them or
navigate them round your BBS.

 @{b} FED (Filing cabinet and scissors)@{ub}

     This icon is created by @{b}Bin/ZeusDock@{ub}, Zeus' internal Dock program
which is configured with the @{b}Prefs/DockCfg@{ub} program. Pressing this icon
will execute @{b}Utils/FileEditor.@{ub}

 @{b} UED (Surgeon with patient)@{ub}

     This icon is also created by @{b}Bin/ZeusDock@{ub} Pressing this icon will
execute @{b}Utils/UserEditor.@{ub}

 @{b} US Mailbox @{ub}

      This icon is created with the @{b}Bin/PostMan@{ub} program. The icon
images are taken from @{b}Zeus:Config/Icons/(No)Mail.info@{ub}. This program
monitors the SysOp's mailbox (the SysOp name is taken from the IEMSI
Information settings as defined in @{b}Prefs/System@{ub} and changes its
image when mail is written or imported for the SysOp.

 @{b} Help button @{ub}

       Another ZeusDock icon. Loads this help file using @{i}Multiview@{ui} on
the @{b}ZEUS@{ub} screen. Configure the viewer by loading up @{b}Prefs/DockCfg@{ub},
selecting "Dock/Help" and changing the "Execute" string gadget.

@{b}@{i}Voyeur Icons:@{ub}@{ui}

 @{b}Jack in the Box@{ub}

       "Pops" up the selected line. This will uniconify the watcher
selected, or launch a new one by calling the "Zeus:Rexx/PopUpWatcher"
script.

 @{b}Boot@{ub}

       Boots the user on the selected line off the BBS. This will
terminate their call!

 @{b}Puzzled Man@{ub}

       Shows pertinent information about the user currently selected.

 @{b}Surgeon and Patient@{ub}

       Loads up "Utils/UserEditor" with the current user already
selected.

 @{b}Broadcast Mast@{ub}

       Sends a "node message" to the user currently onlien.

 @{b}Iconify@{ub}

       Iconifies "Utils/Voyeur" into a small icon on the control screen.
This icon is configurable from the file "Zeus:Config/Icons/Voyeur.info"

@endnode

@Node "Macros" "Macro Keys available on line watchers"

   F1 -- Start/End Chat
   F2 -- View details of the user online
   F7 -- Edit personal details of the user online
   F8 -- Edit account details of the user online
   F9 -- Edit message details of the user online
   F0 -- Edit file details of the user online

 S-F1 -- Log actions of user in LOGS:Logger.<Line>
 S-F0 -- Kick current user

@endnode

@Node "AccLevel" "How do I upgrade my access level?"

New user's on Zeus have an access level of 0 (New User). In the Zeus
demonstration, two access levels are defined (New User and SysOp). You
can add new access levels using the @{b}Prefs/Templates@{ub} program.

If you wish to upgrade your access:

 1) @{"Logon" Link "LogOn"} to a BBS.
 2) Press F8 (see @{"Macros" Link "Macros"})
 3) Press the @{b}Sel@{ub} button next to "Access Level"
 4) Double click on "255 - SysOp", select @{b}Yes@{ub} to the prompt.
 5) Close the Window
 6) Press @{b}Save User@{ub}
 7) You will be updated automatically and have SysOp privelidges.

@endnode

@Node "Callers" "Activating a remote line"

Zeus is not set up to receive calls by default. Callers may be accepted
using one of the following Zeus programs.

 - Connector     -- A simple phone answerer.

   To install "The Connector" on Line 1 of your Zeus BBS, load up
   "Prefs/Progs". This preferences program is a list of the programs
   that Zeus loads after the main executable has set up.

   1) Press "Add"
   2) Delete "(new)" from the string gadget and add the following line:
      "Zeus:Utils/Connector LINE 1", minus the double-quotes.
   3) Press "Save"
   4) Press "Quit"

   @{"Shutdown" Link "Shutdown"} Zeus and reload it.


 - ZMailer       -- Zeus' own FidoNet Mailer.

   The commercial version of Zeus comes with it's own fully-featured
   FidoNet mailer. This can be used to launch the BBS, but is not
   supplied with this demo.


 - NetStart      -- Starts Zeus from an AMITCP/IP telnet session.

   This program makes setting Zeus up for Internet telnet access easy,
   meaning Internet users can access your BBS from anywhere in the
   world at local phone rates! NetStart is not included with the demo
   version of Zeus.


 - MailerStart   -- Start the BBS from a mailer such as Trapdoor.

   Zeus supports the use of most Amiga front-door mailers to start
   the BBS. 
   
   TrapDoor

   The following should be added to your MAIL:TrapDoor.cfg

@rem <PRE>
   --- cut ---
   BBSCOMMAND "ZEUS:Bin/System/MailerStart 1 %b %B"
   BBSINOUT ""
   BBSMODE SPAWN
   --- cut ---
@rem </PRE>

   GMS

   Add the following to GMS:Config/Mailer.1/MailerSettings

@rem <PRE>
   --- cut ---
   BBSMode=Spawn
   BBSCommand="ZEUS:Bin/System/MailerStart 1 %b %B"
   BBSCommandStack=50000
   --- cut ---
@rem </PRE>

   JamMail

   Configure JamMail for a standard bbs, and use this BBS launch command:

@rem <PRE>
   --- cut ---
   1. Command: zeus
   2. TextFile:""
   3. Execute: ZEUS:Bin/System/MailerStart $(line) $(baudlocked) $(baud)
   4. PostBBS:
   5. Check Error: Enabled
   --- cut ---
@rem </PRE>

@endnode

@Node "Shutdown" "Shut down Zeus"

Zeus is loaded as a commodity and can be shut down in a number of
different ways.


@{b} 1) @{ub} Use the hotkey shortcut @{b}CTRL-ESC@{ub}.
@{b} 2) @{ub} Load up @{b}SYS:Tools/Commodities/Exchange@{ub}, select @{i}Zeus BBS@{ui} from the listview and press the @{b}Remove@{ub} button.
@{b} 3) @{ub} Send a @{i}QuitZeus@{ui} command to the ARexx port @{b}ZEUS@{ub}. This can be acheived with the following script:

@rem <PRE>
      ---------------cut----------------
      /*
      ** Close Down Zeus
      */

      Options Results

      Address 'ZEUS'

      QuitZeus
      ---------------cut----------------
@rem </PRE>

@{b} 4) @{ub} Double click on the "@{b}Zeus:Shortcuts/BBS/ShutdownZeus@{ub}" icon.

@endnode

@Node "Logon" "Logon to the local line"

Upon loading Zeus, the Watcher is automatically loaded. This starts up in iconified mode. To deiconify the watcher, click on the icon marked "Line 0" on the Control Screen.

This will bring up the watcher interface. Various aspects of the watcher configuration can be changed from this public screen. Simply hit @{b}Return@{ub} to logon to the local line.

If you quit the watcher, it can be reactivated by selecting "ANSI 0" from the Progs menu on the Control Screen, or by running "Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI <Line>" from a CLI, where Line is the line you wish to watch.

@endnode

@Node "MenuBars" "Configuration of MenuBars"

The menubars of many programs in Zeus may be configured. This is done through the Prefs/MenuEditor utility. This editor allows you to edit the Menu titles, items and sub-items of individual programs and assign executable programs to them.

For instance, to add an option to "Boot Users off" from the Watcher screen, follow these steps:

 1) Load up Prefs/MenuEditor
 2) Press Amiga-O (Open) and load up the file:

        Zeus:Config/Watchers/Menus.Dat

 2) Press the "Add" button in the "Menus" section.
 3) Replace "(New)" with "User" (the name of the menu we are creating).
 4) Select "User" from the listview.
 5) Press the "Add" button in the "Items" section.
 6) Replace "(New)" with "Boot User" (the description of the menu item).
 7) Place the following data in the gadgets:

         CommKey: B
      Executable: Zeus:Bin/BootUser %n
            Type: Executable
           Stack: 4096

    Note that the "%n" item in Executable will be expanded to the current line number.

 8) Close the window and choose Save.
 9) Select "Reload Menus" from the "Project" menu of any watcher.
10) Et voila! We have a new menu options.

Other programs that allow configurable menu bars are:

@rem <PRE>
 Program      File
------------+------------------------------------------
            | 
 FileEditor | Zeus:Config/File/FileEditorMenus.Dat
 UserEditor | Zeus:Config/Zeus/UserEditorMenus.Dat
 Control    | Zeus:Config/Control/Menus.Dat
 Mailer     | Zeus:Config/Msg/MailerMenu.Dat
 Watchers   | Zeus:Config/Watchers/Menus.Dat
            |
------------+------------------------------------------
@rem </PRE>

@endnode

@Node "Watch" "How do I watch the users"

 @{b}To find out who is online and what they are doing:@{ub}

  Run "Utils/Voyeur" - this gives you a realtime view of what the current
user is doing online.

 @{b}To watch and interact with a remote user:@{ub}

 If the "Line 1" icon is present on the Control Screen, press this.
Otherwise run "Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI 1" to bring up the watcher screen,
alternatively in Voyeur, select the remote line and press the "PopUp"
icon.

 @{b}Chat with an online user:@{ub}

 Press F1 on the remote watcher screen.

@endnode

@Node "RIP" "Enabling Remote Imaging Protocol"

To enable RIP graphics you must load the RIP server. This works in conjunction with the ANSI watcher (Zeus:Bin/Watchers/ANSI) to provide 16-colour EGA graphics over a terminal.

To load RIP you should select "RIP Server 0" from the Progs menu on the Control screen. Then you should logon to the BBS and select "RIP graphics on" from the "edit" menu of any BBS.

The RIP public screen is called RIP.<Line>, where <Line> is the BBS line number.

@endnode


