@node ov.Mail "Mail Directory"

 @{b}Mail Directory@{ub}

This is the default directory set by Zeus for storing the message bases.

If you run a BBS without any FidoNet networks or Internet, you can probably leave this as the mail directory. However, if you intend to have a large amount of mail moving through your BBS, it is a good idea to put the mail directory on a different partition to that which the Zeus program is stored.

@endnode


@node ov.Prefs "Prefs Directory"

 @{b}Prefs Directory@{ub}

This is where the @{i}programs@{ui} for changing Zeus preferences are stored. They can be accessed via Workbench or the shell.

Most aspects of Zeus are set via these programs.  ZMP is one of the very few which require configuring via a text file.  However, even when a program is required to alter the configuration it is possible to generate a text configuration which can be recompiled by using programs in the Rexx directory.

@endnode


@node ov.Rexx "Rexx Directory"

 @{b}Rexx Directory@{ub}

This contains many ARexx programs which complement Zeus BBS.

These programs are not required to run Zeus, the purpose of them is to make running Zeus easier.  Some of the programs included are:

 . ZAmiNet - A program to facilitate turning your BBS (or a section or SIG of it) into an AmiNet mirror.
 . Config
 . FileAreas
 . MessageAreas - These are some programs to allow you to configure parts of Zeus with the Prefs/ directory programs, and without using ARexx.  Studying these programs might give you an insite into ARexx which could help you develop powerful, automated configuration scripts!

@endnode


@node ov.Scripts "Scripts Directory"

 @{b}Scripts Directory@{ub}

The "power" behind your BBS.

These determine what the user will see, what they can do, and their whole online experience...  There is far too much to go into here, but the Zeus manual contains a whole chapter on it.

@endnode


@node ov.Shortcuts "Shortcuts Directory"

 @{b}Shortcuts Directory@{ub}

Short scripts to help you run the BBS from Workbench.

The scripts in here invoke Zeus shell programs, in order to perform some simple but necessary functions, such as trimming the message bases.

@endnode


